s and technologies bring in more challenges for researchers, which need to be standardized for more interop- erability. The new technologies need to be well-studied and understood before they are accepted and widely used by consumers. This section gives academics, tech- nologists, and industrial audiences up-to-date standards, technical challenges, and recent advances in the emerging wireless technologies.  In the last ten years, there has been a tremendous increase in wireless internet usage, which is largely due to pervasive devices such as smart phones. This has led to a fast pace of research and development in the wireless area with the promise of signiﬁcant new breakthroughs over the next decade and beyond. In 2001, the groundwork has been laid for fourth generation  4G  technology, which is now al- ready in use. This move to 4G  which is also known as Long Term Evolution, LTE  enabled a wide range of new anytime anywhere computing and multimedia appli- cations ranging from navigation and search for mobile video streaming.  LTE enables rich multimedia content to mobile devices. The LTE technology in- cludes a new air interface and simpliﬁed network architecture. It offers signiﬁcantly higher data rates for users, while reducing the cost-per-bit for service providers. It is anticipated that LTE could bring connection speeds of up to 50 times faster than 3G networks and could offer 3D visuals for the ﬁrst time [1]. The network architec- ture is based on a distributed uniﬁed IP network that improves both throughput and latency.  It is a well known fact that wireless networks are inherently more vulnerable than their wired counterparts. Due to mobility, dynamic topology, and ad hoc na- ture, wireless security has become more challenging compared to wired networks. Even though many valuable lessons were learned from wired security issues, these  N. Chilamkurti  B   La Trobe University, Melbourne, Australia e-mail: n.chilamkurti@latrobe.edu.au  N. Chilamkurti et al. 