ed served as an overlay on the top of the transport layers of the underlying networks. The concepts of regions and gateways from IPN were ex- tended for the DTN as well. The DTN architecture identiﬁed two different types of node—with and without persistent storage. In addition, the author also discussed about different services available in, and issues related to, such networks.  Over the years, researchers have explored the idea of DTNs to give rise to multi- ple specialized sub-domains. Khabbaz et al. [9], however, observed that while DTN was originally meant as an “overlay” architecture [6], in many cases in the existing literature the term DTN has been used to refer to the individual challenged networks as well. The authors differentiate the two categories as “delay-tolerant networking” and “intermittently connected networks”. Two prominent subclasses of such chal- lenged networks are the Opportunistic Mobile Networks  OMNs  [10] and Pocket Switched Networks  PSNs  [11]. An OMN essentially captures the idea that, un- like the traditional networks, communication links do not always exist in such a network. Rather, mobility of the nodes provides them with opportunities to commu- nicate with the other nodes in the network. On a similar note, the concept of PSNs   3 Cooperation in Delay Tolerant Networks  17  was proposed. A PSN is formed by portable devices such as smart phones and PDAs, carried by human beings. The devices in the PSNs communicate among themselves using global connectivities, if available. In absence of that, the devices communi- cate opportunistically when they are in the transmission range of one another. Thus, the PSNs provide an interesting communication paradigm in environments lacking network infrastructure, for example, post-disaster rescue operations [12].  We note that the abbreviation “DTN” has been used in the literature to denote both the delay-tolerant networking architecture and the challenged networks, where one or more assumptions of the Internet fail. In this work, by “DTNs” we refer to such challenged networks that exhibit the characteristics enumerated at the begin- ning of this section.  3.1.2 Characteristics and Challenges  The inherent characteristics of the DTNs ensure that the protocols from the Internet, wireless networks or MANETs fail to work with such networks. This implies that the network dynamics, for example, routing and security, should be addressed from a different point of view. To illustrate, consider a popular routing protocol for the MANETs, Dynamic Source Routing  DSR  [13]. One of the fundamental assump- tions of the protocol is the availability of at least one end-to-end communication path between any source and destination node pairs. In [14], multiple such paths are considered as backups, in case the primary path fails. Unfortunately, such possibil- ities are rare in DTNs. Therefore, the nodes in DTNs need to store the messages in their buffers  for a considerable time  until a communication link is available. Fur- ther, in such challenged networks, it is desired that the nodes engage in cooperative communications so that the resources, and opportunities, are efﬁciently utilized, and the network performance is optimum.  3.1.3 Contributions  In this chapter, we identify the different aspects on which nodes in DTNs could co- operate, and review the different schemes proposed for the same. Speciﬁcally, we explore in detail the incentive-based and game theory-inspired mechanisms adopted for enforcing cooperation in DTNs. The scope of this work, however, excludes ve- hicular DTNs. To the best of our knowledge, no survey on cooperation in DTNs has been done so far.  3.1.4 Organization  The remainder of this chapter is organized as follows. Section 3.2 provides a brief overview on a few representative unicast routing protocols for DTNs. Section 3.3   18  S. Misra et al.  deals in depth with the cooperation issues and challenges in DTNs. In Sect. 3.4, we review the different credit- and reputation-based incentive schemes proposed for en- forcing cooperation in DTNs. Section 3.5 provides a brief overview of game theory, and discuss multiple game theoretic approaches proposed for achieving cooperative behavior among the nodes in DTNs. Apart from incentive- and game theory-based mechanisms, several other schemes for cooperative communications are reviewed in Sect. 3.6. A few open problems in the related domain are pointed out in Sect. 3.7. Finally, in Sect. 3.8, we summarize and conclude this chapter.  3.2 A Brief Overview of Routing Protocols in DTNs  Routing is one of the fundamental activities performed by the nodes in any network. With reference to the OSI model, routing is the decision made at the network layer of any node with regards to the next recipient of a packet. In OMNs, routing by a node is essentially sending a message to another node when the latter comes within the transmission range of the former. To cope with the different challenges, as men- tioned above, routing in DTNs usually involves replication of the messages, i.e., a copy of a message is sent to the node in contact. However, when a node comes in contact with the destination node of a given message, the message is then forwarded. When a node receives multiple copies of a given message, it discards all copies but the ﬁrst. Formally, consider a network with a set of nodes, N, and a set of messages generated in the network, M. The action, Action i, j, m , taken by any node, i ∈ N, having a message, m ∈ M, while in contact with another node, j ∈ N, i  cid:3 = j , could be Forward m, j  , Replicate m, j   or ∅. Here, ∅ indicates that no action was taken. We now brieﬂy look at three representative replication-based routing protocols proposed for DTNs, namely epidemic [15], Spray-and-Wait  SnW  [16] and Proba- bilistic Routing Using History of Encounters and Transitivity  PROPHET  [17]. The epidemic routing protocol presents an extreme case, where uncontrolled ﬂooding o