iveries and high delivery latency, since a source–destination node pair has limited contact opportunities. To overcome these limitations, nodes in DTNs rely on the intermediate nodes, met along the way, for forwarding the messages. In this situation, if the meeting intermediate nodes do not cooperate in the communications process, it will directly affect the network performance. So, the intermediate relay nodes play a key role of cooperation in DTNs and cooperation is one of the major issues in DTNs.  Multiple routing protocols proposed for the DTNs assume that nodes are fully co- operative. However, such situations may not be true in real-life. The non-cooperative behavior exhibited by the nodes could be broadly classiﬁed into two types—selﬁsh and malicious. Selﬁsh nodes attempt to preserve their own resources  for example, energy and buffer space —in other words, look for their own gain. Thus, selﬁsh nodes do not forward messages received from the other nodes, but use other nodes as free riders for serving their own purposes. Malicious nodes, on the other hand, intentionally drop the messages forwarded to them by the other nodes. Unlike self- ish nodes, the primary motive of the malicious nodes is to cause harm to others rather than making self proﬁts. Figure 3.1 illustrates the different communication scenarios in the presence of cooperative, selﬁsh, and malicious nodes.  3.3.1 Challenges  It may be noted that “cooperation in a network” could indicate numerous higher level phenomena. In practice, one must deﬁne the network dimensions where coop-   3 Cooperation in Delay Tolerant Networks  21  eration plays role. Cooperation among the nodes in a network could be with regards to various aspects, including, but not limited to:   Buffer space: A node in a DTN, which forwards it own messages to other nodes, must also accept and store the other nodes’ messages into its buffer. The bundle protocol [18] provides the facility of custody transfer—a reliable mechanism for transferring bundles. In custody transfer, a DTN node accepting a bundle  the custodian  from another node cannot drop the bundle either until it has been for- warded to some node, or its TTL is expired.   Communication opportunities: A node in a DTN not only carries message s  from other nodes, but also forwards them without discrimination when suitable contact opportunities are available. This is important, since, as discussed earlier, lack of connectivity among the nodes in a DTN is the norm rather than exception. Of course, a node forwards messages created by itself with higher priority.   Energy aspects: A node with critical energy considerations may utilize the current communication opportunity with another node to seek cooperation in forwarding the messages. Differently, a node may increase its transmission power to reach the distant nodes [19].  The unique characteristics of DTNs make cooperation enforcement  or, punish- ment  a difﬁcult task. Sparse connectivities among the nodes in DTNs poses a great challenge by delaying the detection of the non-cooperative behavior of the node s , if at all. This is critical, since the damage might have been done before the malicious behavior of the nodes is detected and avoided.  3.3.2 Approaches  A brief walk-through of the existing literature reveals that diverse approaches have been taken towards ensuring cooperation in DTNs. This chapter explores the differ- ent cooperation-enforcing schemes proposed in the literature for DTNs. Among the multitude of schemes, one of the well known is the incentive-based approach [20– 23], to bring about cooperation among the nodes. The problem—whether a node should cooperate or not in the presence of other non-cooperative nodes—has been explored from the game theoretic perspective as well. Several works presented op- timum strategies that the nodes should undertake in order to maximize the network performance metrics.  3.4 Cooperation Based on Incentive Schemes  Many routing protocols for DTNs, for example, [15–17], are based on the assump- tion that the intermediate nodes in the network are ready to forward messages re- ceived from the other nodes. However, when the owners of the nodes are people or   22  S. Misra et al.  parties, the nodes might behave as selﬁshly or maliciously. The presence of these types of misbehaving node forcefully degrades the performance of the networks. So, to overcome the effects of non-cooperative behavior, many incentive-based schemes have been proposed for the DTNs, which indirectly enforce cooperation among the nodes. An incentive-based scheme provides some credit  reputation  to the nodes to motivate them to cooperate and refrain from selﬁsh malicious behavior. The nodes can “encash” the incentive received to get their own messages forwarded. Here, we have categorized two types of incentives scheme:  a  credit-based, and  b  reputation-based. In credit-based incentive schemes, virtual currency or pricing acts as the credit. In reputation-based schemes, reputation of the nodes is calculated by their neighbors based on the message forwarding actions. Thus, if node X ﬁnds that the reputation of node Y is less than some chosen threshold, X would refuse to accept messages from Y .  3.4.1 Credit-Based Incentive Schemes  To encourage message forwarding among the nodes, credit is given to each of the forwarding nodes in the form of virtual currency. The nodes receive payments when they help in forwarding the messages from the other nodes. The nodes can use these credits to transmit their own messages. Thus, if node A knows  for example, through acknowledgments  that node B has forwarded some message s , it provides appro- priate credits to node B. Node B, in turn, uses its accumulated currency to ask the other nodes to forward its messages.  Shevade et al. [21] proposed a pair-wise Tit-for-Tat  TFT  incentive mechanism for DTNs. The authors described two constraints, generosity and contrition, to max- imize the cooperation among the nodes. The basic TFT scheme prevents relaying the messages when two nodes meet for the ﬁrst time, as no message is relayed by the other node. To overcome this drawback, the generous TFT was proposed. In a generous TFT, a node must relay at least ε number of messages. Generous TFT helps to overcome asymmetric trafﬁc demands. So, it is possible that a node may act selﬁshly after it has achieved this criterion. To prevent this selﬁsh behavior, another constraint, contrition, is considered. Contrition stops for doing selﬁshness by getting a valid counterattack to its own mistakes. Contrition prevents endless retaliation.  Zhu et al. [20] proposed a Secure Credit-based Incentive scheme  SCI , a frame- work for enforcing cooperation among the selﬁsh nodes in DTNs. In addition to cooperation, SCI also adds a security mechanism for layered coin, a virtual elec- tronic credit system where credits are distributed by the intermediate nodes without the involvement of senders. A layered coin consists of a base layer originated at the source node, and multiple endorsed layers generated by the intermediate nodes. The base layer expresses different rewarding policies such as payment rate, remuneration conditions, and class of service requirement. When any intermediate node receives a layered coin, it veriﬁes the bundle life time, likability of layers chain, sender’s cer- tiﬁcate, supporting signatures of the base layer, and intermediate nodes certiﬁcates.   3 Cooperation in Delay Tolerant Networks  23  After performing these veriﬁcations, the intermediate node determines the next-hop forwarding node and creates an additional endorsed layer. The endorsed layers ap- pends a unforgeable digital signature based on previous layers. The authors intro- duced a concatenated layer technique, which prevents malicious users for cheating credits and concatenates different layers with each other by injecting the generator information of the next layer into the previous layer. The authors further proposed two performance optimization techniques to minimize the transmission overhead.  In [22], the authors proposed SMART, a Secure Multilayer Credit-based Incen- tive scheme for DTNs. SMART not only stimulates cooperation among the nodes, but also prevents the malicious users from cheating credits by a secure incentive scheme, which is based on layered coins. The propagation path can be easily tracked by checking the digital signature of an endorsed layer. The digital signature provides the security and the propagation path of the end-to-end connection from source to destination. Each intermediate nodes periodically submits the layered coin to a Vir- tual Bank  VB , which takes charge of credit clearance. The last intermediate node submits the collected layered coins to VB for clearance. The VB checks the de- posited layered coins and shares the credits with each of the forwarding nodes ac- cording to predeﬁned reward policy.  MobiCent [23] is a credit-based incentive scheme, suitable for mobile social net- works [11], where people carry low power mobile devices. MobiCent is compatible with replication-based routing protocol in DTNs. In this scheme, the selﬁsh nodes in DTNs are not detected. Rather, the nodes are motivated for cooperation by pro- viding them incentives for the message relays. A mobile device operates in two modes:  a  long-range low-bandwidth radio, and  b  short-range high-bandwidth link. The ﬁrst mode ensures that a mobile device can maintain connectivity with dis- tant devices, while, in the second mode, devices can exchange huge amount of data opportunistically with their closely located peers. Due to these two types of opera- tion, a mobile device in this environment can face the challenges in forwarding the data in unpredictable, opportunistic networks, where disconnections among nodes are the general norms. The authors described two types of attack—edge insertion and hiding. These two attacks are addressed by an incentive compatible payment scheme. Edge insertion attacks are launched by the selﬁsh nodes by inserting a sybil in the earliest path. Adding a sybil on a later path does not change the eligible path set. In edge hiding attacks, the selﬁsh nodes hide the path, and they can hold the message instead of forwarding it to other nodes. To counter edge insertion attacks, the Multiplicative Decreasing Reward  MDR  algorithm is used, which prevents the relay and clients from gaining in edge insertion attack. To prevent edge hiding attacks, minimum cost and minimum delay selection algorithms are used to deter- mine an incentive-compatible relay set by examining a sufﬁcient subset of paths ever revealed before the deadline. These two algorithms prevent the selﬁsh nodes from launching edge insertion and hiding attacks, and, thereby, ensure cooperation among the nodes.  Lu et al. [24] proposed a practical incentive  Pi  protocol, where the selﬁsh nodes are stimulated to cooperate by forwarding the bundles. Pi utilizes both credit-based and reputation-based incentive schemes, and considers the single-copy data for- warding algorithms. Each source node sends the bundle by attaching some incentive   24  S. Misra et al.  with the bundle. This incentive scheme is fair to the source node. An intermediate node may or may not participate in the bundle forwarding. If the intermediate nodes forward bundles, which ﬁnally reach the destination node, then all the intermedi- ates nodes get credits, which leads to increased reputation from the source node. However, if any forwarded bundle fails to reach the destination, then each of the intermediate nodes are assigned higher reputation values from a trusted authority. In this case, the source node is not required to provide any credit to the intermedi- ate forwarding nodes. Thus, each intermediate node in the network is stimulated for cooperation. The Pi protocol also guarantees a secure incentive schemes by using a layered coin model and veriﬁable encrypted signature techniques. The Pi protocol provides fair incentives, and prevents free riding attacks i.e., the layer removal and addition attacks.  SATS [25] is a Secure dATa-forwarding Scheme proposed for the DTNs. This scheme prevents black hole and selﬁshness attacks. Black hole attackers silently drop others’ messages. SATS uses credit or micropayment, which encourages the selﬁsh nodes to cooperate in data forwarding. SATS also uses a trust system for assigning a trust value to a node, when the nodes cooperate in forwarding. The trust value of a node degrades, if a node does not cooperate in forwarding.  Discussions: The following observations could be made from the above reviewed credit-based incentive schemes for cooperation:   Shevade et al.’s scheme does not address any security issues for DTNs, whereas SMART and SCI provide security to prevent cheating credits. Similarly, Mobi- Cent prevents edge insertion and edge hiding attacks.   SMART is based on individual selﬁshness. If a node has limited storage and power, it would not be able to participate in message forwarding, which is not intentional non-cooperation.   MobiCent is based on social selﬁshness, where a node is willing to forward the messages belonging to the same community, while it does not forward the mes- sages of the other communities. Li et al. [26] considered these two types of selﬁsh behavior and evaluated the impact of social selﬁshness in DTNs.   Different from the other protocols, Pi focuses on the fairness towards the source nodes, and uses a hybrid  credit- and reputation-based  incentive model, which encourages the selﬁsh node to take part in forwarding the bundle. The Pi protocol allows preventing the layer adding attack for a DTN node with multiple identities. However, it is still a challenging problem when more than one of the DTN nodes collude and launch a layer adding attack.   SMART [22], MobiCent [23], pair wise Tit-for-Tat [21] are designed for mul- ticopy routing protocol such as epidemic routing, whereas Pi with single copy routing protocols.  Furthermore, a fair incentive protocol for multicopy routing algorithms has yet  not been developed. So, Pi could be extended to address such algorithms.   3 Cooperation in Delay Tolerant Networks  25  3.4.2 Reputation-Based Incentive Schemes  In the reputation-based incentive schemes, each node is evaluated by the neighbor- ing nodes and assigned a reputation value based on their cooperating behavior with the other nodes. If a node cooperates, its reputation value is high and the node re- ceives better services. The reputation value of a node is reduced when it does not cooperate with the other nodes in forwarding the other nodes messages. Therefore, to avoid low reputation values, all the nodes try to cooperate with other nodes by forwarding their messages.  Wei et al. [27] proposed MobiID, a user-centric and social-aware incentive scheme based on reputation, to mitigate the effects of dishonest nodes in the net- work. The scheme used reputation self-check and community-check. The nodes in the same community meet frequently and periodically forward bundles among each other. When any node assigns a low reputation value to any other node, the latter is blacklisted, and the former informs its community members about the same. The network is modeled as a weighted directed graph, where the link weights are deter- mined based on the forwarding histories of the nodes. The authors deﬁned Average Forwarding Time  AFT , a metric to capture the effects of both contact durations and messages forwarded among any pair of nodes. Using this, a new metric willing- ness, wij ∈ [0, 1], was deﬁned as [27]   cid:7  wij = exp   cid:8   − AFT2 ij 2σ 2   3.5   The willingness, wij , indicates the extent to which a node i wills to forward the  bundles to node j , ∀i, j . The term σ denotes a scaling factor.  To deal with reputation management, reputation tickets are used. A reputation ticket is a signed evidence of 