 based on game theory.   3 Cooperation in Delay Tolerant Networks  27  Table 3.1 Payoff matrix for two player strategic game  Fig. 3.2 Extensive form game tree  Player 2  Left  Right  Player 1  Top Bottom   a1, a2    b1, b2    c1, c2    d1, d2   3.5.1 Brief Overview of Game Theory  Game theory is the study of mathematical techniques, where the actions taken by each rational user affects the outcome of the group. A group of individuals make decisions that beneﬁt each player by optimizing their payoffs. A game is com- posed of a set of players, a set of rules strategies for specifying the individual actions decisions, the outcomes for each such decision taken, and the payoff ma- trix that deﬁnes the players’ utility functions. There exist different forms of games, including strategic  normal  form, extensive form—with or without perfect informa- tion, and coalitional  characteristic  forms. The extensive form and strategic games are classiﬁed under the non-cooperative games, while coalitional games belong to the cooperative games category. We brieﬂy discuss the different types of game in the following.   1  Strategic Form Games In strategic form games, all players acts without knowing the strategies of the other players. It suppresses the sequential structure of decision making. This game is also known as normal form games or matrix games. A strategic form game can be represented as G =  N,{Si}i∈N ,{pi}i∈N  , where N is the set of players, Si is the set of actions for player i, and pi : S → R is the pay- off function of player i. Table 3.1 shows the payoff matrix for two players strategic game, where each player has two actions. If Player 1 plays Bottom and Player 2 plays Right, then the payoff received by Player 1 is d1 and the payoff received by Player 2 is d2.   2  Extensive Form Games An extensive form game describes the possible se- quential moves of players, each of the players makes his own decision and the play- ers are free to change their mind based on the consequences. An extensive form game is represented by a game tree, as shown in Fig. 3.2.  Such a game tree consists of nodes  initial, decision and terminal , branches, action labels, player labels, and payoffs. Figure 3.2 shows an extensive form game   28  S. Misra et al.  tree for two players—1 and 2. Player 1 moves ﬁrst and chooses either left or right. Based on player 1’s decision, player 2 makes his decision and chooses either A or B. If player 1 chooses right and player 2 chooses A, then player 1 gets −10 and player 2 gets 5.   3  Coalitional Games Coalitional games [31] are cooperative games, which fo- cus on the behavior of the group of players, rather than on individual players in the non-cooperative games. A coalitional game consists of:   a set players, N,   a set of actions for each group S  S ⊆ N  or coalition, and   preferences of the player over the set of all actions of all coalitions of which the player is a member.  A coalitional game can be represented by the pair  N, v , where N is the set of player and v is the coalitional value. The coalitional value is mapped into the amount of utility that individual members obtained from their coalition. A coalitional value can be in three different forms: characteristic, partition, and graph. In the charac- teristic form, the value of a coalition S depends exclusively on the members of the coalition. In the partition form, the coalitional value depends both on the members of the group or coalition, S, and on the rest of the players in the other coalition, N − S. In the graph form, the value v depends on the connection between players in the coalition.  3.5.2 Non-cooperative Game Theory  Non-cooperative game theory involves a set of players, where each player takes his individual decision independently, knowing the possible choices of other play- ers and their effect on the player’s utilities. Non-cooperative game theory mainly focuses on the study and analysis of competitive decision-makers. These types of game are used in various ﬁelds, for example, economics, political science, biology, sociology, and wireless networks. In this section, we describe how non-cooperative game theory is used for enforcing cooperation in delay tolerant networks.  To avoid selﬁsh behavior and stimulate cooperation, Buttyan et al. [32, 33] pro- posed the concept of barter, and developed a non-cooperative game theoretic model. The authors considered delay-tolerant personal wireless networks in a touristic city that distribute the information among the tourists. It may happen that selﬁsh users download interesting messages from others, but they do not store and distribute messages for the other users. Their model prevents this selﬁsh behavior using the concept of barter. When two nodes A and B come in contact with each other, they ﬁrst send the description of their messages. Then, they send a list of messages that they want to download from each other. Two types of messages were considered in the system—primary and secondary. A message is primary if the mobile node has interest in it, and secondary if the mobile node has no direct interest in it. Each   3 Cooperation in Delay Tolerant Networks  29  message has some barter value for each node and the value is determined by its age and type. Using the game theoretic model, the mobile nodes A and B decide the messages that they want to download from each other to maximize their own bene- ﬁt. The game model described consists of the players  P  , strategy space  Si , and the payoffs. Each individual node act as a player. The node behavior depends on two parameters  s, h , where s is the secondary ratio of the nodes represented by the primary players, and h is the threshold value, below which the nodes do not download the secondary messages from the other players. The payoffs of the players is the average total score of the nodes in the groups. Each node receives a score after each interac- tion, i.e., Score = Gain − Loss, where Gain is the total value of primary messages downloaded in the interaction and Loss is total number of exchanged messages in the interaction. Using the concept of best response and Nash equilibrium, it was observed that message delivery rate increases if the mobile nodes follow the Nash equilibrium.  Yin et al. [34] proposed a model named Pay-for-Gain  PFG . In this mechanism, each node keeps record of the identiﬁcation of encountered nodes, the total amount of buffer space it has lent from the encountered nodes, and the amount of buffer space it will lend to the encountered nodes. The authors deﬁned a Loan Feedback  LFB  function, as shown in  3.8  and  3.9 , which helps in computing the amount of buffer space lent to user Y by user X [34],   cid:10  × BF  X   BL Y     cid:9   cid:2  B Y   = g  cid:10  =  1,   cid:11    cid:9   g  BL Y    BL Y   ≤ B0  1   B Y  −B X    , BL Y   > B0   3.8    3.9   where B Y   is the amount of buffer space X lends to Y , BL Y   is the total amount of buffer space X lent to Y , BF  X  is the amount of buffer that has not been occupied, and B0 is the initial amount of buffer that a user can be lent.  Using the above two equations, each node can calculate how much it can lend to other users. When each pair of node offers equal-sized buffer space which they borrow from each other, the strategy PFG is similar to TFT, and according to the Nash equilibrium it is the maximum optimization possible. When the buffer space of a node is smaller than the expected buffer size of another node, then the node offers smaller buffer space between them, which is the Nash equilibrium of maximum optimization. So, both conditions lead to maximal interest.  3.5.3 Cooperative Game Theory  In non-cooperative game theory, each player’s individual actions are taken as prim- itives, whereas in cooperative game theory, the joint actions of group of players are taken as primitives.  Niyato et al. [35] used coalitional game theory for improving data delivery in DTNs. The authors ﬁrst developed a model based on a multi-dimensional absorbing   30  S. Misra et al.  Markov chain for heterogeneous groups of nodes in DTNs. This model measures the performance gain from various groups in terms of delay, throughput, and aver- age number of nodes carrying the packet. Then, they proposed a non-transferable utility  NTU  coalitional game. In a NTU game, the coalitional value cannot be as- signed a single real number, and thus, cannot be distributed among the players of the same coalition. The payoff received by each player in a coalition S is dependent on the joint actions that the players of coalition S select [36]. The game consists of communities or groups of nodes, strategy of each player and the payoff. The pay- off of data delivery of each community is calculated by considering the gain from throughput and loss from the cost of carrying and forwarding the packets. The strat- egy of each player is to ask whether to join or leave the coalition. A player can leave the coalition, if the payoff of the player is higher than that in original coalition. In this way, a coalition is split into multiple coalitions. Multiple coalition can collec- tively form a single coalition, if the newly formed coalition have higher payoff than the individual coalitions. The game is solved when it reaches a stable coalitional structure, where all players stops changing their decisions of joining and leaving the coalitions.  3.6 Other Cooperation Schemes Mechanisms  Besides the cooperation mechanism discussed above, there are other approaches, which shows how the cooperative and non-cooperative nodes affect the performance of routing in DTNs. We brieﬂy review them in this section.  Panagakis et al. [37] studied the effect of node cooperation  and lack of it  on epidemic, two-hop and binary spray-and-wait routing algorithms using the random direction mobility model. The performance of these algorithms was studied in terms of delivery delay of the messages and the corresponding transmission overhead. Co- operation was measured in terms of the node’s probability to drop the message copy on reception  Type I cooperation  due to misbehavior or resource constraints, or carry the message and forward the message copy upon node encounter  Type II co- operation . On reception of a message copy, a node either drops a message with probability Pdrop or forwards the message with probability Pf orward . So, the de- gree of cooperation in the ﬁrst case is  1 − Pdrop  and the degree of cooperation in the second case is Pf orward . Cooperation degree is measured using the metrics nor- malized mean delivery delay and total number of transmission as a function of the applied forwarding threshold. The authors observed that epidemic routing performs well in Type I and Type II cooperation, whereas binary spray-and-wait is more sen- sitive to mean delay and the two-hop relaying algorithm is the least sensitive to the cooperation algorithm.  Resta and Santi [38, 39] also analyzed the effect of different degree of node co- operation on the performance of routing protocols  epidemic, two-hop and binary spray-and-wait  in DTNs. Their work is different from [37] in the respect that they provide detailed theoretical insights on routing protocol performance in the pres- ence of different types of node cooperations. The authors considered four different   3 Cooperation in Delay Tolerant Networks  31  behaviors of the nodes—coop, def , rand and tft. In coop, the nodes behave normally according to the underlying routing protocol. In def , the nodes discard messages from the other nodes and send their own messages. In rand, the nodes forward other nodes messages with a probability p. With the tft strategy, a node forwards other nodes’ messages with a probability p, where p depends upon the network con- ditions. The authors evaluate the network performance with respect to the packet delivery rate. Epidemic routing performed the best and two-hop routing provided the worst performance. Binary SnW provided the best compromise between packet delivery rate and message transmission overhead.  Keranen et al. [40] considered forwarding, non-forwarding, and partly forward- ing nodes and investigated their impact on the message delivery ratio for three mobility scenarios  random waypoint, map-based model, and the real-life KAIST traces [41]  and three routing protocols  epidemic routing, spray-and-wait and PROPHET . In [37, 38], the nodes accept and silently drop the messages with some probability, which waste energy for the reception of the messages. On the contrary, in [40], the nodes do not accept the messages in the ﬁrst place, but exhibits a co- herent behavior. This work does not consider any incentive mechanism for cooper- ation. Instead, the authors proposed two types of behavior for cooperation—static and dynamic. Under the static cooperation scheme, behavior of the node remains the same throughout the network operation; under the dynamic scheme cooperation, the nodes acclimate the behavior on the basis of time energy constraints. Forward- ing nodes are cooperative nodes, which help in storing and forwarding the messages. Non-forwarding nodes are non-cooperative, which do not help in storing forwarding the messages of others, but receive messages destined to them using other nodes as free riders. Partly forwarding nodes receive others’ messages and forward if they come in direct contact with the corresponding destinations. So, the messages travel at most two hops for delivery to the destination. The authors evaluated network per- formance by considering the message delivery ratio achieved under the different routing protocols. The relative performance of spray-and-wait was less than the epi- demic and PROPHET protocols. All the three routing protocols behave good in the presence of 20–60 % of non-cooperating nodes, suggesting that mobile DTNs are quite robust against selﬁshness.  Panagakis et al. evaluated the effect of cooperation in DTNs through simulations. While Resta and Santi presented a theoretical framework for evaluating the effect of node cooperation in DTNs, they have not focused on the cost caused by the non- cooperation behaviors. Li et al. [42] studied the selﬁsh behavior of nodes which affects the system performance and analyzed how the non-cooperative behavior of the nodes impart negative impacts on the different routing algorithms. They consid- ered two-hop relay and epidemic routing protocol and modeled a two-dimensional continuous time Markov chain, which derives the system performance in terms of the message delivery latency and the delivery cost. The message delivery cost in- creases while dropping the messages, and reduces while not receiving the messages in the two-hop relay. Dropping a message increases the delay but does not affect the cost in case of epidemic routing. For both epidemic and two-hop routing pro- tocols, delivery latency increases and delivery cost decreases on not receiving the messages.   32  3.7 Open Issues  S. Misra et al.  The aspects of cooperation is promising in research on DTNs. While several ap- proaches for ensuring cooperation in such networks have been proposed, a few is- sues still remain there for further explorations.   Energy aspects: As discussed in Sect. 3.3, there are several attributes on which the nodes in a network could cooperate with each other. The existing works, however, do not investigate if energy of the nodes could be a driving force for cooperation. This is particularly relevant for unattended DTNs or PSNs, where the nodes do not have regular opportunities for recharging.   Multicasting scenarios: Multicasting in DTNs has received relatively less at- tention till date. Li et al. [43, 44] evaluated the performance of multicasting in energy-constrained DTNs in presence of social and individual selﬁshness of the nodes. It may be noted that any form of group-based communication would fail if the nodes in the network do not cooperate among themselves.   Content sharing in DTNs: Nguyen et al. [45] proposed Content Centric Delay Tolerant Networks  CCDTNs , where the content is provided through publish- subscribe mechanisms. The performance of CCDTNs would be affected if the nodes exhibit selﬁsh malicious behaviors. Such behavior could be with respect to the source destination of the content, or, perhaps, their category.   Human aspects: In PSNs, the mobile devices that communicate, are carried around by their human owners. Saha and Misra [12] have considered the effects of human intelligence on mission-oriented opportunistic networks  MOONs , which are an extension of the PSNs. It would be interesting to study how, if at all, the human factors affect cooperation in such networks.  3.8 Conclusion  To cope with issues such as intermittent connectivity, high latency, and asymmetric bandwidths, and provide interoperability among heterogeneous networks, the De- lay Tolerant Network  DTN  architecture was proposed. Since the communication opportunities among the nodes are rare in such challenged networks, it is desir- able that the nodes engage in cooperative behavior. In this work, we reviewed the incentive- and game theory-based approaches for stimulating cooperation in DTNs. While some schemes punish the selﬁsh malicious nodes, others reward the coop- erating ones. This survey reveals that game theoretic modeling of cooperation in DTNs is relatively poor, but growing. Furthermore, we identify several other direc- tions, for example, devices’ energy considerations and human aspects, into which the research efforts on cooperation in DTNs could be focused.  Acknowledgement The second author would like to thank TCS for their Fellowship Scheme and generous help, which has partly supported this work.   3 Cooperation in Delay Tolerant Networks  33  References  1. Warthman, F.  2003, Mar. . Delay-tolerant networks  DTNs : a tutorial v1.1. http:  www.dtnrg.  org docs tutorials warthman-1.1.pdf. Accessed 