sion has a vital role in crit- ical applications such as security, reconnaissance, surveillance, health monitoring amongst others. Thus digital video holds the key in future wireless communication. However, digital video transmission over wireless channels is signiﬁcantly compli- cated compared to traditional voice transmission due to the tremendous amount of bandwidth required. The following example illustrates the need for sophisticated signal processing for video transmission. As shown in Fig. 4.1, digital video transmission is organized into a series of picture frames. Consider the transmission of a video sequence of resolution 640 × 480 pixels at a rate of 30 frames per second with each of the Red, Green and Blue  RGB  components quantized to one byte each per pixel. The net raw bit rate Rraw  A.K. Jagannatham  B   Indian Institute of Technology, Kanpur, India e-mail: adityaj@iitk.ac.in  N. Chilamkurti et al.  eds. , Next-Generation Wireless Technologies, Computer Communications and Networks, DOI 10.1007 978-1-4471-5164-7_4,   Springer-Verlag London 2013  37   38  Fig. 4.1 Video frame sequence  A.K. Jagannatham  required for such video transfer is given as  Rraw = 30 × 640 × 480 × 3 × 8 = 220 Mbps.  Hence transmission of a raw unprocessed video signal consumes a signiﬁcant amount of bandwidth that cannot be supported by traditional communication links. It is therefore imperative to compress the video content prior to wireless transmis- sion and this involves the use of a video encoder. At the receiver, the video signal can be reconstructed from the compressed data stream through the use of a corre- sponding decoder. This encoder-decoder pair, which employs a certain format of compression, is termed a codec.  Figure 4.2 shows a basic schematic of a wireless communication system for video transmission. It is the complexity of the encoder and decoder processing which make the design and implementation of wireless video transmission an arduously chal- lenging task. Further, there is a keen interest in developing open global standards for the video codecs to ensure uniformity and platform independent video transmission and decodability. This desire has resulted in the coming together of video compres- sion experts across the world to spawn international standardization bodies such as ITU-T VCEG  Video Coding Experts Group  and ISO IEC MPEG  Motion Picture Experts Group  amongst others. Their efforts have resulted in the development of video compression standards such as MPEG-2, H.262, MPEG-4, H.264 etc., which have greatly sped up the implementation and adoption of systems for digital video storage and transmission such as DVDs, set-top boxes, video streaming over IP and so on. In this context, the H.264 SVC  Scalable Video Coding or Scalable Video Codec, depending on the context  is one such standard that has garnered signiﬁcant attention due to the promise it holds for wireless transmission of video content and is the focus of this paper. In the rest of the paper we describe the motivation to de- ploy such an SVC over wireless channels, followed by an elaborate overview of the SVC process and paradigms for optimization of multimedia streaming.   4 Wireless Multimedia  4G and Beyond   39  Fig. 4.2 Generic schematic of a video compression-based wireless communication system  Fig. 4.3 Spatial and temporal redundancies in a video stream  4.2 Basics of Video Compression  A digital video stream consists of a sequence of images known as frames  shown in Fig. 4.1  represented using the binary format of logical 0s and 1s. Such a video sequence is typically generated by the visual sampling of a dynamically evolving scene [3]. Video frames contain a signiﬁcant amount of spatially and temporally redundant information. The spatial redundancy arises from the fact that a substantial part of a typical frame is comprised of the background and objects with large swaths of uniform intensity such as people, trees etc. and is illustrated in the rectangular boxes in the frames in Fig. 4.3. Hence, a signiﬁcant reduction in the number of bits required to represent a frame can be obtained by compressing the spatially redundant parts of the picture frame. This is termed intra-frame compression and such frames are termed I frames. This is essentially similar to the principle employed in still image compression standards such as JPEG, GIF etc.  A unique feature of video that sets it apart from still images is the presence of a large amount of temporal redundant information. This arises from the presence of a number of objects displaced slightly between successive frames as indicated by the elliptical regions in the successive frames in Fig. 4.3. By predicting the motion   40  A.K. Jagannatham  Fig. 4.4 Motion prediction-based video compression  of the different objects or different components of a composite object  such as a human face , temporal redundancy can be eliminated, in turn substantially lowering the bit rate. This process is termed motion compensation  MC  and a generic encoder schematic that employs MC-based compression is shown in Fig. 4.4.  The process of predicting the motion of the objects between successive frames is termed motion estimation. This is done through the computation of motion vectors, which represent the direction and magnitude of displacement of the objects between the current and previous frame [3]. These motion vectors can be represented as a motion vector ﬁeld shown in Fig. 4.5.  Thus, in principle one can transmit the previous frame and the motion vectors and avoid transmission of the current frame entirely to save the bit rate. However, many times the motion vector estimation is not accurate. Further, motion estima- tion suffers from the problems of occlusion and uncovering. Occlusion refers to the phenomenon when an object in the previous frame becomes occluded in the cur- rent frame due to another object blocking it. Uncovering refers to the opposite case where an object becomes visible in the current frame after being blocked visually in the previous frame. Both these occurrences result in inaccuracies in motion pre- diction. Hence, one also transmits along with the motion vectors, the error between the motion compensated previous frame and the current frame  which is essentially small if the motion prediction algorithm is accurate and robust . The same is rep- resented in the schematic in Fig. 4.5 and lies at the heart of all modern video com- pression algorithms.   4 Wireless Multimedia  4G and Beyond   41  Fig. 4.5 Motion vector ﬁeld for a sample video frame  Fig. 4.6 IPB frames for video compression  Such frames which are predicted exclusively from a single past or future I frame are termed predicted or P frames. Further, frames can be predicted from a combina- tion of past and future frames, and such frames are denoted by B or bi-directionally coded frames. Figure 4.6 shows a typical sequence of frames in a compressed video stream along with the prediction dependencies. Such a sequence is termed a GOP  Group of Pictures . The interested reader can ﬁnd a more elaborate introduction to video compression in [4].  4.3 H.264 Video Compression and Scalable Video Coding  H.264 SVC supports video transmission at multiple bit rates depending on the qual- ity demanded and supported by the wireless environment [5]. However, a unique feature of the SVC is that the computational complexity required to code at several bit rates does not scale linearly with the number of bit rates supported. Instead, by   42  A.K. Jagannatham  Fig. 4.7 Group of pictures for temporal scalability  coding each higher bit rate as an enhancement layer over a base layer, the encoding complexity is much lower compared to multiple rate coding, signiﬁcantly improv- ing the ease of processing. Thus, it essentially codes a master bit-stream from which several valid lower quality video streams can be extracted depending on the require- ment. The term scalable refers to this aspect of the video stream, where the quality of the video content can be appropriately scaled by choosing to retain and drop dif- ferent layers from the same master bit-stream. Conventional bit-streams that do not have this scalability feature are termed single-layer streams. Scalability is achieved in the H.264 SVC through three scalability modes. These are  1. Temporal scalability 2. Spatial scalability 3. Quality or SNR scalability  Below we describe each of these modes in greater detail.  4.4 Temporal Scalability  A video stream is said to be temporally scalable when the frame rate of the stream can be varied adaptively by dropping a subset of frames from the master bit stream. A schematic of such a temporally scalable video stream is shown in Fig. 4.7. Each frame Tk belongs to the kth temporal layer, with k = 0 denoting the base tem- poral layer. The scalable stream is organized such that one can dispense with all   4 Wireless Multimedia  4G and Beyond   43  Fig. 4.8 Spatially scalable video stream  frames belonging to layers k ≥ K + 1 and the remaining frames belonging to lay- ers 0, 1, . . . , K will still constitute a valid video sequence, albeit one of a lower frame rate. Hence, the lowest temporal resolution one can choose corresponds to the layer T0. The addition of each subsequent higher layer increases the temporal resolution of the video sequence.  4.5 Spatial Scalability  A video stream is spatially scalable when one can dynamically vary the pixel res- olution of the transmitted video frames. A schematic of a spatially scalable video stream is illustrated in Fig. 4.8. This in turn yields a convenient handle to vary the bit rate dynamically, as it is directly proportional to the spatial resolution. Thus, one can transmit or extract a stream of lower spatial resolution for video streaming on handheld devices such as mobile phones and PDAs, while higher spatial resolutions can be employed for video conferencing, gaming, and other applications on portable laptop computers. Again, as in the case of temporal scalability, one can discard all spatial layers Sk such that k ≥ K + 1 and the remaining layers constitute a valid video stream, which has a lower spatial resolution compared to one that includes all the spatial layers. The video frames illustrated in Fig. 4.9 employ a dyadic scaling, in which the spatial resolution increases by a factor of 2 with each decoded enhancement layer.  4.6 SNR or Quality Scalability  Quality scalability refers to varying the bit-rate of the transmitted bit-stream by adaptively adjusting the resolution of the quantizer employed to represent the digi- tal frame. A coarser quantization results in a lower bit-rate and higher quantization noise level. This in turn yields a low SNR for the digital video stream and the cor- respondingly lower ﬁdelity of reproduction. Figure 4.10 shows three digital video   44  A.K. Jagannatham  Fig. 4.9 Video frames illustrating dyadic spatial scaling  Fig. 4.10 Video frames of decreasing quantizer resolution  frames encoded at progressively coarser quantization levels  quantization is coarser from left to right . Thus, by tweaking the ﬁdelity of the digital video one can opti- mally scale the bit-rate of the video stream to match the link quality of the wireless environment and also meet the QoS criteria for content delivery. The resolution of the quantizer is adapted in the transform or the DCT domain as it yields the most graceful degradation with decreasing quantizer resolution. As in the case of spatial and temporal scalability, the base layer video stream has the lowest SNR or essen- tially corresponds to the coarsest quantizer resolution. Each successive reﬁnement layer is predicted from the lower layers and the transform domain  block DCT  co- efﬁcients of the error image are quantized at a much ﬁner resolution compared to the lower layers and coded using a variable length entropy code.   4 Wireless Multimedia  4G and Beyond   45  4.7 Conclusion  The H.264 SVC speciﬁes the video stream syntax for the scalable proﬁle of the H.264 video compression standard. The scalability characteristic of the video stream is achieved through a combination of the temporal, spatial, and quality parameters of the video stream. However, the complexity of encoding this scalable stream is much lower than coding independently at multiple bit rates. The H.264 SVC’s rel- evance has been demonstrated in the context of next generation wireless networks since it can optimize the network performance for multimedia delivery by adaptively adjusting the bit-rate to suit the link quality, end client specs, and QoS constraints.  References  1. Dahlman, E., Parkvall, S., Sköld, J., & Beming, P.  2007 . 3G evolution HSPA and LTE for  mobile broadband. San Diego: Academic Press.  2. Andrews, J. G., Ghosh, A., & Muhamed, R.  2007 . Fundamentals of WiMAX: understanding  broadband wireless networking. New York: Prentice Hall.  3. Bovik, A.  2009 . The essential guide to video processing. Amsterdam: Elsevier. 4. Sullivan, G., & Wiegand, T.  2005 . Video compression—from concepts to the H.264 AVC  standard. Proceedings of the IEEE, 93 1 , 18–31.  5. Schwarz, H., Marpe, D., & Wiegand, T.  2007 . Overview of the scalable video coding exten- sion of the H.264 AVC standard. IEEE Transactions on Circuits and Systems for Video Tech- nology, 17 9 , 1103–1120.   Part II Wireless Communications and Applications   Chapter 5 Vehicular Ad-hoc Networks  VANETs : Architecture, Protocols and Applications  J.A. Guerrero-Ibáñez, C. Flores-Cortés, and Sherali Zeadally  5.1 Introduction  Modern society faces serious problems with transportation systems. Several factors contribute to the increase of the severity of these problems. One factor is the con- centration of population in speciﬁc areas. The technical report of the United Nations Population Foundations showed that for the ﬁrst time, more than half of the world’s population lives in urban areas [31]. As the urban z