iod where the UE device should follow Short Sleep Cycle, after The Inactivity Timer has expired. In LTE DRX, the sleep wake-up mode consists of the three different states, namely, inactivity period, light sleep period, and deep sleep period. The Inactivity period is the power active mode, whereas the light sleep period and the deep sleep period are the power saving mode. The transition from the Inactivity period to the light sleep period is controlled by Inactivity Timer, while the transition from the light sleep period to the deep sleep period within the power saving mode is controlled by Short Cycle Timer [28].  A typical power saving process in WiMAX is as follows: after the negotiation with the Base Station  BS , the Mobile Station  MS  turns off its Wireless Network Interface Card  WNIC  and gets into a low consumption state, namely, the sleep state, when the BS buffers all downlink trafﬁc for the MS and ensures that no trafﬁc is sent to it. Indeed, the MS does not know whether there are any data for it being buffered in the BS, and hence it has to wake up constantly to listen to the indication from the BS. If no packets are available for it, a new sleeping interval continues; otherwise it wakes up, switches on the WNIC again and enters into a serving state to receive the data. 802.16e deﬁnes three classes of power saving for different kinds of trafﬁc and applications. Class I, which caters for Best Effort  BE  and Non-Real- Time Variable Rate  NRT-VR  trafﬁc, provides limited QoS yet saves energy as much as possible. Class II supports delay guaranteed services and is suitable for Real-Time Variable Rate  RT-VR  trafﬁc. In addition, Class III sleeps for a long ﬁxed interval, and is therefore appropriate for multicast and management operations. In WiMAX, the BS controls the transmission power of the MS, as in the case of the CDMA system. The MS transmission power is controlled in order to avoid exceeding the BS’s total receiving power from an antenna. The WiMAX system sup- ports Adaptive Modulation and Coding  AMC , which varies the modulation, or the error correction coding rate according to the wireless channel quality. In the pres- ence of a good Signal-to-Noise-Ratio  SNR , the MS can use a high-speed modula- tion, and a small amount of error correction code, so a high transmission rate can be achieved. The SNR can be improved by allowing the MS to transmit at high power. However, increasing the transmission power increases the battery consumption, re- sulting in a shorter battery time. In the WiMAX system, the BS assigns sub-channels for each subordinate MS to avoid interference. An MS that experiences interference with its signal increases the transmission power to maintain the transmission rate. This shortens the battery lifetime further. Since battery lifetime is critical for a MS, it is important to control the transmission power in Mobile Stations, taking into consideration the transmission type and the battery lifetime [12].  Both WiMAX and LTE use OFDMA for the downlink and so have broadly similar performance for any given RF bandwidth and set of conditions. In con- trast, the modulation techniques for their uplinks are entirely different. WiMAX   98  F. Siddiqui et al.  Fig. 6.11 SC-FDMA transmitter–receiver [22]   including Mobile WiMAX  also uses OFDM for uplink, while LTE uses a new technique—Single Carrier Frequency Division Multiple Access  SC-FDMA . SC- FDMA is more power efﬁcient than OFDMA. This makes mobile devices consume less power, which increases their battery life.  SC-FDMA is a new multiple access technique that utilizes single carrier modula- tion, DFTspread orthogonal frequency multiplexing, and frequency domain equal- ization. It has a similar structure and performance as OFDM. SC-FDMA transceiver  as shown in Fig. 6.11  has a similar structure as a typical OFDM system except the addition of a new DFT block before subcarrier mapping. Hence, SC-FDMA can be considered as an OFDM system with a DFT mapper. The main advantage of SC- FDMA is the low Peak-Average-Power Ratio  PAPR  of the transmit signal. PAPR is deﬁned as the ratio of the peak power to average power of the transmit signal. As PAPR is a major concern at the user terminals, low PAPR makes the SC-FDMA the preferred technology for the uplink transmission. PAPR relates to the power am- pliﬁer efﬁciency at the transmitter, and the maximum power efﬁciency is achieved when the ampliﬁer operates at the saturation point. Lower PAPR allows operation of the power ampliﬁer close to saturation resulting in higher efﬁciency. With higher PAPR signal, the power ampliﬁer operating point has to be reduced to lower the signal distortion, and thereby lowering the ampliﬁer efﬁciency. As SC-FDMA mod- ulated signal can be viewed as a single carrier signal, a pulse shaping ﬁlter can be applied to transmit signal to further improve PAPR.  6.8 Cloud-Based Radio Access Networks  The traditional wireless network topology consists of adjacent or overlapping macro cells. However, various factors are changing this topology, including capacity con- straints, coverage issues and a need to support new classes of users and devices. A different network architecture called Cloud Radio Access Network  C-RAN  is being envisioned. A C-RAN moves the communications signal processing back into   6 Broadband Wireless Technologies  99  Fig. 6.12 Cloud-based Radio Access Network  C-RAN  architecture  a centrally located, virtualized base station, referred to as a Baseband Unit pool. As a result, cell sites are only responsible for radio transmission. Cell sites primarily consist of Remote Radio Heads  RRHs  and antennas  as shown in Fig. 6.12 . The virtualized servers perform baseband processing for a high number of cell sites  for example, thousands in a large data center . These cell sites are pooled resources and have the intelligence needed to support additional services [11].  In traditional base stations, the digital and radio processing elements are co- located with the antenna array. This is true for both macro and small cell formats, though there are variations of the implementation scheme. For example, RRHs are now relatively common in macro deployments. In a C-RAN conﬁguration, the radio equipment is located with the antenna array and the baseband digital processing, called radio equipment control, is remote with a ﬁber link connecting the two. The radio elements reside at the top of the tower and the digital processing in the cabinet at the base of the tower.  The Common Public Radio Interface  CPRI  provides a standard interface for interconnecting the radio elements. The major difference between the classic RRH and the cloud base station is the length of the ﬁber. In RRHs, the ﬁber is relatively short  a few hundred feet at most . In a cloud topology the ﬁber run may be up to several kilometers. In addition, there is extra processing deployed at the antenna to compress the antenna data so that multiple antenna streams can access and share the long-haul ﬁber. The beneﬁt of a cloud base station, which is the centralized portion   100  F. Siddiqui et al.  of a Cloud Radio Access Network  C-RAN , comes from co-locating many sets of Radio Equipment Control elements. According to the China Mobile Research Insti- tute, Cloud RANs will “improve network quality and coverage, reduce transmission resource consumption” [25].  6.8.1 Beneﬁts of C-RANs  Cloud-based RAN deployments are expected to provide spectral efﬁciency gains. Co-location of large-scale antenna processing may also lead to very efﬁcient co- ordinated interference management. Rather than coordinate across multiple geo- graphically disperse base stations, a concentrated view of the available spectrum eliminates the need to transmit coordination data sets. The ability to generate and evaluate multiple transmission scenarios between transmission intervals will ulti- mately determine the spectral efﬁciency for the entire geographic coverage area. A well designed scheduler implemented in a cloud RAN will lead to better user scheduling and ultimately to enhanced spectrum usage. This assumes a signiﬁcant increase in signal processing capability that is scaled to handle the larger spectral input and a large number of users.  6.8.2 Challenges in Deploying C-RANs  There are a few challenges that may prevent the vision of cloud RAN from becoming a widespread reality. The main issue could be the cost and availability of long- distance ﬁber. Often wireless or other wired links are used for base station backhaul. This is because ﬁber may be impractical for cost, physical impediments or right-of- way issues. Other alternatives to ﬁber simply do not have the bandwidth to transport the volume of antenna data that a cloud base station requires. In those situations where these impediments exist, traditional macro or small cell base stations will continue to be deployed. Another potential obstacle in the C-RAN deployment is latency. Propagation delay over relatively long ﬁber links may not be high, but it might induce enough latency to negatively impact spectral efﬁciency. This could hinder cloud RAN deployments or limit them to dense city environments, where the distance to the server facility will be short [25].  6.9 Conclusion  There exists an ever-increasing demand for high speed broadband wireless tech- nologies supporting high data transmission rates and mobility. This requirement has created an interest among network providers and telecom operators to develop and   6 Broadband Wireless Technologies  101  deploy new technologies capable of offering low-cost, high efﬁciency services to end users. WiMAX, 3GPP LTE, an LTE-A are leading wireless broadband services being deployed to fulﬁll user demands. WiMAX deployments have already begun throughout the world, whereas LTE-A is still in an early installation phase. There are also ongoing research efforts to integrate WiMAX and LTE and provide seamless mobility services across these two access networks.  In this chapter we have presented a comparison of existing and emerging broad- band wireless technologies. WiMAX and LTE have several similarities, yet they differ in their evolution, industry support, and deployment models. As the number of WiMAX subscribers increases, and the LTE LTE-A market also gains momen- tum, these technologies will play a major role in achieving successful deployment of large-scale mobile broadband services. Furthermore, as subscribers continue to increase and higher data transfer speeds are required, vendors around the world are trying to move Radio Access Networks into the cloud to address some of the emerg- ing challenges of broadband wireless access networks. Cloud RANs are expected to signiﬁcantly improve the scalability as well as the computational efﬁciency of these networks.  Acknowledgements We thank the reviewers for their constructive comments which helped us improve the quality of this chapter. Sherali Zeadally was partially supported by a District of Columbia NASA Space Grant and an NSF TIP grant  Award Number 1036293  during the course of this work.  Appendix: Deﬁnition of Acronyms  Third Generation Partnership Project Average Revenue Per Unit Base Station Buffer Status Reports  3GPP ARPU BS BSR CDMA Code Division Multiple Access Customer Premises Equipment CPE Dynamic Host Conﬁguration Protocol DHCP DL Down Link Evolved Packet System EPS Fast Base Station Switching FBSS Frequency Division Duplex FDD FS Frame Structure Guaranteed Bit Rate GBR Long Term Evolution LTE MAC Medium Access Control MDHO Macro-Diversity Handover MME MMR MS  Mobility Management entity Mobile Multi-hop Relay Mobile Station   102  F. Siddiqui et al.  Network-Architecture Speciﬁc Non-Line-of-Sight Orthogonal Frequency Division Multiplexing Physical Broadcast Channel Physical Downlink Control Channel Packet Data Network Gateway Physical Point-to-multipoint Physical Uplink Control Channel Physical Uplink Shared Cha