for the movement path of an object. With this information, it is possible to minimize the number of nodes to be visited without ﬂooding queries to all nodes in the network. Traceability queries are ﬁrst processed locally. Based on the outcome of this process, the query is further ana- lyzed. It may be rewritten and then forwarded to other distributed databases. The results retrieved from the network are added to the local results and post-processing is required to yield the ﬁnal response.  One advantage of Theseos is that the data are not centrally maintained and each organization has the ability to selectively share traceability data with other trading partners. Another advantage is its scalability. Since data are processed and stored in each individual node, the workload is naturally distributed. Unfortunately, to obtain the sentTo and receivedFrom information, Theseos requires high synchronization with other enterprise data  e.g., billing or accounting information . This is imprac- tical for many applications where such enterprise data may be unavailable. Another signiﬁcant disadvantage of Theseos is its instability. If any of the peers is down, all queries relevant to that peer will fail. This is because of the difference between peer-based RFID solutions and other peer-based data sharing applications such as Bittorrent [47]. Bittorrent allows redundancy to exist and makes good use of this feature to increase data availability and reliability. But peer-based RFID solutions keep data strictly private at each node  i.e., there is no redundancy .  Theseos allows enterprises to selectively control access to traceability data using Hippocratic Database  HDB  [4] technology based on ten principles rooted in pri- vacy regulations. Consequently, successful execution of a traceability query requires the inquiring party to have the access privileges to the data stored at the nodes along the movement paths of an object.  7.3.2.7 PeerTrack  PeerTrack [49, 50] is a platform designed for efﬁciently tracking and tracing objects in large-scale RFID systems. PeerTrack features a pure P2P architecture for data and query processing. In particular, a data model for traceability networks has been designed, which eliminates the data dependencies between organizations. Important tracking and tracing queries have been implemented as built-in features and it en- ables ﬂexible support for the development of add-in queries. PeerTrack relies on a generic data model for moving objects in large-scale networks, namely “a Model for mOving Objects in Discrete Space”  MOODS . A discrete space refers to a ﬁnite set of nodes which represents all the organizations in the network. MOODS elimi- nates the data dependencies between organizations by storing the information about object movements at the nodes where the object has been transported. In particular, PeerTrack introduces the Information of Object Path  IOP , which includes proper- ties that indicate the departure and arrival information of objects, such as timestamps and physical locations. With IOP, each node maintains segments of objects’ moving paths and uses this information to expedite P2P queries in the network.   118  Y. Wu et al.  7.3.3 Open Issues and Challenges  As we have discussed above, many issues still need to be addressed at the architec- ture level in RFID systems.  7.3.3.1 Uncertainty and Prediction Query Support  Most of the existing architectures do not address uncertainty explicitly. The assump- tion that the underlying data capturing technologies are perfect is not correct. Un- certainty in captured data signiﬁcantly affects the results generated by traceability queries. In recent years, uncertainty has become an active research topic [2, 6]. Only the architecture extension supported by BRIDGE has provided high-level models and algorithms capable of modeling the uncertainty. However, an important issue with the approach is the need of supervised learning for the models to be useful. Signiﬁcant work is needed to  i  investigate other modeling techniques such as Con- ditional Random Field  CRF , skip chain CRF [40] and Emerging Patterns [18] and  ii  consider more dynamic models that do not require a learning phase [19, 37].  7.3.3.2 Scalability  The existing architectures have achieved scalability based on either federated or P2P architectures. EPCglobal Network and BRIDGE are federated. The problem with this approach is that the Discovery Service  Serial Lookup Service in BRIDGE  be- comes a bottleneck. This issue is considered by the Hierarchical P2P approach by implementing the Discovery Service in a pure distributed manner and by DIALOG based on its multi-agent design. In general, in a P2P-based approach, each node delegates a query to its neighbors if it cannot answer the query itself. For exam- ple, in Theseos and PeerTrack, queries are processed locally and rewritten before forwarded to the next node. However, a signiﬁcant issue for P2P-based approach is that each node must take an equal importance in the network and be open to the idea of having its data stored on different peers that may be controlled by competitive businesses.  7.3.3.3 Timely Response  EPC Network, BRIDGE and DIALOG use subscription mechanisms  “push”-based approaches  to support real-time data requirements. However, in query processing, P2P architectures are not capable of providing time constraints although this is an important requirement for traceability applications. For P2P architectures, a query may be propagated several times and this signiﬁcantly increases the processing time. Improving the timeliness of query responses is a signiﬁcant issue and future research is needed in this direction.   7 RFID: Opportunities and Challenges  119  7.3.3.4 Security and Privacy  To enable a fully distributed RFID system, there must be some level of data shar- ing between nodes. Access control in DIALOG is shifted away from parties down the supply chain towards manufacturers. Manufacturers of objects exercise a strong control over the collection of information from other parties and sharing of that information with client applications. In contrast, the EPCglobal Network  through the Discovery Services mechanism developed in BRIDGE  allows highly granular access control policies to be speciﬁed by parties collecting information in order to determine access rights by other entities to product related data. There are trade- offs between the privacy and data sharing. For example, P2P architectures protect privacy adequately by providing nodes with ownership of the data and the choice to respond to queries from desirable parties, which also means some constraints for data sharing. Thus techniques for dealing with the tradeoff between privacy and data sharing are still a research challenge.  7.4 RFID Data Processing, Management and Mining  In this section, we present the state-of-art research on RFID data processing, man- agement and mining.  7.4.1 RFID Data Processing  7.4.1.1 RFID Data Cleaning  To compensate the unreliability of RFID streams, most of the RFID stream clean- ing middleware employ the “Smoothing Filter” technology. SMURF [22] is the ﬁrst declarative, adaptive smoothing ﬁlter for RFID data cleaning. In particular, SMURF models the unreliability of RFID readings by viewing RFID streams as a statistical sample of tags in the physical world. SMURF continuously adapts the size of the smoothing window size to provide accurate RFID data. In [21], the authors pro- posed an abstracted adaptive RFID framework called MDI-SMURF which cleans the RFID data while shielding applications from the challenges that arise when interacting directly with sensor devices. Rao et al. [35] introduced a deferred ap- proach for detecting and correcting RFID data anomalies. Unlike SMURF which cleans data according to its own rules, this work allows applications to deﬁne detec- tion and correction rules and rewrites the queries based on these rules on the data. In [30], a new adaptive data cleaning scheme, called WSTD, is proposed. WSTD uses the comparison of the two window subrange observations or estimated tag counts to detect when transitions occur within a window.  In [52], the authors introduced an approach for data cleaning that exploits basic characteristics of RF signals as well as the maximum likelihood operations. This   120  Y. Wu et al.  method enables reasoning about the position of RFID tags in the reader’s range without measuring the signal strength of tag responses.  Liao et al. [28] dealt with another problem that data streams collected by multiple readers usually contain cross-reads,7 by introducing a method that estimates the density of each tag using a kernel-based function and keeps the event from the reader corresponding to the micro-cluster with the largest density.  In [26], a Bayesian inference-based framework for cleaning RFID raw data is proposed. The authors ﬁrst studied an n-state detection model and formally prove that 3-state model can maximize the system performance. Then they extend the model to support 2-dimensional RFID reader arrays.  There are also some generic data cleaning frameworks. Gonzalez et al. [17] pro- posed a cleaning framework that takes an RFID dataset and a collection of clean- ing methods, with associated costs, and a cleaning plan that optimizes the overall cleaning costs by determining the conditions under which inexpensive methods are appropriate and necessary. Jeffery et al. [20] propose the Extensible Sensor Stream Processing  ESP  framework to build sensor data cleaning infrastructures. ESP is designed as a pipeline using declarative cleaning methods.  Open Issues and Challenges Recently proposed cleaning methods for RFID streams mostly focus on improving the data qualify from a statistical perspective  i.e., they are speciﬁcally designed for aggregated queries such as COUNT, AVG and SUM. Moreover, these methods focus on the aggregated information of indi- vidual objects. As a result, they are not suitable for dealing with cross-site trajectory queries in distributed traceability applications. The ability to recover the missing readings in a distributed system at the item-level is still a challenge.  7.4.1.2 RFID Event Processing  In an uncertain environment, extracting and processing semantically events from RFID data streams is also associated with various challenges. Consequently, regular event processing techniques are no longer effective.  In [25], a probabilistic approach  called PEEX  is presented for high-level event extraction from RFID data. PEEX translates event deﬁnitions into SQL queries and based on conﬁdence tables to determine the probability of ambiguous events. It uses partial events to handle data errors. In [36], an event processing system, Lahar, for probabilistic event streams was proposed. Lahar exploits the probabilistic nature of the data to enable declarative queries over real time and archived streams of prob- abilistic events. Cascadia [48] is another RFID event processing system which can cope with ambiguous RFID data by transforming RFID readings into probabilistic  7In a small environment, a tag may be read by more than one reader at the same time; as a result, its location is uncertain because of inconsistency derived from the readers.   7 RFID: Opportunities and Challenges  121  events. In [31], the authors proposed an approach to perform Complex Event Pro- cessing directly over the unreliable RFID event streams instead of the cleaned ones, by incorporating cleaning requirements into complex event speciﬁcations.  In [45] and [46], the authors introduced an approach for event materialization under uncertainty, which includes a model for representing materialized events us- ing Bayesian Network, and the algorithms for specifying the probability space of an event history where Monte Carlo sampling algorithm is used to assess materialized event probabilities.  In [41], the authors proposed a probabilistic model to capture the mobility of the reader, object dynamics and noisy readings. This model can self-calibrate by auto- matically estimating key parameters from observed data. Based on the model, the authors also proposed a sampling-based technique to infer clean, precise informa- tion about object locations from raw streams from mobile RFID readers.  Open Issues and Challenges The models, algorithms, and frameworks discussed earlier are designed mainly for the extraction of high-level events from unreliable RFID data and the derivation of their conﬁdences. However, they mostly focus on each individual RFID-tagged object and location, rather than the trajectories of their movements. As we discussed in Sect. 7.2, extracting trajectory-based information is very important for RFID-based traceability applications and many open research issues still need further research.  7.4.2 Management of RFID Data  Data models determine the structures of the data storage and representation. The design of data models signiﬁcantly affects the performance of the whole system. Due to the nature of large-scale traceability applications, data models must be ap- propriately designed to support various queries in highly dynamic, data-intensive environments. To support traceability applications in different business contexts, fundamental generic data models are necessary. In this section, we examine recent research efforts on data modeling and corresponding query processing techniques for RFID systems.  7.4.2.1 DRER Model  Dynamic Relationship ER  DRER  [42] as shown in Fig. 7.3 is the data model used by Siemens’ RFID middleware system. It is one of earliest RFID data models. It abstracts the static and dynamic entities including object, reader, location and transaction. Interactions are modeled as either state- or event-based relationships. In [42], low-level temporal and spatial queries are considered. Although the design takes containment into consideration by introducing the Containment relationship, it does not mention how this relationship is captured. DRER models the transition   122  Y. Wu et al.  Fig. 7.3 The DRER model  The simplicity of this model also leads to a few drawbacks:  of states for objects using the dynamic relations  e.g., ObjectLocation . This model is simple yet expressive, so that it can be used to answer most of the queries.   The model and the query processing techniques assume all data are stored in a single database or database cluster. They are hard to use in highly distributed, heterogeneous systems.   The model focuses on modeling individual RFID events. It lacks support for com- plex data structures  such as path . Consequently, some queries have to be imple- mented by composing low-level queries which are not efﬁcient.   The model lacks support for statistical queries.  7.4.2.2 KAIST Trace Model  Researchers from KAIST  Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology  proposed a novel model to efﬁciently encode and query path information in an RFID database [27].8 The encoding scheme is based on the Chinese Remainder Theorem and can encode a path to a serial number level. A query processing language is also proposed. The idea of this model is to represent the paths as a forest. Each starting location is presented by the root of a tree and receiving locations are child nodes of sending locations.  Experiments have proved that this encoding scheme with the query processing method efﬁciently discovers the path information for a given object. In particular, for most queries, the KAIST model is better than RFID Cuboid [16]. Moreover, similar to the RFID-Cuboid model, it signiﬁcantly decreases the data storage size. However, this model does not assume that the object moves in groups, so it can be  8The authors did not give a name to the model. For convenience, we call it “KAIST Trace Model”.   7 RFID: Opportunities and Challenges  123  Fig. 7.4 SPIRE  used in more scenarios. The KAIST trace model is path-centric and can efﬁciently process path-oriented queries.  The KAIST trace model has several issues which prevent it from being used in distributed environments. First, the encoding decoding scheme is path-oriented, thus data from different nodes must be stored in the same sever, otherwise it be- comes difﬁcult to build the tree. Second, once the tree is built, any change in the network requires the whole tree to be rebuilt. In dynamic distributed environments, this process is costly in terms of both time and bandwidth.  7.4.2.3 SPIRE Model  None of the aforementioned models discuss how the containment relationship is captured. The automatic inference of the containment relationship is still an open research problem. It is a multiple-layer problem which involves hardware conﬁgu- ration, data cleansing, uncertain data management and other techniques. SPIRE is a research effort that attempts to address this problem.  An earlier work from SPIRE [8] proposes two options to detect containment relationships. One option is the manual approach, the other is to conﬁgure RFID readers so that each reader can read only the outermost container’s tag. However, it does not solve the regrouping problem. In addition, due to the unreliability of RFID readers, it will not work perfectly even with the assumption that no regrouping exists. In a recent work by the same authors [9], the SPIRE system is improved to detect containment relationship using a statistical method. In this approach, the containment is inferred by the historical co-location of tags. A time-varying colored graph model was proposed as shown in Fig. 7.4.  The edges indicate possible containment relationship, while the objects detected together at the same location are marked with the same color. At the beginning, the edges are added from the higher level container to lower level objects containers if   124  Y. Wu et al.  they are at the same location. After they move to a new location, some edges are removed if there is no co-location relationship anymore. Ideally, after some point, there should be exactly one path from the root to a certain leaf. However, this rarely happens because of regrouping. To address this problem, a probabilistic inference method is proposed in SPIRE. The basic idea is to assign weights to the co-location records with a recent record receiving a higher weight. The incoming edges to a node are sorted by the weighted sums of the co-location records. SPIRE chooses the edge with the highest sum to update the containment relationship.  The containment relationship is inferred by co-location of tags but it cannot dis- tinguish between co-location and containment. To solve this problem, it is necessary to encode the containment level information in the tag. This makes this model in- ﬂexible and expensive because the tag must be uniﬁed across all organizations.  7.4.2.4 Open Issues and Challenges  The underlying RFID data models play an important role in shaping the higher level architectures for RFID systems. A well-designed data model can signiﬁcantly im- prove system performance and decrease persistent data storage requirements. From the discussion above, we found that signiﬁcant work remains in the area of RFID data models and query processing:   Distributed data model. Most RFID systems are distributed and spread across or- ganizations. It is difﬁcult to assume or require data to be stored in centralized databases. Distributed data models therefore need to be carefully designed to support traceability queries. However, at the time of writing, to the best of our knowledge, there are no existing data models that meet all the requirements we have outlined. We believe that extensive research efforts are needed for modeling distributed RFID data.   Statistical queries over trajectories. These queries can provide data ﬂow statistics through particular nodes or trajectories, which are vital for high-level business decisions in RFID applications. Unfortunately, these statistical queries are not well supported by existing data models.   Containment queries. Containment queries over object trajectories are also im- portant, especially in product recalls where an object  e.g., tainted pork  from a node should be recalled. For these scenarios, it is necessary to ﬁnd all other ob- jects  e.g., other pork that traveled in the same pallet  that have a containment relationship with the object in question, obtain their paths and recall them. Unfor- tunately, containment queries are also not well supported by most of the existing data models.   Uncertainty. Most existing data models do not take uncertainty of RFID data into consideration. However, as we have discussed in Sect. 7.2, uncertainty should be treated as ﬁrst class citizen in RFID traceability networks.   7 RFID: Opportunities and Challenges  7.4.3 RFID Data Mining  7.4.3.1 RFID Warehousing  125  The idea of RFID Cuboid [16] is based on the observation that individual objects tend to move and stay together  i.e., bulky object movements . The records for the objects moving along the same segments can be merged without loss of informa- tion. The term “cuboid” implies that data are merged at some point. Compared with DRER, RFID Cuboid is a data mining model instead of dynamic event-driven model.  The most important advantage of RFID-cuboid is the efﬁcient support of sta- tistical and path-oriented queries, by grouping the objects and consolidation of the group information. This consolidation signiﬁcantly improves the performance of query processing. However, the storage used by RFID-Cuboid is higher than that used by DRER because of the additional tables. This additional storage cost is fur- ther reduced by the same authors’ recent work where they introduced a Gateway- Based Movement Graph model [15]. This enhanced work assumes that there are some “gateway” nodes in an RFID network, which have either high fan-in or high fan-out edges. These gateway nodes connect the sub-graphs together.  The RFID Cuboid can be established around the gateway nodes, and ungrouped within the sub-graphs. Instead of using the starting location of a group of objects as the root, the gateway-based movement graph selects the gateway nodes as the root. In this way, the root groups are the largest, so that the number of groups is minimized. This is very useful for large-scale, distributed traceability applications  e.g., global supply chain systems .  The RFID-Cuboid model efﬁciently compresses the data and improves the per- formance of queries using a tree-structure. However, it is highly dependent on the data distribution. The performance is signiﬁcantly affected if objects do not exhibit bulky movements. Consequently, this data model is only suitable for large datasets that share some common properties  e.g., move together in bulky mode .  7.4.3.2 Pattern Matching  Pattern matching over uncertain event streams is an important topic also. In [1], the authors proposed a formal evaluation model that offers precise semantics for the new class of queries and a query evaluation framework that allows for systematic optimizations in a principled way. Zhao et al. [51] proposed a model to measure pat- tern frequency based on the possible world semantics. Two mining algorithms were developed based on the model for mining frequent sequential patterns. In [29], two solutions to deal with out-of-order event streams were proposed, namely aggressive and conservative strategies. The aggressive strategy produces maximal output under the optimistic assumption that out-of-order event arrival is rare, while the conserva- tive one deals with the common out-of-order data.   126  Y. Wu et al.  In [43], the authors modeled the mining of frequent itemsets as a Poisson bino- mial distribution and developed an approximate algorithm which can efﬁciently and accurately discover frequent itemsets in a large uncertain evolving databases.  7.4.3.3 Open Issues and Challenges  As we discussed above, there has been some research on mining RFID data. How- ever, there are still some open issues and interesting challenges that need to be ad- dressed in the future.   Trajectory-based mining. The current pattern matching research focus on frequent item sets  i.e., objects often appearing together . However, no trajectory-based mining has been done. Due to the uncertainties of RFID data, it is difﬁcult to get the complete trajectory for all the objects. This still remains a challenging problem that has not really been investigated.   Distributed RFID data mining. Most large-scale RFID systems are distributed. It is necessary to enable the mining across different organizations which leads to several challenges. First, we have the problem of exchanging large volumes of data. Due to the network cost, it is inefﬁcient to send over all the data. The second issue is about the location where mining should be done. This will require careful load balancing solutions to be in place.  7.5 Summary  RFID promises to revolutionize the way we track items in supply chain, retail store, and asset management applications. In this chapter, we have provided an introduc- tion of its basic concepts and we have highlighted the challenges that currently need to be addressed in the RFID system architecture. We presented the state-of-art re- search results on RFID data processing, data management and mining. We also propose some problems which are suitable topics for future exploratory research, including:   Uncertainties management. Uncertainty is a natural characteristic of RFID tech- nology, not only in the data themselves, but also in the way they are processed. Modeling uncertainties and managing them are important and interesting prob- lems.   Trajectory management. Most data models are object-based. Trajectory is treated as second-class citizen. However, trajectory is fundamental to implement tracking and tracing in RFID systems. We argue that more research needs to be done in this area.   Distributed data mining. Mining distributed RFID data streams is also needed because most RFID systems are distributed across several sites and are spread across various organizations. Data exchange and load balancing are two interest- ing issues that need to further investigations.   7 RFID: Opportunities and Challenges  127  Acknowledgements Quan Z. Sheng’s work has been partially supported by Australian Research Council  ARC  Discovery Grant DP0878917 and Linkage Project LP100200114. We thank the reviewers for their valuable comments, which helped us improve the content and quality of this chapter.  References  1. Agrawal, J., Diao, Y., Gyllstrom, D., & Immerman, N.  2008 . Efﬁcient pattern matching over event streams. In Proceedings of the 2008 ACM SIGMOD international conference on management of data  SIGMOD’08 , Vancouver, Canada.  2. Agrawal, P., Benjelloun, O., Das Sarma, A., Hayworth, C., Nabar, S., Sugihara, T., & Widom, J.  2006 . Trio: a system for data, uncertainty, and lineage. In Proceedings of the 32nd inter- national conference on very large data bases  VLDB’06 , Seoul, Korea.  3. Agrawal, R., Cheung, A., Kailing, K., & Schonauer, S.  2006 . Towards traceability across sovereign, distributed RFID databases. In Proceedings of the 10th international database en- gineering and applications symposium  IDEAS’06 , Delhi, India.  4. Agrawal, R., Kiernan, J., Srikant, R., & Xu, Y.  2002 . Hippocratic databases. In Proceedings  of the 28th international conference on very large data bases  VLDB’02 .  5. Aigner, M., & Feldhofer, M.  2005 . Secure symmetric authentication for RFID tags. In Pro-  ceedings of the telecommunication and mobile computing  TCMC’05 , Graz, Austria.  6. Cheng, R., Singh, S., & Prabhakar, S.  2005 . U-DBMS: a database system for managing constantly-evolving data. In Proceedings of the 31st international conference on very large data bases  VLDB’05 .  7. Cheung, A., Kailing, K., & Schönauer, S.  2007 . Theseos: a query engine for 