the need to extend the lifetime of WSN by prolonging the life of its sensor nodes.  Let us consider a scenario where the WSN is required to monitor the forest to avoid or minimize the risk of ﬁre hazards. Hundreds of sensor nodes will be re- quired to monitor the vast area of the forest. Accordingly, the farthest node in the forest will be many hops away from the sink. As the number of hops increases we will require more transmissions for the data to reach to the sink. Among the three subsystem of a sensor node the communication subsystem consumes more energy on average than the processing subsystem [2]. Generally, the sensing subsystem consumes a lower amount of energy depending on the type of sensor used  e.g., for temperature, light etc. . However, in some cases the sensor nodes may consume a substantial amount of energy  e.g., when using a Global Positioning System  GPS  module [26] . Accordingly, there are various mechanisms that can be implemented to either consume less energy or to provide more energy by scavenging from the environment. In any case, energy consumption is critical and is a key issue in WSNs that must be addressed.  Since the communication subsystem consumes more energy many approaches proposed in the literature aim to minimize the communication cost. Some of these approaches include: the use of in-network processing, location awareness or to send data when needed to reduce the communication cost while others exploit duty cy- cling and put the nodes in sleep mode whenever there is no task to be performed. Other approaches use mobility if available in the network to further reduce the en- ergy consumption by not allowing the sensor nodes to directly send the data to the   8 Energy Efﬁcient Routing in Wireless Sensor Networks  135  sink but by moving mobile sensor nodes toward the sensor nodes in order to col- lect the data. Referring to the forest monitoring scenario we describe how we can save energy during transmissions. Generally, all the sensor nodes need to report to the sink periodically. In this case the sensor nodes farthest in the forest drain more energy from the network because nodes on the way have to send their own data and forward the data from other sensor nodes as well. The situation becomes worse for nodes near to the sink resulting in an imbalance of energy in the network. To address this imbalance one proposed solution is to use multiple disjoint paths which lead to a balanced energy consumption. Another proposed mechanism requires that the sen- sor nodes do not send data periodically. Instead, the sensor nodes start sending the data towards the sink [37] when an event occurs  e.g., when a ﬁre is detected in the forest . In this mechanism the energy depletion is directly proportional to the num- ber of events happening in the forest. It is also found that the generated data have spatial and temporal correlations [41]. Some mechanisms [17, 30] exploit these cor- relations and make clusters within the forest based on some criteria. In this scenario, instead of all nodes from the farthest areas sending data to the sink, they will send data to some speciﬁed cluster head  e.g., trees of same kind may form a cluster . After some processing only the cluster head will send data to the sink instead of all sensor nodes in the vicinity thereby saving signiﬁcant amounts of energy. Energy can also be saved by not allowing the sensor nodes to send data periodically but whenever the application needs the data it will send the query to the network  e.g., the humidity level at tree number 120 . In this case, only sensor nodes which can respond to the query will respond back . In addition, the energy drain is related to the number of queries made by the application. Location information can also be used to save energy in WSNs. Instead of ﬁnding paths to the sink the sensor nodes know where the sink is located and send the data in that direction  e.g., the sensor nodes of some tree send data in a northern direction .  To further save energy when there are no data to send the sensor nodes may go into a sleep mode. Despite the fact that sensor nodes are not sending the data, being in active state consumes energy. Therefore, duty cycling is now getting attention by researchers. However, if the sensor nodes require to sleep and wake up frequently then the energy savings may not be optimal since letting the sensor node to go in sleep mode and awakening it back also requires energy. Still, in this case, once the data are generated they have to traverse the network to reach the sink.  Mobility in WSNs can also be utilized to reduce the energy consumption pro- vided mobility incurs low overheads. Generally, mobility incurs more energy ex- penditure on the mobile node, i.e., motors and other hardware require more energy. The main assumption by mobile WSNs is that the mobile nodes do not have energy constraints. They traverse the network and return back to the sink where they can be recharged because at the sink we do not suffer from limited resources. Moreover, the mobility may be inherent in the network  e.g., moving people or guards in the forest . Using our forest example, the sensor nodes on the trees gather the environ- mental data and wait for the mobile node to come in contact with them. Once the sensor node encounters a mobile node it will transfer its data to it. After traversing the forest, the mobile node comes into contact with the sink where it ofﬂoad the data,   136  F.K. Shaikh et al.  saving energy. This approach needs the sensor nodes to be aware of the existence of the mobile node. Next, we classify current energy-efﬁcient routing protocols that have been proposed for WSNs.  8.3 Classiﬁcation of Energy Efﬁcient Routing Protocols  Energy is a very scarce resource in WSNs and most of the times WSNs are used for applications where access is either not necessary or not possible in order to monitor or sense vicinity conditions. The energy resource could be saved by avoiding the transmission of redundant user data or may be by following the same routes or not to transmit receive anything when not required to do so. Therefore, it is not desirable to use sensor nodes in a way that they need to be recharged frequently. To address this aforementioned issue, various routing protocols have been designed to utilize the energy resource efﬁciently.  Typically, WSNs utilize intrinsic sensor node redundancy for assuring proper network connectivity such that all sensor nodes can communicate with the sink in a multihop fashion. However, the redundancy of sensor nodes comes at a cost. Redun- dant nodes generate correlated information and deliver the same information from multiple sensor nodes rapidly depletes the energy resources in the network. Being an ad-hoc environment, WSN is subject to a wide range of operational perturbations af- fecting the delivery of information to the sink. Along with node and communication perturbations, environmental disturbances also contribute to the loss of information. New routing protocols that take into consideration these perturbations in WSNs have emerged in the last few years. These proposed routing protocols consider the inher- ent features of WSNs along with the application requirements. An efﬁcient routing protocol will improve network lifetime and supports efﬁcient power utilization. Due to energy constraints, ﬁnding and maintaining routes in WSNs is a core issue be- cause the sensor node status  e.g., failure, malfunction, sleep or relocation  along the route may change, resulting in frequent topological changes. Thus, the routing protocols employ different routing mechanisms, suitable for WSNs, to minimize energy consumption. Accordingly, we classify the current energy-efﬁcient routing protocols for two major classes of WSN applications, i.e., delay sensitive routing protocols and delay tolerant routing protocols as shown in Fig. 8.3. We further clas- sify energy-efﬁcient routing protocols for delay sensitive routing as reliable routing and best effort routing and for delay tolerant routing as routing based on duty cycles and routing for mobile WSNs.  Energy-Efﬁcient Best Effort Routing The protocols in this class ﬁnd available paths from source sensor nodes to the sink on a best-effort basis. The protocols in this class can be further classiﬁed as follows.   Flat Routing: All the sensor nodes in WSN have the same role, i.e., they can be either source or routers.   8 Energy Efﬁcient Routing in Wireless Sensor Networks  137  Fig. 8.3 Taxonomy of energy-efﬁcient routing in wireless sensor networks    Clustering-based Routing: The routing protocols in this class organize the sensor nodes in a group or cluster to achieve load balancing and energy efﬁciency.   Location-based Routing: The sensor nodes take advantage of the available posi- tion information in order to send data in an energy-efﬁcient manner.  Energy-Efﬁcient Reliable Routing Under this class the protocols are more re- silient to route failures either by achieving load balancing of the paths or by re- transmitting the undelivered data. The sensor nodes may suffer from the overhead of maintaining routing tables and other parameters. Energy-efﬁcient reliable routing can be further classiﬁed as follows:   Multipath Routing: The protocols in this class exploit the redundant paths in the networks to deliver the data towards the sink.   Event-to-Sink Routing: In this class, the protocols take advantage of the inherent spatial correlation of the data in forwarding them to the sink.  Energy-Efﬁcient Routing Based on Duty Cycling To save energy, the protocols in this class put the radio in the  low-power  sleep mode whenever communication is not required. Ideally, the radio should be switched off when there is no more data to send receive, and should be activated when new data become available. This mechanism of switching the radio on and off is referred to as Duty Cycling.  Energy-Efﬁcient Routing for Mob