s only on how to optimize the energy constraint. The protocols in this class can be further classiﬁed as Flat, Clustering and Location-based routing protocols. There are many protocols [35] in this class. Next, we present an overview of some of these important protocols.  8.4.1.1 Energy Efﬁcient Flat Routing  Flat routing protocols are those protocols that keep the same criteria for all the nodes in a network, i.e., either source nodes or nodes forwarding the user data. The routing protocols in this category provide a route for each sensor node towards the sink. Table 8.1 compares the Flat routing protocols and techniques for delay sensitive WSN applications.  Generally, there are two types of routing protocol in WSNs, i.e., proactive and reactive. The proactive routing protocols ﬁnd the routes in advance before the user data  the data required by the application  are sent to the sink. The routes are built by exchanging the control data  the data required to update the routing information  between the sensor nodes periodically in order to overcome topological changes. Thus, in proactive routing there is an inherent loss of energy due to these periodic   8 Energy Efﬁcient Routing in Wireless Sensor Networks  139  Table 8.1 Comparison of energy-efﬁcient ﬂat routing protocols  Protocol  Path type  Periodic messages Efﬁciency Type  Based on Dijkstra [32, 33] optimal TORA [6] shortest best energy E-TORA [47] SEER [13] remaining energy HELLO  routing table No No  low medium high medium  proactive reactive reactive reactive proactive  updates. The reactive routing protocols ﬁnd the routes when the user data are avail- able for sending to the sink. Before sending the user data the sensor nodes try to ﬁnd the routes towards sink by using ﬂooding or related techniques. In reactive routing as well there is energy consumption involved by design. The different energy-efﬁcient routing protocols try to optimize the utilization of energy in the network.  To establish routes in WSNs