ncy by exploiting the threshold values. Whenever the sensed attribute parameter has reached its hard threshold value, the node starts transmitting the sensed data. In other case the node remain idle and only senses the environment and saving the energy.  The Adaptive Threshold sensitive Energy Efﬁcient sensor Network  APTEEN  [31] protocol is an improved version of TEEN. It periodically collects data and reacts to time-critical events. After the cluster formation, the CHs broadcast the environmental attributes of interest, the threshold values and transmission schedule to all the nodes in the cluster. Since the environmental data have correlation it is wasteful to forward all the received data from the sensor nodes of the cluster to the sink. Therefore, after cluster formation the data aggregation is performed by the CHs, which saves much energy by sending only the aggregated data. APTEEN is more energy-efﬁcient than TEEN but it is more complex and has higher latency due to aggregation delays.  Extending Lifetime of Cluster Head  ELCH  [27] is yet another cluster-based algorithm. However, the cluster heads are decided on the basis of mutual consent of neighbors through an election process. This protocol has two phases. The ﬁrst phase is the setup procedure when the clusters and the CHs are formed by an election process. The most voted sensor becomes the CH. The second phase is the steady- state phase where the election results are considered to set up clusters, forward user data to CHs and transmitting from CHs to the sink is carried out. The clusters consist of CH and sensor nodes located in a radius less than the radio radius of CH. Then, the Time Division Multiple Access  TDMA  is used for each cluster member to transmit data to the CH. In addition, each CH maintains a table with maximum power for each cluster member. Once the clusters have been organized, the CHs form a multihop routing backbone towards sink. The data are directly sent to CH by its cluster membe