receive the location information of the sink and that of their neighbors. To save energy, SELAR exchanges control messages  HELLO messages  among one hop neighbors only. In addition to that, user data are sent by the sensor nodes by ﬁnding candidate neighbor nodes  with the highest level of energy  in their forwarding zone, where zone is the area formed by the angle α in the direction of the sink and the coverage area of the sending node. The advantage of this protocol is that it always routes the information through the nodes that have the highest energy. The disadvantage is that this protocol is not well suited for dynamic network topology changes.  The Minimum Energy Relay Routing  MERR  [53] protocol calculates the dis- tance between two nodes that are transmitting information. This distance is cal- culated based on the energy consumed on a particular link. When the next hop is decided, the transmitting power is regulated in order to use the minimum energy required for the signal to reach the sensor node. In MERR each sensor node ﬁnds a neighbor node within its maximum transmission range which is closest to the sink. Once the next hop is selected, the sensor node adjusts its transmission power such that the next hop sensor node just receive it. The energy consumption can be min- imized by adjusting the transmission power. MERR performs well when nodes are following a linear topology and they send their information to a single sink. The disadvantage is that it considers its adjacent neighbor for routing and if many sensor nodes are in the vicinity, a lot of energy can be wasted.  Geographic Routing with Environmental Energy Supply  GREES  [49] com- bines geographic and energy-efﬁcient routing by considering the lossy wireless channel with the renewal capability. In GREES, each sensor node locally main- tains its one hop neighbor’s information  i.e., the neighbor location, residual en- ergy, energy harvesting rate, energy consuming rate, and wireless link quality  using HELLO messages. The sensor node forwards the user data progressively towards the sink, while at the same time it tries to balance the energy consumption across all its forwarding neighbor nodes.  8.4.1.4 Discussion  Tables 8.1, 8.2, 8.3 compare the various routing protocols in the best effort routing class for delay sensitive applications.  We observe that for ﬂat routing protocols, E-TORA and SEER are more energy- efﬁcient than the traditional and TORA protocols. Flat routing views WSNs as tra- ditional wired networks where each sensor node requires a path toward the sink. Generally the periodic messages are exchanged to maintain the connectivity across the neighbor nodes which increases the energy consumption by the network.   144  F.K. Shaikh et al.  We observe that maintaining routes for each and every node in the network is cumbersome and not much energy-efﬁcient. Thus, clustering protocols divide the network into clusters to balance the energy consumption. We note that periodic mes- sages are not normally exchanged for routing purposes in WSNs but are used for cluster information and maintenance operations. ELCH and SHPER are the most energy-efﬁcient protocols in this category. LEACH and LEACH-C are good pro- tocols and provide insights how clustering is achieved in WSNs but unfortunately they are not scalable and provide only single hop communication. On the other hand TEEN and APTEEN achieves energy efﬁciency by aggregating the data from sensor nodes at the Cluster Head  CH  and forwarding only the aggregated data.  For location-based routing we observe that MERR and GREES outperform SE- LAR an GEAR in terms of energy efﬁciency. Periodic messages are normally ex- changed by location-based protocols to ﬁnd the location of neighboring nodes and maintain network connectivity. External sensors may be utilized but they tend to be costly and may require more processing at the nodes which can lead to energy drain.  8.4.2 Energy Efﬁcient Reliable Routing for Wireless Sensor  Networks  As the name suggests, the protocols in this category are robust to link failures and ultimately guarantee reliable data routing. Link failures can be mitigated by satis- fying certain requirements such as following routes with low delays or routes that consume the lowest energy or routes where a minimal number of retransmissions occur. This category can be further broken down into multipath-based protocols and Event to Sink  Ev2S  protocols. A brief description of these routing strategies is given in the following sections.  8.4.2.1 Energy Efﬁcient Multipath Routing  Multipath routing is a robust technique and avoids route failures by rerouting us- ing load balancing [44] techniques. Multipath protocols perform well compared to single-path protocols because of their robustness against node failures, congestion and their ability to cope with latency with low overheads. Several multipath routing protocols have been designed in order to guarantee reliable data transfer [35]. In this work, we focus on and compare the major techniques  Fig. 8.4  adapted by the routing protocols to achieve energy efﬁciency  Table 8.4 .  Overlap Multipath  OM : Usually protocols employing the OM technique are reactive in nature, i.e., the route is created when user data need to be transferred. Sensor nodes periodically exchange control data  including energy  among neigh- bors to maintain network connectivity. Each sensor node selects a set of multiple neighbor nodes based on their energy budget. Once the user data are available for sending, the sensor node selects a forwarding node from the set. The selection can   8 Energy Efﬁcient Routing in Wireless Sensor Networks  145  Table 8.4 Comparison of energy-efﬁcient multipath routing approaches  Technique  Path type  Periodic messages  Efﬁciency  Type  Overlap multipath Funnel multipath Disjoint multipath Hierarchical multipath  energy-efﬁcient any energy-efﬁcient energy-efﬁcient  Yes Yes Yes Yes  medium medium low