ious load bal- ancing techniques at the sensor nodes only [35]. Although these techniques help in extending the lifetime of the WSN network, it is becoming a challenge to provide energy-efﬁcient routing on an end-to-end basis as WSNs become an integral part of cyber-physical systems. Furthermore, many routing protocols for WSNs do not adequately investigate the impact of scalability on energy-efﬁciency. Many recently proposed energy-efﬁcient routing protocols are evaluated using various simulation studies. The real deployment scenarios often impose different characteristics that are not really captured in these simulation tests. Thus, evaluating these energy-efﬁcient WSN routing protocols using real testbeds or in real deployment settings can pro- vide a much better insight into the practical performance of these protocols.  In the last few years there has been an increased interest in applications that support the mobility of the users. In contrast, mobile WSNs where single or very few nodes are mobile to assist with the data delivery, the new paradigm may include mobility for all or the majority of sensor nodes. An example of this scenario is the e- health care application where sensors are attached to the patient and the sensor data need to be sent to the doctor continuously. Another example can be VANETs where cars are equipped with sensors which cooperate with each other as the vehicles move to share road safety data. Very little work has been done in this area and a more in- depth analysis and energy-efﬁcient protocols are needed to address the challenges posed by the highly mobile nodes.  8.7 Conclusion  Due to limited battery capabilities, energy efﬁciency has become an important issue for Wireless Sensor Networks  WSNs . Given the cooperative nature of WSN nodes along with the complexity of the operations performed by them we need to design, implement and deploy energy-efﬁcient routing approaches which can guarantee net- work connectivity for WSNs for data delivery.   8 Energy Efﬁcient Routing in Wireless Sensor Networks  153  We have presented a comprehensive taxonomy of recently proposed energy- efﬁcient routing approaches in WSNs based on the types of application supported by WSNs. We discussed the importance of the various approaches based on the appli- cation perspective, i.e., delay sensitive and delay tolerant applications. The results of this work should enable researchers and designers of WSNs to better design and optimize future energy-efﬁcient routing protocols for WSNs.  Acknowledgements We thank the anonymous reviewers for their helpful comments which helped us to improve the quality and presentation of this chapter. Faisal K. Shaikh was partially supported by Mehran University of Engineering and Technology, Jamshoro, Pakistan and National ICT R&D Fund, Ministry of Information Technology, Pakistan under National Grassroots ICT Re- search Initiative. Sherali Zeadally was partially supported by a District of Columbia NASA Space Grant and an NSF TIP grant  Award Number 1036293  during the course of this work.  Appendix: Acronyms  Acknowledgment Adaptive Threshold sensitive Energy Efﬁcient sensor Network Cluster Head Directional Controlled Fusion Distributed hierarchical agglomerative clustering Disjoint Multipath Energy-Aware Routing to Mobile Gateway Energy-efﬁcient Beaconless Geographic Routing with Energy Supply Extending Lifetime of Cluster Head Event to Sink Reliable Transport Energy-aware Temporarily Ordered Routing Algorithm Event to Sink Funnel Multipath Geographic and Energy Aware Routing Generic Information Transport Global Positioning System GRAdient Broadcast Geographic Routing with Environmental Energy Supply Hierarchical Multipath Low Energy Adaptive Clustering Hierarchy  ACK APTEEN CH DCF DHAC DM EARM EBGRES ELCH ESRT ETORA Ev2S FM GEAR GIT GPS GRAB GREES HM LEACH LEACH-C Low Energy Adaptive Clustering Hierarchy Centralized LMR MAC MASP MERR MMSPEED Multi-Path and Multi-SPEED OM RBC  Label-bas