nsors are connecting inanimate daily objects and are building the actual things enabling the ﬁrst Internet of Things services.  Following the American Auto ID research center description of an internet of things and the European CASAGRAS research project terminology [12], things or objects are described as a set of atoms, the atom is the smallest object in the Internet of Things; as could be seen by the nanotechnology which is also one of the enabling technologies of the Internet of Things. Network of atoms combined with network of bits falls into what is named Internet of Things. It will gather a set of objects connected to the network to help in the execution of new services, enabling the smart world. So the atom being the smallest probable object, it is possible to classify objects as follows based on their size and complexity, their moveable aspect and the fact of being animate or inanimate as shown in Fig. 9.4 [12].  In this terminology, classical devices such as PCs, mobile phones are already connected objects using wired or wireless communication. Internet of Things will extend the connectivity and interworking of these current existing objects with new ones connected through the radio sensing or identifying technologies such as sensor networks or RFID networks allowing the development of new services involving in- formation from the environment. This information could be either a simple identiﬁer as with RFID or captured information as with sensors. In other terminologies, com- mon networking devices such as PC, laptop, and mobile phone are not considered as object. Only small devices such as sensors, actuators, RFID added to objects are considered as connected things or objects. But also machines identiﬁed in home net- working; connected consumer electronic devices as smart TV, fridge, light, etc. are connected objects. In this chapter, by “thing” or “object” we refer to the connected daily life and surrounding items using radio connectivity as sensors or R