of Things  IP addresses are identifying the nodes in the Internet and also serve as locators for routing. IPv6 allows larger address space than IPv4. In the Internet of Things a large identiﬁcation space will be needed to cover the identiﬁcation of the tremendous   168  H. Chaouchi et al.  number of connected objects. A speciﬁc semantic of these identiﬁers will follow the application’s need. In the Internet of Things, where objects are addressed via identi- ﬁers stored into tags and interrogated by networked readers, the question of unifying and standardizing the identiﬁer’s size and structure is critical in order to allow large deployment of services relying on these new connected objects. Since RFID tech- nology is naturally used for identiﬁcation, the standardization of the identiﬁer stored in the RFID is the current Internet of Things concern. The same question rises for any addressing schema used in the network of objects. In case that it is IP based, the problem will be more about the semantic of the identiﬁer, scalability of the address- ing space, and the memory size limitation of the devices addressed by the chosen address identiﬁer space.  The term “identiﬁer” is similar with the term “name”. A name does not change with location, in contrast to an “address” which is intended to be used to refer to the location of a thing. IP addresses are used to route packets between end-systems. Emerging Internet of Things service providers expect to rely on a convenient iden- tiﬁer space for the envisioned service, knowing that anything can be assigned an identiﬁer—a physical object, person, place or logical object. A wide variety of ser- vices and applications can be envisaged, once it becomes possible to provide in- formation associated with a tag identiﬁer in different forms  text, audio or image . For example, in a museum, an identiﬁer on a tag attached to a painting could be used to ﬁnd further information on the painting and the artist. In a grocery store, an identiﬁer on a food package could be used to check that the food is safe to eat and not a member of a sample that has been found to be contaminated in some way. Other areas in which identiﬁer-triggered information access could be valuable are in medicine pharmaceuticals, agriculture, libraries, the retail trade, the tourist industry, logistics and supply chain management [20].  So, the major issue to start with in this Internet of Things to maximize its success is the standardization in order to ensure interoperability of the connected objects and nodes in the Internet of Things. As will be presented in Sect. 9.7, this prob- lem is well known in the communication ﬁeld, but it is worsened in the Internet of Things since billion of objects are expected to be connected. It is then important to standardize the object identiﬁer since the objects in the network of objects will be addressed by a unique identiﬁer similarly to IP addresses of connected nodes in the Internet.  EPCglobal has ﬁrst standardized the electronic product code identiﬁer, followed by ISO. In addition to ISO and EPCglobal, the Ubiquitous ID Centre  UIDcentre  has deﬁned a generic identiﬁer called “ucode” which is not only intended to iden- tify physical objects but also extended to places and digital information. ISO has addressed the issue of standardized identiﬁer by considering proprietary propos- als such as EPCglobal and UIDcentre but also offers the possibility to deﬁne other identiﬁers but conform to ISO recommendations. For example, if one might use IP address space for identiﬁcation, and if a device thing has enough memory, one can propose to consider IPv6 address space to be used as identiﬁer space of objects since IPv6 address space is supposed to be large enough to offer up to 223 addresses in a square meter. Unfortunately, deﬁning an identiﬁer is not only about the scalability of   9 Internet of Things: From Real to Virtual World  169  the identiﬁer space but it is also about the structure and the meaning semantic of the identiﬁer. Also it is important that an identiﬁer plays only the role of identiﬁcation, so that even if the identiﬁed objects are mobile, the identiﬁer remains the same. In the IP communication model, IP addresses play two roles: from a network point of view, they act as a locator for routing and from an application point of view; they identify hosts for the duration of a communications session. This dual role is seen to be problematic due to increasing demands for mobility and the multi-homing of end-systems. For this reason the Internet Research Task Force  IRTF  and the Inter- net Engineering Task Force  IETF  have developed the Host Identity Protocol  HIP  which deﬁnes Host Identiﬁers that can perform the identiﬁer role of the IP address, leaving the IP address to act solely as a locator for routing. These Host Identiﬁers of HIP protocol could potentially be used as another type of identiﬁer in the Internet of Things under the condition to respect the ISO standard and being capable to carry the semantic of the identiﬁer needed by the intended Internet of Thing application. For instance, a EPC global identiﬁer contains information on the product itself, the manufacturer, etc. IPv6 address informs us about the network preﬁx and the address of the node, this is not containing the semantic expected by the new identiﬁers. A mapping between IP addresses and the things identiﬁers will be possible in case of using IP network to interconnect these identiﬁed and connected objects to the Internet.  As mentioned earlier identifying, addressing and naming the objects in the In- ternet of Things service are very important. As for IP-based devices, IP addressing and naming are used to enable the routing and the network resource location in the network. Address resolution protocol  ARP  and name resolution using the IP Do- main Name Service  DNS  are used in IP networks to offer different services such as World wide web, email, ﬁle transfer, Voice over IP, etc. Some existing IP services such as domain name service are considered in handling the identiﬁer resolution to a name in certain Internet of Things services such as product tracking where and electronic identiﬁer of the product will call the web page of the manufacturer and all the history of this product manufacturing and shipping. This service is named by EPCglobal ONS or Object Name Service. In order to use ONS for all the emerging Internet of Things services orchestrating identiﬁers, certain problems such as the scalability of this naming service also have to be addressed, since we are expecting billions of objects tagged with identiﬁers. Other non-technical issues related to ONS such as the governance of this ONS are also important. As for the DNS root which is hosted in United States, ONS system will also have an ONS root, and Europe would like to host it [11]. Using DNS approach in certain Internet of Thing services raises the term World Object Web as the application running over the network of objects or web of objects similarly to World Wide Web running over the network of IP nodes; the Internet. Figure 9.5 shows an example of ONS usage to retrieve a manufacturer web page.  An example of ONS usage for other Internet of Thing application than product tracking was presented in the Internet of Things conference in 2008 [6], it was about helping a blind person in automatic reading of a book tagged with an RFID where he can put it on a reader connected to a computer. As soon as the reader gets the   170  Fig. 9.5 Object name service architecture [12]  H. Chaouchi et al.  identiﬁer of the tagged book, a web page appears in the screen starting reading the book; it is the application developed and running at the Internet side. Most of the current RFID-based applications will be based on this touch a tag and trigger an application relying on the resolution of the RFID object identiﬁer through the ONS [15].  9.5 Enabling Technologies of Internet of Things 