ice [9]. More applications and services will emerge taking advantage of the RFID technology and more research effort is currently ongoing in RFID area. For instance, in [22] the authors introduce the possibility to use the RFID technology to improve the wireless indoor positioning, and in [23] the authors pro- pose to improve the IP mobility by boosting the movement detection of the mobile node using the RFID technology.  9.5.2 Sensing and Actuating Technology  As mentioned earlier, an RFID mainly answers the question “What, Which, Where”, while the sensor answers the question: “How”.  A sensor is an electronic device that detects senses or measures physical stimuli from the real world environment, converts signals from stimuli into analogue or digital form. Some sensors are also providing actuation functionality; it is named sensor actuator.   mechanical  e.g. position, force, pressure, etc. ,   thermal  e.g. temperature, heat ﬂow ,   electrostatic or magnetic ﬁelds,  Sensors can be classiﬁed according to the parameters they measure [18]:   174  H. Chaouchi et al.    radiation intensity  e.g. electromagnetic, nuclear ,   chemical  e.g. humidity, ion, gas concentration ,   biological  e.g. toxicity, presence of biological organisms , and so on.   military—enemy tracking or battleﬁeld surveillance; Many scientiﬁc and research groups are working to develop more efﬁcient and fea- sible sensor networks. The main technical constraints are:   power, size, memory and storage capacity,   trade-off between power and size,   interference, communication model,   the environment where the sensors are deployed  underwater, land ﬁeld, etc.   Many applications of sensors can be envisioned in different domains; military environment, healthcare, construction, commercial applications, remote monitoring of the temperature of products, home applications such as smart home, and so on.  9.5.3 Other Technologies  Emerging technologies will bring about more possibilities to develop new Int