work of objects to the Internet.  9.6.2 Object or Network of Objects to Other Networks  First generation of Internet of Things services that are close to the market will rely on these new objects connected to the network via technologies such as RFID  NFC for secure short range reading applications , sensors to introduce the real world in- formation into the network to be processed by these new applications. In this case, most of the interconnection effort will be made at the gateway point attaching the objects to the network. This gateway can be connected either by wired or wire- less mobile communication system. Other technologies that are already used for different applications might be mentioned, such as possible technologies for new Internet of Things services to connect the object at one hop to the network such as are smart cards for automatic payment, location technologies  Real Time Location System  RTLS , Global Positioning System  GPS , etc.  to enable location-based services and also tracking, bar code  2D  for item tracking etc.  9.7 About Internet in the Internet of Things  Connecting objects of different technologies and different communicating models raise the question of end-to-end communication between heterogeneous systems. IP or Internet Protocol has in the past answered this same question where it suc- ceeded to interconnect heterogeneous networks with different physical and link lay- ers transporting different type of trafﬁc through the network IP layer by introducing the new addressing space; the IP addressing and the routing schema that allows to reach any connected node to the IP network as long as it has a routable IP address. In the Internet of Things there are more issues than heterogeneity in connecting the new objects and also interconnecting the network of objects to the existing network, so we need to:   design or adapt an appropriate communication model to set up the network of objects,   176  H. Chaouchi et al.    design or adapt the connectivity of this network of objects to the current Inter- net where some of the Internet of Things functionalities will be hosted such as information data bases, applications, actuation commands, etc.  Regarding the communication model to set up the network of objects, several issues need to be considered. An important issue is the available resources offered by the objects such as battery, memory, and processing capability. For instance tiny objects such as sensors or RFIDs have limited resources. However, other objects in home networking application such as smart TV or smart fridge might have enough resources. Usually when there are enough resources, IP model meaning addressing and routing could be considered as the communication model to set up this network of objects as long as it respects the application trafﬁc requirement. Another issue is the heterogeneity of the connecting objects. Again the IP model could be con- sidered to handle the connectivity of heterogeneous nodes and networks, but this will be possible only if there are enough resources. Tiny objects such as sensors, RFID, etc. show clearly the limitation of the current IP model especially with the energy consumption, thus new adaptation of this model has already started in the IETF meaning that IP model might be used to connect some objects in the Inter- net of Things such as sensors under certain parameters. In fact, the IETF 6lowpan working group has produced an IPv6-based model to satisfy the sensor environment requirement over IEEE 802.15.4 [2]; also the ROLL working group has looked at how to adapt the routing process to these new environments and came up with the RPL protocol [8]. IP for Smart Objects  IPSO  Alliance which is a group of more than a 100 industrials is also looking at the adaptation of IP to these smart and tiny devices [17]. Note that sensor networks are gaining more and more attention from the industry since they can help in building new services and applications in differ- ent domains such as health, agriculture, transport, in any place, therefore creating new revenues and so does the RFID technology. But before developing more appli- cations and considering more and more objects, it is necessary to avoid problems such as scalability, complexity, and heterogeneity in communication. Internet  cur- rent future  model is considered as one possible communication framework for the emerging Internet of Things-based services at least in the short and medium term. But to be more generic, we should consider the word Internet in the “Internet of Things” as INTERNET working of objects, meaning transport capability, hetero- geneity management, easy object network management, easy services development, and deployment capability. This could be realized by an adapted version of the IP model or totally new communication model, which is highly expected by the Future Internet Network worldwide initiative [3, 4].  Regarding the interconnection of the network of objects to other networks such as existing Internet, it will depend on the purpose of this interconnection. We know that Internet of Things applications will orchestrate functionalities from the current In- ternet network to allow the transport of the generated trafﬁc of the Internet of Things nodes and also allow the service access locally or remotely. Another functionality is related to this network of objects management with simple and known tools lo- cally or remotely. Consequently, network of objects using IP model or any other communication model within objects’ network has to be connected to the Internet   9 Internet of Things: From Real to Virtual World  177  Fig. 9.7 ITU Internet of Things reference model [20]  through some speciﬁc gateways, as shown in Fig. 9.13, allowing the communication between the network of objects and the worldwide Internet in order to beneﬁt from its existing tools and data transport and management. The gateway will be close to the tag reading or the sensor to handle the transport of this information on the IP side. For instance some command can be sent from an Internet node toward the network of objects. In this case the Internet model should be adapted to support the properties of this new trafﬁc coming from, and going to this network of objects.  In order to understand the new trafﬁc properties, it is important to look at the functionalities required by the Internet of Things service. Since these emerging ser- vices intend to introduce information from the real world environment in the net- work to be processed and then automate some tasks in the real world, identifying, sensing and actuating are the major building blocks of an Internet of Things-based service. All these functionalities will generate trafﬁc that need to be transported from one point to another of the network. For instance, the identifying process will generate the identiﬁer information using the current identiﬁer technology, the RFID that will be used by the application service located in the network. The RFID reader can be directly connected to the network or multi-hop away from it. When using sensors, sensing information is generated by the sensor and has to be transported to the application process through other sensors; multi-hop transport model or one hop away from the node running the application. The actuation process might be trig- gered locally or remotely also through a network and will need an efﬁcient network transport to satisfy the trafﬁc requirement of the actuation service. In any case, there is a need for efﬁcient information transfer taking into account the limited resources of the current object technologies such as RFID tags and wireless sensors among other requirements.  The ﬁrst proposed architecture by the ITU is shown in Fig. 9.7 where IP network is selected to transport the identiﬁcation or the sensing information at the edge of the Internet, and it shows a need for an interface to the transport and the service planes of the Internet or NGN  Next Generation Network . But IP network will not be the only possibility to support the transport of the information generated by these   178  H. Chaouchi et al.  new Internet of Thing-based services. This is a short and medium term view of the Internet of Things’ applications that are close to the market. A Future network model might emerge to handle the new requirement of the Internet of Things services and trafﬁc transport based on these tiny devices suffering from lack of energy, memory and processing resources. More adaptation and autonomic behavior will be included in the new communication model.  As mentioned by the ITU in Fig. 9.7, the industry’s point of view is considering IP and Next Generation Networks  NGN  in the short and medium term as the net- work support for Internet of Things services. This is seen as a natural step forward to the convergence process in telecommunication seeking the All IP model. Based on this fact, certain Internet of Things services might be deployed very quickly as soon as some security related issues are solved such as privacy related to RFID deployment. These close to the market services are those that are using Internet to run the application that orchestrates the objects connected to the existing net- work nodes. In this context, the user interface to these new services will be either related to the ﬁxed or mobile networks. The actuation process might be triggered locally if it is programmed so, or remotely through a given network based on a cer- tain terminal. For instance through a mobile phone connected to the emerging 4G network or any other wireless or mobile network and this has attracted a particular interest from mobile network operators and mobile devices manufacturers designing smart phones with RFID reader capability. In fact emerging mobile phones could be used to trigger some Internet of Things services remotely, and also interact locally through new reading interface with the objects added to the real environment.  Following the industry approach where the convergence to All IP continues with the new Internet of Things services, it is then important to recall the convergence path to All IP. As summarized in Fig. 9.8, the convergence in telecommunication can be seen from different angles. The value chain actors are initially telecommunica- tion, Internet, and broadcasting operators to offer speciﬁc services as regards voice, data, and media, respectively. The convergence will impact these speciﬁc operators to offer all the three services at the same time on the same network. In fact the con- vergence in telecommunication will end up by designing the same container named IP packet to transport different information  voice, data, media  in the same network known today as IP network. This transported information has speciﬁc properties sat- isﬁed by the corresponding network before the convergence and by IP network after the convergence since IP completed with the QoS architecture can offer these mul- tiple services in the same packet switched network, the Internet. Consequently, the convergence impacts also the corresponding markets; communication, information, and entertainment, respectively. Finally, the convergence impacts the design of de- vices or interfaces to the corresponding services; terminal  telephone , computer, and home consumer electronic appliances  e.g. TV  where the convergence pushes to design an all in one device to get access to all these services no matter which phys- ical network we are connected too, ﬁxed or mobile. This has also an impact on the service management from the network side, the convergence in telecommunication came with a service oriented approach where a service abstraction layer is intro- duced and the access to a service has to be transparent from the physical transport   9 Internet of Things: From Real to Virtual World  179  Fig. 9.8 Convergence in telecommunication [13]  of the information generated by this service. IP Multimedia Subsystem IMS and ﬁxed mobile convergence is a good example of a service abstraction layer, where it is possible to get a service  e.g. telephony  no matter which physical network the user is connected to thanks to the SIP  Session Initiation Protocol  signaling that in- troduces a new user identiﬁer to be mapped with the location of the user at anytime and anywhere.  All IP, which is one concrete answer to the need to convergence in telecommu- nication, has started with the need to optimize network resources of ﬁxed telephony network based on a circuit switching model. Initially, there were speciﬁc and ded- icated networks with speciﬁc nodes and linking technologies to offer one speciﬁc service. In fact, the ﬁrst designed network was meant to be used only for telephony; it is the ﬁxed telecommunication network. The data transport network came mainly with Internet network and ﬁnally the television application was deployed in another speciﬁc network, the TV broadcast network. Designing a speciﬁc network for a spe- ciﬁc service is deﬁnitely not optimizing the usage of the resources, and using an end-to-end physical circuit for only one communication, even if there is no voice transported, is not optimizing the resource utilization.  One of the major revolutions in networking is the move from the circuit switched networking to the packet switched networking, known also as IP network, Internet, TCP IP network, data network, or packet network. IP being the de facto protocol to interconnect heterogeneous networks, added by a set of other protocols for con- trol as well as for management, makes it the convergence vector in the evolving telecommunication systems. IP was threatened at different times, ATM as a packet switching network but too complex and expensive, switched Ethernet was not scal- able. IP has won due to its simplicity, less investment, scalability, and multi usage to carry different services relying on the virtual circuit switching over packet switching   180  H. Chaouchi et al.  Fig. 9.9 Telecom value chain evolution [13]  network. The convergence to what is called All IP can then be seen at different lay- ers, the transport, the management, the control, and application development; this is all to maximize the revenues of the telecom actors of the value chain.  The value chain is also impacted in this convergence path as shown in Fig. 9.9, since initially it was linear where each actor in the value chain has his own devel- opment and market, and now after the convergence the value chain is non-linear; most of the actors are moving to this user centric approach where it is all about designing new services to be transported by this unique and stable network, the All IP. New services will emerge with the Internet of Things and will also impact the value chain where some services will be object centric, meaning that the interaction of these new services will be based on object-to-object with no human interaction. The trafﬁc generated by these object-to-object oriented services will need to match a certain business model with new actors.  The path to convergence continues with the Internet of Things, and raises the question if IP will be fully adopted to support Internet of Things services, or if it will be used only partially. As shown in Fig. 9.10, the Internet of Things will impact the convergence in telecommunication at different angles  By adding Internet of Things services in the network, it will impact ﬁrst the value chain, since new actors will be introduced in the telecommunication chain. For instance the actor of product identiﬁcation since RFID technology is part of the Internet of Things enabling technologies. As shown in Fig. 9.11, sensing and actuating designers, automation process developers will join the existing telecom value chain with wired and wireless communication providers in order to develop Internet of Things services.  By introducing IoT in the convergence path, it will impact the selection of the information container  IP?  that will transport in the converged network the Internet of Things generated information. Knowing that Internet of Things services will in- troduce mainly new functionalities; identifying, sensing, actuating, we need to ask   9 Internet of Things: From Real to Virtual World  181  Fig. 9.10 Internet of Things in the convergence path [13]  Fig. 9.11 New actors in the IoT value Chain [20]  two questions regarding keeping IP as the convergence vector. First, what is inter- esting for IP to be used in Internet of Things? Internet model might be considered immediately in connecting the objects  with enough resources  for its capabilities of naming and addressing, routing, scalability, easy deployment and management, easy application development, easy naming, addressing, name and address resolu- tion, etc. [17]. Second, what are the limitations in using IP for Internet of Things services? In the current object technologies we can mention resources limitation of the objects: battery, memory, processing. Also, IP has to support the trafﬁc proper- ties of the introduced functionalities mainly identifying, sensing, and actuating.  In Fig. 9.10, we add “IoT information” next to “voice, data, media” knowing that Internet of Thing generated information might be an “identiﬁer, a sensing in- formation, an actuation order, etc.”, this type of information might have different QoS properties and there is a need to study the trafﬁc model of this new type of   182  H. Chaouchi et al.  information and analyze if IP as it is today can transport this information by re- specting the trafﬁc properties. For instance a remote actuation might have higher priority than existing voice trafﬁc due to the urgent character of a given Internet of Thing application. For delay tolerant Internet of Thing applications, the question will be more about the overhead of the IP model compared to the Internet of Thing generated data. It is then important to know if 