 eases the design and access to the applications of the IoT. Most of these architectures follow the Service Oriented Architecture  SOA  approach which is mainly offering the possibility to compose in a modular way the functionalities necessary to build a service or an application.  The adoption of the SOA principles as stated in [10] as shown in Fig. 9.12 allows for decomposing complex and monolithic systems into applications consisting of an ecosystem of simpler and well-deﬁned components.  Note that other architectures are possible, such as a resource oriented approach where speciﬁc gateways have to be developed in order to orchestrate the objects communication to offer the intended service  application to the user [24].   9 Internet of Things: From Real to Virtual World  183  Fig. 9.12 SoA architecture of Internet of Things [10]  Fig. 9.13 Internet of Things abstract view  Following the convergence path in Fig. 9.10 from the service access point of view, we might follow the service oriented approach where IoT services should be independent from the network transport part, so that in case of changing the trans- port network, the service will always be accessible, as in IMS approach. This might sound as a new step in the convergence of networks to the All IP convergence where a service oriented approach is followed in order to get a service no matter the net- work transport. It is important to have an abstraction layer for Internet of Things services to be developed independently from the transport network, meaning that it should be independent if the network is ﬁxed or mobile, IP based or post IP based or Future network based. What is important is to be capable to reuse the developed In- ternet of Things services over any transporting network and also offering the service no matter which transport network is used by the network of objects. Our abstract view of the Internet of Thing service oriented approach is shown in Fig. 9.13.   184  H. Chaouchi et al.  Fig. 9.