actors of this concept are the pervasive and ubiquitous deployment of a wide variety of wireless devices  such as Radio-Frequency IDentiﬁcation  RFID  tags, sensors, actuators, mobile phones  around us. Many of these devices are able to interact communicate with each other to reach common goals. A major driving force behind this promising paradigm is the ability to integrate several different devices, technologies, platforms, and communi- cations solutions. We focus on an analysis of the communication issues that support the IoT ecosystem. First, we review recent standardization efforts on the IoT pro- tocol stack. We compare four recently proposed protocol stacks implemented on resource constrained devices in the IoT. We analyze different types of communi- cation, such as device-to-device, device-to human and device-to-data storage, that need to be supported in the IoT ecosystem. Based on this analysis, we highlight challenges and constraints that need to be addressed at the inter-domain communi- cation level when developing current and future IoT solutions and applications. We also propose solutions that can be developed to address the challenges. Finally, we discuss the impact of emerging technologies on the IoT ecosystem.  O. Bello  B   School of Information Technology, Monash University, South Africa Campus, Ruimsig, South Africa e-mail: oladay@ieee.org  S. Zeadally Department of Computer Science and Information Technology, University of the District of Columbia, Washington, DC 20008, USA e-mail: szeadally@udc.edu  N. Chilamkurti et al.  eds. , Next-Generation Wireless Technologies, Computer Communications and Networks, DOI 10.1007 978-1-4471-5164-7_10,   Springer-Verlag London 2013  189   190  10.1 Introduction  O. Bello and S. Zeadally  The Internet of Things  IoT  is said to be an extension of the Internet into the physi- cal world, in which physical entities  objects devices things  are interconnected [1]. There are already many more “things” than “people” and the integration of the Inter- net with the physical world will be a challenge for the future Internet technology [2]. This will be a challenge because the Internet has been operating with human in- tervention, and the integration of the physical world with the Internet requires a self-conﬁguring network in which devices may have to take decisions and operate without human intervention. The challenges that will need to be addressed include dealing with the identiﬁcation of devices, mobility of wireless devices, providing security and quality communication between devices. The IoT paradigm will make it possible for virtually any device  “thing”  around us to exchange information and work in synergy with each other in order to dramatically increase the quality of our lives [2]. Intelligent day-to-day devices will inter-operate and exchange information between each other seamlessly via the Internet. These devices have sensing capabil- ities and are able to initiate communication or request data to take decisions  human guided or non-human guided decisions . Communication could be device-to-device and device-to human and device simultaneously.  There are several deﬁnitions for the IoT in general. Basically all the deﬁnitions share the fact that the main components of the IoT are the devices or objects, the wired wireless networks and the Internet; and the information knowledge  data  storage facility. Devices are the major building blocks of an IoT ecosystem [3]. They bridge the real world of physical entities with the digital world of the Internet. They have monitoring, sensing, actuation, computation, and processing capabilities. Devices can be classiﬁed as sensors, tags or actuators. Sensors provide information about the physical entity they monitor. The information from sensors can be stored for later retrieval. Tags are specialized sensors known as readers which enable iden- tiﬁcation processes. Actuators can modify the physical state of a physical entity. However, some actual devices are a combination of several of these types. For in- stance, a sensor node often contains both sensors  e.g., movement sensing  as well as actuators  e.g., room-light switch  [3]. The devices are visible and traceable  i.e. they can be monitored and tracked . In addition, the status and current location of the devices can be obtained because they are addressable and have unique identities within the IoT. They are able to interact with each other, access each other’s infor- mation, store, and retrieve data via the Internet in order to create information for different purposes.  The wired or wireless networks include the autonomous ﬁeld networks and the wide area networks. The smart day to day devices in the IoT form part of the short range ﬁeld networks that exist autonomously. These autonomous ﬁeld networks are seamlessly interconnected together via any available long range wired or wireless access network which facilitates access to information available through the Inter- net. Examples of ﬁeld networks are the Radio-Frequency IDentiﬁcation  RFID  networks, where RFID tags, labels, and readers are the devices, wireless sensor networks with sensors and actuators as the devices, and vehicular networks with   10 Communication Issues in the Internet of Things  IoT   191  cars as the devices. Other ﬁeld networks include WiFi  Wireless Fidelity  networks, Bluetooth or ZigBee, where devices may be smart mobile phone, laptops, and home appliances. The third component of the IoT is the information data storage facil- ity including cloud computing environments or a data repository available via the Internet.  Some popular applications areas of the IoT include: smart grid  automatic me- ter reading , home automation, intelligent transport systems, vehicle monitoring and tracking, industrial applications such as inventory, supply chain, retail, logis- tics, healthcare, personal, and public security, and agriculture. References [2, 4, 5], and [6] provide detailed descriptions of these IoT application areas.  Though various research efforts within the academia and industry are actively working on the IoT concept, yet the lack of standards on the architecture of the IoT is deterring major developments. The current status quo is that there is an intranet of things where many islands of ﬁeld networks exist in silos with each providing solutions for different IoT applications. Thus there are only several decentralized architectures and no unifying architecture yet for the IoT. It is explicit that a major attribute of the IoT will be the heterogeneity of network technologies and the hetero- geneity of devices. Another major attribute is the interoperability between network technologies and between devices. Interoperability is the ability of devices or net- works to provide service to and receive services from other devices or networks [7]. These services enable the devices to effectively operate together and collaborate to achieve some common goal in the IoT. The common goal could be that a major decision needs to be taken in the healthcare application or the smart grid system and it requires retrieving information from other devices located elsewhere within the IoT ecosystem. It could also be the case that we need to provide information or data that have been requested. It is expected that the IoT will encompass different types of device. These devices will belong to different ﬁeld networks and operate using different networking standards. In addition, these devices and networks will be ex- pected inter-operate with each other. These two attributes increase the challenge to provide seamless communications within the IoT ecosystem. Efforts that success- fully address the challenging communication issues within the IoT will enable the full beneﬁts of IoT applications to be reaped through successful worldwide and in- teroperable deployments [8]. We therefore focus on major communication issues within the IoT ecosystem to achieve its beneﬁts in a broader context.  Since the advent of the IoT concept, several authors have presented surveys on IoT. For example, Atzori et al. in [9] presented a general survey on the Internet of Things. The authors elaborated extensively on the applications of the IoT and cov- ered issues related to standardization, addressing networking and security privacy in IoT. Atzori et al. discussed issues that need to be addressed to make the IoT concept a success. However, our work takes the survey on IoT further by focus- ing speciﬁcally on the communication issues in the Internet of Things. The goal of this chapter is to provide comprehensive information on the communication issues within the IoT  e.g. device-to-device or device-to-human communication . In partic- ular, we present detailed information on the IoT communication protocol stack, the   192  O. Bello and S. Zeadally  Table 10.1 Standardization efforts for the IoT Layer  Standard  Application layer  Transport layer  Network layer  Adaptation layer  Medium Access Control  MAC  layer Physical layer  Constrained Application Protocol  CoAP , Hyper Text Transfer Protocol  HTTP  Transmission Control Protocol  TCP , User Datagram Protocol  UDP  Internet Engineering Task Force Routing Protocol for Low Power  IETF RPL  Internet Engineering Task Force IPv6 over Low power Wireless Personal Area Network  IETF 6LoWPAN  IEEE 802.15.4e IEEE 802.15.4-2006  envisaged communication types, and communication trends within the IoT ecosys- tem. In addition, we also discuss some of the challenges and research opportunities at the inter-domain communication level of the IoT ecosystem.  The rest of the chapter is organized as follows. In Sect. 10.2, we present a re- view of the standardization efforts on the IoT protocol stack. Section 10.3 discusses a generic IoT communication protocol stack and compares a few recently pro- posed protocol stack models that have been implemented on constrained devices. In Sect. 10.4, we prese