with RFDs or other FFDs. FFDs man- age the network and route messages. To keep the RFDs from colliding with each other, FFDs deﬁne ﬁxed, predictable slots for data transmission with the use of a synchronization schedule. An RFD can communicate only with an FFD and cannot become a network coordinator. An RFD is intended for extremely simple applica- tions such as a light switch or a passive infrared sensor. These devices do not have the need to send large amounts of data and may only associate with a single FFD at a time and thus use minimal resources and memory capacity.  As shown in Fig. 10.1, the physical layer provides two services: the PHY data service and the PHY management service. The PHY management service interfaces to the Physical Layer Management Entity  PLME  Service Access Point  SAP   known as the PLME-SAP . The PHY data service enables the transmission and reception of PHY Protocol Data Units  PPDUs  across the physical radio channel. Likewise, the MAC sublayer provides two services: the MAC data service and the MAC management service interfacing to the MAC subLayer Management Entity  MLME  Service Access Point  SAP   known as MLME-SAP . The MAC data ser- vice enables the transmission and reception of MAC Protocol Data Units  MPDUs  across the PHY data service [11].  The PHY layer is responsible for the activation and deactivation of the radio transceiver, Energy Detection  ED  within the current channel, Link Quality In- dicator  LQI  for received packets, channel selection and Clear Channel Assess- ment  CCA . It also enables data transmission and reception across the physical medium [11]. The MAC sublayer is responsible for handling all access to the phys- ical medium using the Carrier Sense Multiple Access with Collision Avoidance  CSMA-CA  mechanism for channel access. It generates network beacons if the device is a coordinator and supports device security. In addition, it provides syn- chronization to network beacons, handles, and maintains the Guaranteed Time Slot  GTS  mechanism, performs frame validation, frame delivery acknowledgement, association, and disassociation services.  The IEEE802.15.4e standard deﬁnes the MAC amendment to the IEEE802.15.4- 2006 standard. The major enhancements and functionality added by the 802.15.4e standard is Time Synchronized Channel Hopping  TSCH , which signiﬁcantly in- creases robustness against external interference and persistent multi-path fading.   194  O. Bello and S. Zeadally  Fig. 10.1 IEEE802.15.4-2006 PHY and MAC layers [11]  TSCH allows nodes to send successive packets on different frequencies using a pseudo-random hopping pattern [13] with nodes being synchronized on a com- mon timing pattern. IEEE802.15.4e does not change the data frames format of the IEEE802.15.4-2006, but redeﬁnes the acknowledgment frame and does not use bea- con frames. Time correction is used by a sender node to synchronize the acknowl- edgment received from the receiver.  10.2.2 Adaptation Layer  6LoWPAN   The Internet Protocol Version 6  IPv6  over Low power Wireless Personal Area Networks  6LoWPAN  concept originated from the idea that “the Internet Proto- col could and should be applied even to the smallest devices” [14]. 6LoWPAN is a protocol that enables IPv6 packets to be carried over LoWPANs, speciﬁcally IEEE 802.15.4.6. A Low-Power Wireless Personal Area Network  LoWPAN  is a simple low cost communication network that allows wireless connectivity for applications with limited power and throughput requirements [14]. If IP can be applied to small devices then these low-power devices with limited processing capabilities can par- ticipate in the Internet of Things.   10 Communication Issues in the Internet of Things  IoT   195  The 6LowPAN technology adopts PHY and MAC layer standards of IEEE802. 15.4, and IPv6 is chosen as the networking technology. Since the payload length supported by MAC in IPv6 is much bigger than the one provided by 6LowPAN lower layers, to implement the seamless connection of MAC layer and network layer, 6LowPAN working group adds an adaptation layer between the MAC layer and the network layer. The adaptation layer helps to achieve the header compression, fragmentation, and reassembly and mesh route forwarding [14]. As stated in [15], interoperability is one of the very basic requirements of providing IP connectivity to 6LoWPAN.  10.2.3 Network Layer  Routing   The Internet Engineering Task Force  IETF  IPv6 Routing Protocol for Low Power and Lossy Networks  RPL  is a routing protocol designed for Low Power and Lossy Wireless Networks  LLNs . A particular instantiation of LLN will be the LoW- PANs [16]. LoWPANs are formed by devices that comply with the IEEE 802.15.4 standard [11]. LLNs consist of constrained nodes with limited processing power, memory, and energy. The nodes are interconnected by links, which may be char- acterized by high loss rates, low data rates and instability [17]. RPL is designed with a consideration to practically support the implementation of IPv6 on devices which operate under severe resource constraints. RPL supports the use of multi- ple paths, where duplicated trafﬁc may be sent along diverse paths. It also supports advanced features such as Class of Service  CoS -based routing, or simple load bal- ancing among a set of paths. Load balancing could be useful when the network needs to spread trafﬁc load and avoid fast energy depletion on some nodes. The design of RPL also supports constraint-based routing based on a set of routing met- rics. Trafﬁc may be directed along the appropriate constrained path based on trafﬁc marking within the IPv6 header. Nodes running RPL can autonomously and inde- pendently discover their network topology, compute and install routes, without re- quiring any further administrative interaction. RPL provides efﬁcient routing paths for three trafﬁc patterns namely, multipoint-to-point, point-to-multipoint, and point- to-point trafﬁc in LLNs [18]. RPL uses a form of