n the devices can be based on different protocols and require additional processing at the gateways. The nodes that constitute the network are limited in terms of resources such as computational power, memory, energy, and data rate [3]. The characteristics of each network can have a signiﬁcant impact on the overall end- to-end communication.   Unconstrained Networks: These are networks that are of high resources capacity, coverage, transfer rates and of different technologies and architectures [1]. An unconstrained network connects several constrained networks and retrieves data from the constrained networks via the IoT gateways.   Gateway: The gateway is the core network element within the IoT. It facilitates the communication and data exchanges between devices. It can handle incoming and outgoing trafﬁc of the unconstrained and constrained networks. IoT gateways have the interface of the constrained and the unconstrained networks. They under- stand the addressing format between these networks. The Internet and WAN are networks that enable the connection of devices in different constrained networks and the collection and storage of data from the devices at the management level.  This work discusses the communication issues  as depicted in Fig. 10.7  with a focus on how data trafﬁc will be exchanged at the inter-domain communication sub-level. According to [8], the IoT is expected to interconnect an incredibly high number of devices. These devices will initiate communication through the creation of data con- tent  generation of data trafﬁc , retrieval of stored data content  create a demand for data trafﬁc , and the exchange of data. The trafﬁc generated as a result of the com- munication could be for the purpose of fulﬁlling the major requests from devices in varying IoT applications areas  e.g. healthcare, transport, or logistics applications . Therefore, it is pertinent to study the manner in which the network resources will be managed among the trafﬁc generated. As stated in [9], diverse trafﬁc will be gener- ated within the IoT and since it is expected that the pattern of such data trafﬁc will be signiﬁcantly different from those observed in the current Internet, the charac- teristics of the trafﬁc is completely unknown. The trafﬁc pattern complexity within the IoT arises from the fact that the large amount of data trafﬁc that will traverse the network will be generated by heterogeneous devices which have been deployed for different IoT applications areas such as the smart grid, telemetry, and healthcare applications.   10 Communication Issues in the Internet of Things  IoT   209  As mentioned earlier, one of the major challenges of communication within the IoT is the co-existence of heterogeneous technologies in terms of the devices and the networks. These technologies are expected to be able to inter-operate seam- lessly. Thus, the IoT has to be able to support interoperability between existing and emerging technologies.  Due to the existence of several types of IoT application, diverse communication trends also exist in the IoT. These trends, which are presented in [2] are analyzed  in Table 10.5  in terms of the IoT network elements that will be involved, the purpose of the communication, and the type of communication.  Trafﬁc is generated for different purposes  as outlined in Table 10.5  and the information or data communicated for these purposes could be stored data or real- time data. The communication process in IoT generates different types of trafﬁc  as shown in Fig. 10.8 . Before an interaction can exchange, retrieve or store informa- tion, a series of requests and responses are performed between the devices involved. Such interactions could be event-driven or polling-based. An interaction would be event-driven if it is triggered by the occurrence of a particular event, and it will be polling-based if it takes place in predeﬁned time intervals [5]. Such information can generate different types of trafﬁc with varying delay or throughput depending on whether the trafﬁc is generated by a time-critical or life-critical application  e.g., obtaining real time health information of a patient . Signaling operations are exe- cuted before request and response communication messages are exchanged between devices in the IoT ecosystem as depicted in Fig. 10.9.  10.4.2 Inter-domain Communication Within the IoT: Challenges  and Opportunities  In this section, we present some of the issues, challenges, and opportunities at the inter-domain communication level within the IoT ecosystem that we have identiﬁed.  10.4.2.1 Lack of a Standardized Framework for the IoT Protocol Stack  The lack of a standard for the IoT protocol stack leads to incompatible products and applications for the IoT. Moreover, the lack of standard is also a barrier to the integration of several IoT technologies into a homogeneous IoT ecosystem. Several recent efforts have proposed IoT frameworks and architectures, but there is still no universal agreement on a uniﬁed, standard architecture. The number of communica- tion technologies, from high speed backbone networks to access technologies such as WiFi or Bluetooth and data gathering technologies such as sensor networks con- tinue to proliferate at a fast pace. This trend is likely to continue and has prompted the emergence of the IoT concept [42]. Therefore, a pragmatic approach to the de- velopment of standards, architectures, and protocol that can handle the diversity in the IoT ecosystem is needed.   210  O. Bello and S. Zeadally  Table 10.5 Communication trends in the IoT ecosystem  Type of communication  Intermediary Agent  IA   Purpose  Intra-domain Device-to-device on the same network  Sink Cluster head Access Point. In the case of multihop, other devices will be the IA    Communication to gather information   Communication about the state of a de- vice  Inter-domain Device-to-device on another network without human intervention  IoT gateway  Device-to-device 