dressed. The IoT paradigm will compose of diverse devices operating with varying communication standards, thus communi- cation protocols that will enable inter-domain communication and interoperability among all devices are required. In some cases, the communication protocol must have security features, be energy efﬁcient and also have localization or distance   212  O. Bello and S. Zeadally  measurement capabilities [39]. Protocols are also needed to provide and support reliable message delivery mechanisms which can be used by the IoT applications that require it [5]. Since the IoT ecosystem will include several constrained devices and communication between the devices can be based on different protocols, it may be desirable to develop open and generic communication protocols. These protocols may serve to bridge between different protocol stacks of autonomous ﬁeld networks.  10.4.2.3 Scalable Resource Management Protocols  Network resources are being stretched to their limits as more devices are added to the IoT ecosystem and the amount of trafﬁc generated increases. This is because the number of devices that need to communicate with each other will be at least an order of magnitude larger than the devices connected to the current Internet [2, 42]. Efﬁcient mechanism should be in place to manage and handle the trafﬁc explosion caused by the retrieval and exchange of information at the inter-domain communi- cation level within the IoT. Such mechanisms should be able to optimize and per- form fair allocation of network resources for the trafﬁc generated by different IoT applications. In addition, the mechanisms should be scalable in order to meet the ever-increasing trafﬁc demand. To efﬁciently allocate, manage, and optimize net- work resources at the IoT gateway, the inclusion of a control layer as a vertical or horizontal component within the protocol stack should be able to handle dynamic resource management for the trafﬁc generated by the communication processes and the signaling operations.  10.4.2.4 Signaling Trafﬁc  As illustrated in Fig. 10.3, the data exchange, storage, and retrieval processes re- quire signaling support. Since the amount of connected devices is expected to in- crease, the push pull of information data will also increase the number of requests and responses associated with the setup and tearing down of sessions. Thus, it is expected that there will be an increase in the signaling trafﬁc between devices and the IoT gateway which will worsen congestion at the IoT gateway  in addition to congestion caused by autonomous ﬁeld networks . Scalable algorithms need to be developed to manage signaling trafﬁc during communication within the IoT. Such algorithms may take advantage of information from other layers by using cross lay- ered techniques. Moreover, in order to reduce the delay experienced during the sig- naling operations within the IoT, signaling channels of cellular networks could also be used to carry the signaling trafﬁc generated by IoT devices.  10.4.2.5 Quality of Service  Apart from security, addressing identiﬁcation, billing, and location, Quality of Ser- vices  QoS  for trafﬁc within the IoT is also a major concern. Different QoS levels   10 Communication Issues in the Internet of Things  IoT   213  need to be supported for various types of trafﬁc [44]. To ensure QoS for trafﬁc, it is necessary to be able to identify, differentiate, and prioritize trafﬁc ﬂows. Trafﬁc differentiation could be done by classifying trafﬁc based on their delay and through- put requirements. For trafﬁc identiﬁcation, devices should be able to append special headers which provide information about the kind of trafﬁc being transported. In addition, the gateways must also be able to interpret the headers. Prioritization may be based on different schemes, which may use different criteria to classify trafﬁc. For example, a prioritization scheme may be based on the level of criticality of applications. Such applications may be classiﬁed as time sensitive, life-critical or normal applications. QoS is an issue because different devices enable different IoT applications and belong to different ﬁeld networks. In addition, as stated in [3], it is important to be able to distinguish between communication interactions that involve humans and those that only happen between non-human entities  e.g. devices . In an interaction that involves human, it is important to address the quality of the commu- nication in terms of QoS, quality of the data and the Quality of Experience  QoE  as judged by humans [45]. In the case of interactions between devices QoE is not normally assessed but meeting QoS requirements and having data with good quality could make a difference in the decision to be taken within an IoT application  e.g. healthcare, transport or smart grid .  10.4.2.6 New Trafﬁc Management Protocols for Buffering, Queuing,  and Scheduling of Trafﬁc at the IoT Gateway  For adequate QoS provisioning, trafﬁc management protocols are needed within the IoT gateway. These protocols need to employ relevant mechanisms for buffer- ing, queuing, and scheduling trafﬁc during inter-domain communications in order to ensure and maintain QoS and the quality of data. To improve QoS for trafﬁc within the IoT, content-based scheduling within the IoT gateway is recommended. Content-based scheduling is a technique that schedules trafﬁc based on their data content. For example, trafﬁc that contains a security related information or health related information may be prioritized in the scheduling process. In a content-based scheduling system, trafﬁc may be represented as data object. The system can com- prise an identiﬁer generator, which generates an identiﬁer for the data object on the basis of its data content and the identiﬁer gives information about the impor- tance of each data objects waiting to be scheduled. In this way, the system is able to schedule trafﬁc based on the data sensitivity and delay tolerance of the requesting application [43].  10.4.2.7 Maintaining Connectivity Within the IoT While Trafﬁc Is Generated  in Real Time  An example would be maintaining connectivity in scenarios where devices are wire- lessly connected, mobile, and permanently attached to human. Such devices may   214  O. Bello and S. Zeadally  experience intermittent connectivity to the network, which may not be favorable for the IoT application. It is also worth noting that instances where some devices within the IoT ecosystem may not be able to connect directly to their ﬁeld network’s sink or access point or the IoT gateway are likely to occur. In such situations we will have to rely on other devices that have more reliable connectivity. Therefore, communica- tion protocols, which are resilient to disruption within the network, are needed. The communication protocols may be connectivity-aware or connectivity-based proto- cols in which connectivity is taken as a function of other underlying network fac- tors such as interference, mobility, energy-level, etc. To ensure connectivity, it is therefore desirable to deploy connectivity-aware protocols based on opportunistic paradigms to allow seamless connectivity between IoT devices.  10.4.2.8 Energy-Efﬁcient Communication Protocol  Communication protocols in IoT will be required to be energy savvy and energy efﬁcient. Devices may have to maintain inter-domain communication links for a fairly long period of time and in addition may be required to relay information for other devices within the network  e.g. in some sensor networks . An energy-efﬁcient communication protocol will allow devices to be able to retain connectivity for a longer period. It is also important that communication protocols employ minimal signaling operation between devices so as to efﬁciently utilize the battery power of IoT devices.  10.4.3 Impact of Emerging Technologies on the IoT  IoT encompasses a diverse range of technologies  existing and emerging , systems and applications that constantly are being developed [4]. Although these technolo- gies and applications are heterogeneous in nature, they will be seamlessly intercon- nected and interoperable through the capabilities provided by the IoT ecosystem. As new technologies evolve, the trend will be for them to be a part of the IoT ecosys- tem. New devices will be developed with capabilities that will ensure that they can operate within the IoT. We discuss below the impact of emerging technologies on IoT deployment and adoption.  Machine-to-Machine  M2M  communication, cloud computing, IPv6, and the evolution of miniature devices are some of the emerging technologies that are really going to spur the integration of IoT into different facets of our lives. The opportuni- ties that these technologies present are motivating the adoption of IoT applications. It is well known that M2M communication is one of the major drivers and an es- sential part of the IoT concept. The term M2M refers to systems that enable devices to communicate with back-end information systems and or directly with other de- vices, in order to exchange or access real-time data [5]. These devices can be seen as the IoT end-points and therefore facilitating reliable and secure communication   10 Communication Issues in the Internet of Things  IoT   215  between them is essential for the IoT ecosystem. Most industries such as the retail, transport  road, automobile, and vehicle tracking , logistics, consumer electronics, health, home security, industrial automation  the use of Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition  SCADA   and energy  smart grid  make use of diverse devices such as sensors, actuators for some form of data collection or the other. These de- vices are less visible and even more pervasive than personal communication devices. Therefore, connecting them together using the M2M communication concept will make it possible to achieve the IoT objective, which is to enable devices to share in- formation seamlessly in order to ease operational processes and improve the quality of decisions being made. The IoT will allow the interoperability of these heteroge- neous devices.  The concept of cloud computing offers a dynamic way of accumulating and stor- ing huge volume of data. Typically, cloud computing can offer infrastructure, plat- forms or software as a service to less resource capable devices [46, 47]. The majority of the IoT devices are generally constrained in terms of resources such as memory and these devices are required to churn-out information almost every time. Cloud computing provides data storage capacity for large volumes of data produced and also eases the process of data access and data analysis for decision making anytime. In addition, the security of data can be well managed through the cloud thereby im- proving data quality. The evolution in the area of network processor architectures will increase processing power and thus leads to massive parallel processing of data through the cloud computing infrastructure at low cost.  IoT will greatly beneﬁt from the rapid deployment of IPv6 [4, 48]. The adoption of IPv6 into the IoT protocol stack is another main driver that will make it possible to connect 50 to 100 billion devices by 2020 as envisaged. It will be the basis for which every device within the IoT ecosystem will have a unique address for identiﬁcation purposes.  In the area of devices, the evolution of tags such as the RFID and the minia- turization of devices will also enable the adoption and implementation of the IoT concept. In addition, new generation devices with low-power and energy harvest- ing capabilities continue to evolve. The development of ultra low-power processors and microcontrollers’ cores will enable the design and production of such devices. These future devices will integrate different communication standards and proto- cols, operate at different frequencies and allow different architectures  centralized or distributed . This will make seamless inter-communication between devices pos- sible as global and well deﬁned standards emerge [6].  10.5 Conclusion  IoT has been receiving a lot of attention in the last couple of years. The interest in IoT continues to be strong because there are still many challenges that need to be addressed as we pointed our earlier. In this work, we focus on communication issues within the IoT. Our analysis reviewed recent protocol stack standardization efforts   216  O. Bello and S. Zeadally  for the IoT. We discuss the requirements imposed by constrained devices on the layers of the IoT protocol stack. We also present the various types of communication and communication trends we expect in the IoT ecosystem. We identiﬁed some of the forthcoming challenges at the inter-domain communication level within the IoT ecosystem.  The various analyses we present in this work are necessary to enable the de- velopment and the deployment of the IoT in a broader context. In particular, the communication challenges outlined in this work are of utmost importance. If these challenges are not addressed with innovative solutions, the IoT ecosystem will be affected by network congestion, reduced reliability of communication processes, re- duced quality of data information and low QoS for the various types of trafﬁc gener- ated and delivered. These issues will in turn affect the efﬁcacy of the IoT ecosystem in general.  References  1. Bassi, A.  2011 . IoT-A: main architectural reference model concepts. Presentation at the 1st IoT-forum, Berlin, Nov 23rd, 2011. http:  www.iot-forum.eu events launch-event  presentations wg-technology Bassi-111123_iot-forum.pdf. Accessed March 23, 2012.  2. Sundmaeker, H., Guillemin, P., Friess, P., & Woelfﬂé, S.  Eds.   2010 . Vision and challenges for realising the Internet of Things. ISBN 9789279150883. Cluster of the European Research Projects on the Internet of Things.  3. Bauer, M., Bui, N., Giacomin, P., Gruschka, N., Haller, S., Ho, E., Ke