ndards and technologies between this wide range of organization and business actors to realize a seamless and ubiquitous communication modules for smart ob- jects. Note that a common M2M architecture is not yet envisioned. However, each designed architecture shares similar key concepts and features as the aim of M2M is to allow different kinds of device as sensors to send information to the network to other devices or applications. Also, devices as actuators should receive actions from the network. Other features should exist, such as supporting huge amount of nodes  T. Bourgeau  B   University of Paris VI, Paris, France e-mail: thomas.bourgeau@lip6.fr  H. Chaouchi Telecom Sud Paris, Paris, France e-mail: hakima.chaouchi@it-sudparis.eu  P. Kirci University of Istanbul, Istanbul, Turkey e-mail: Pinar.kirci@istanbul-edu.tr  N. Chilamkurti et al.  eds. , Next-Generation Wireless Technologies, Computer Communications and Networks, DOI 10.1007 978-1-4471-5164-7_11,   Springer-Verlag London 2013  221   222  T. Bourgeau et al.  with power efﬁciency solution on devices and seamless inter-operability between different network technologies with self-organization of autonomous smart devices. The idea of M2M communication is not new as it began in the early 2000s with several industrial proposals and research papers [18, 30]. Nowadays, semiconduc- tor industry has achieved chips size miniaturization, thus making electronic devices cheaper and more efﬁcient. Furthermore, the advance in network technologies has brought a seamless communication anywhere and anytime allowing ubiquitous con- nectivity for the connected machines. It is important to mention before going further, that the M2M concept can be seen as a subset of functionalities necessary for the design of some Internet of Things applications. This means that Internet of Things has to be seen as a much broader concept than M2M communication, as it involves different other technologies such as nanotechnology, robotics, artiﬁcial intelligence, etc. It is worth mentioning that in the literature sometimes those two concepts, M2M and IoT, are presented as almost synonyms [2].  What makes M2M communication important lately, is the various market re- search forecasts [26], where it has been estimated that by the end of 2020 there will be 50 billion connected devices worldwide; thinking mainly about sensor nodes and RFID tags in addition to the classical devices as phones or computers. These pre- dictions might be seen as great opportunities to business verticals as it offers new possibilities for new stakeholders entrants, it also offers new revenue possibilities for diverse industrial actors such as operators, manufacturer, service providers, etc. Despite its impacts on user daily life and business actors, leveraging the current network infrastructure to the scale of a billion of seamless communication devices poses new challenges and important technological changes.  M2M have already started to emerge in various sectors and M2M systems ﬁnds application in many different areas such as ehealth, smart grid, security, automo- tive, telemetric, smart homes, environmental monitoring, industrial automation, to mention a few of them [15, 40]. Each of these applications imposes their own re- quirements in terms of power, bandwidth, latency, security, and mobility. For ex- ample, smart grid application would require ﬁxed meters that interacts with low power sensor devices that are tolerant to low bandwidth and high latency in case of aggregating monitoring energy consumption. Automotive application such as crash detection needs to be mobile with cellular access and are not tolerant to low latency as it is an emergency application.  As showed in [7, 15], M2M architecture might be decomposed in three main domains. The M2M device domain is dedicated to making devices communicate in the same domain through different kinds of wired or wireless network technologies. This can be done through a capillary 