uations, determining the target sensor positions are so crucial, to be able to manage the catastrophic facts or save affected peoples’ lives. During these incidents, with the help of the data collected from the sensor nodes that know their positions, this may be used for monitoring, redirecting, and conducting. Device or machine localization and positioning are among the important   11 Machine-to-Machine Communications  227  functionalities to be supported in the M2M architecture. In [31], the authors present possible localization techniques by combining RFID and sensor technologies.  The sensors in a WSN are used to sense and gain speciﬁc data about an area considering the outlying circumstances around themselves, also to convert these collected data into signals to transmit and process. The distributed sensor nodes transmit the gathered information to the sink over a multihop structure on the sensor ﬁeld. WSN is widely used in many areas like security, health, distributed computing, stock monitoring, and collecting information about temperature, motion or voice and rescue managements. In a WSN there might be thousands of sensors collecting, processing, and transmitting data. A sensor node is composed of many functional parts like sensing part, processor, transmitter, mobilizer, position ﬁnding system, and power units.  In addition to these wireless technologies, Power Line Communication technolo- gies  PLC  [4] are used to transmit communication signals, at high or low bit rate, on the electrical support of the so-called “indoor” or “in-home” environment, that is to say, in any electrical network known as “private” as opposed to electrical networks using medium or high voltage and operated by electrical power providers. The great advantage of PLC technologies lies in the simplicity of its implementation since it uses existing electrical network and makes any electrical access communicating. These technologies have grown signiﬁcantly in recent years with the success of In- ternet access offerings such as “triple-play”  Internet, phone, TV  and the provision of “Internet box” by ISPs, these boxes require “indoor” technologies to be connected in networks. The proposed theoretical speeds can raise up to 200 Mbps for Home- Plug AV standard and 14 Mbps for HomePlug 1.0 standard. As PLC technologies provides ubiquitous access to the network through the electric grid it should be a major candidate in the area of Smart Homes and Smart Grid applications.  Note that home networks to be managed by a femtocell [11, 41], a miniature cellular base-station connected to an IP-based backhaul with support of local net- work protocols, are already found within the home. Mobile devices would no longer need to support multiple physical links because they could connect to the femtocell with their cellular radio interface. The femtocell would then serve as M2M Gateway between the deployed sensors and the backhaul network.  11.3 M2M Architectures  M2M architectures need to be designed to support the new type of trafﬁc generated by massively connected devices. For instance, the sensor with all measurable param- eters  location, pressure, speed, temperature, etc.  converts the analog signal onto a digital interface. The data are being aggregated for further transmission, encrypted, and sent via wireless  WIFI, GPRS, UMTS, LTE, etc.  or wire line  LAN, etc. . It is also necessary to allow remote problem detection with terminals and the possibility to reboot update ﬁrmware remotely as well.   228  T. Bourgeau et al.  Different features should be fulﬁlled in designing M2M architecture depending on the application, thus the optimization and the subscription pricing should be adapted by the service provider depending on the type of requirement needed [26]. Some of the M2M requirements are listed here; interested readers can found more detail in [12, 32, 40]:   Latency: M2M application such as smart grid are not requiring high latency as the monitored information can be aggregated and sent later on. However, extremely low latency is mandatory for any emergency situation  ehealth, Intelligent Trans- port System  where the information has to be sent straight away after detection of emergency situation.   Bandwidth: Regarding this feature, M2M application’s data structure and amount will deﬁne the bandwidth needed. For instance in simple sensor network, min- imum bandwidth might be sufﬁcient to send few bytes of captured temperature or pressure. However, a high bandwidth will be needed if high quality captured video data are transported.   Reliability: connectivity and reliable transmission must be guaranteed regardless of operating environment  e.g., mobility, channel quality . This feature is required in emergency situations or scenarios where privacy is extremely important  e.g., healthcare, remote payment .   Access priority: Some application may need access priority for some kinds of emergency situation. For example, a security alarm signal should be sent with higher priority than the temperature information in the home. Moreover, the need to adapt the network to a varying capacity requirement in real time is another example of access priority requirement. Thus the M2M QoS requirement has to be speciﬁcally addressed, depending on the use cases and services to offer.   Power consumption: devices that have no or limited access to power sources, waking only on demand, experiencing infrequent human or system interaction, require updates to control signaling, idle, and sleep mode, link adaptation, and uplink  UL  power control.   Mobility: Many M2M use cases involve stationary or low mobility devices  e.g., payment, metering, and retail . It provides simpliﬁed or optimized mobility man- agement in order to reduce power consumption and signaling overhead. Changes to the signaling related to handover preparation and execution may be required to take advantage of low no mobility.   Scalability: A simultaneous transmission attempt to the access network’s base station from an extremely large number of M2M devices is a great challenge. It requires enhancements to the network entry re-entry and bandwidth request protocols, link adaptation,  hybrid  automatic repeat request, and changes in the frame structure. Addressing extremely large numbers of devices may require ex- tending the addressing space or updating the addressing scheme.   Security: The nature of M2M deployments makes the deployed system vulnera- ble to attacks on hardware and software ﬁrmware, compromise of credentials and conﬁguration, and network attacks  e.g., hacking and denial of service . The de- vices may be physically corrupt by changing its hardware if they are accessible and they can also be compromised by remote access when conﬁguration occurs.   11 Machine-to-Machine Communications  229  Moreover, for application such as ehealth, metering, the system should employ cryptographic and authentication features to make private data transfer more se- cure.   Trafﬁc control: M2M trafﬁc has to be controlled to enables power saving reduc- tions in the bandwidth request, and network access, by using idle sleep mode protocols. Time-tolerant trafﬁc can support signiﬁcant delays in data transmis- sion and reception. This implies that the system can give lower access priority to or defer data transmission of time-tolerant trafﬁc. Furthermore, devices can be conﬁgured to only send data to a sink node or a server; this one-way trafﬁc may require changes to the network entry and addressing protocols which would enable simpliﬁcations to the bandwidth request allocation protocol. Infrequent trafﬁc may enable sleep idle mode improvements that save power and channel resources.  The literature regarding the possible M2M architectures is divided into two ap- proaches, one is distributed without any infrastructure interaction between the con- nected machines, and one is centralized by connecting each machine to the infras- tructure either in a wired or in a wireless cellular way. Both M2M distributed and centralized approaches might use a speciﬁc M2M gateway to connect to the in- frastructure mainly via wired or wireless cellular networks as these technologies are offering large connectivity coverage. In case where M2M gateways are not used, the end-to-end M2M communication approach is desirable. It is also possible to build a hybrid architecture combining both distributed and centralized approaches depend- ing on the applications’ needs. The distributed approach is also named capillary M2M; either wired or wireless cellular capillary architecture. The gateway-based M2M architecture is hierarchical.  Capillary M2M wireless cellular network includes mostly embedded design, and short-range communication between machines. Power consumption is a major issue as we cannot generalize the harvesting mechanism. Wireless sensor network is a good example of a capillary wireless M2M network. It is including different aspects of the M2M network, such as small devices aware of power consumption optimiza- tion, networking techniques such as efﬁcient multihop routing, and efﬁcient data processing.  Non-capillary M2M networks as wired or cellular M2M on the other hand as-  sume connectivity of each machine to the infrastructure.  Note that large cells provide ubiquitous coverage to M2M devices and support high mobility; while smaller network elements such as relays and pico femto ac- cess points  APs  bring connectivity closer to the devices, improving link reliability and increasing system capacity [3]. The lower cost of smaller APs makes them an attractive method of adding capacity.  Both capillary and non-capillary M2M architectures might use M2M gate- ways [15, 41] to connect to another network such as Internet. These gateways need to support one or more of the local network protocols as well as the backhaul con- nection to the Internet. The backhaul connection may be Ethernet, cable, DSL, ﬁber, or cellular, or 