application and services are located at the edge of the core network or embedded in the Internet when offering cloud-based ser- vice [8, 28]. The application servers are dedicated to gather data of the devices and offers services to users such as data analytics. Furthermore, the service application can also contact M2M devices such as actuators to react to triggers or changed event sent by sensors.  11.4 M2M Applications  We focus our description on a subset of possible applications such as smart grid, ehealth, intelligent transport systems, vehicular, security, and remote control [12, 40].  11.4.1 Smart Grid  A smart grid [14, 28] refers to an electrical grid that integrates communications technology in the energy providers and consumer utilities in order to monitor and control the delivery and usage of distributed energy. Some keyed smart grid appli- cations are distribution network automation, smart homes or smart metering.  Electricity providers can improve the reliability, efﬁciency, and sustainability of their production and distribution in regard to the real consumption demand. For decentralized power generation such as wind power and solar panels, the smart grid offers monitoring information, billing, and accounting and brokerage services for   232  T. Bourgeau et al.  third party operators. In the context of smart homes, connected devices and sensors can monitor the overall energetic consumption as electric power, gas, and water to enable enhanced energy management.  New solutions based upon the use of wireless and cellular networks as UMTS, the use of wired networks as Power line Communications, and xDSL enable smart me- ters to transmit their metering data, receive tariff information and provide additional information to customers. The P2P-based communication model is also selected to ease data exchange and exploitation.  Smart meters are immobile devices with very long maintenance intervals  sev- eral years , which is a real challenge for maintenance issues. The current design of smart grid has a light requirement on latency as energy consumption can be aggre- gate in smart meters before being sent. However, future smart power grids might offer much shorter latency  time intervals  with the ability to control and adapt the power grid faster. The issue related to robustness, distributed architecture, and se- cure data transfer should hold in order to cover the demands on smart metering, energy management, and electric mobility. The home area network may hold many potential protocols for the communicating devices and the connection to the smart meter  M2M Gateway  could cope with several short-range wireless technologies such as WiFi, PLC Home-Plug, ZigBee, or even 3G 4G if used with femtocell tech- nology.  11.4.2 eHealth  eHealth refers to medical services offered remotely to enhance the quality of patient care while reducing healthcare cost. The sensors devices can monitor the patients’ health state as heart beat rate and blood pressure and report changes of the patient’s physical condition directly to the hospital network. Exchange of medical data be- tween patients, doctors, and medical groups lower transaction’s cost, and improves patient care. Services include telemedicine, emergency monitoring or shared care information.  This is an M2M application where reliable high-speed connectivity such as 4G cellular is required. Medical sensors have diverse resource limitations, includ- ing power, sensing, communications, and computation. The device information on blood pressure and heart beat rate, can be aggregated in the device and transmitted as bulk results for long term analysis. However, the device could react to emergency events implying stronger requirements on latency and transmission reliability. These applications necessitate having access priority and short latency as they are critical to the health of the patient. In terms of data transfer, the aggregation of monitor- ing data will not produce heavy bandwidth requirement on the network, but access priority must be addressed and security must be addressed for safety and billing reasons [22].   11 Machine-to-Machine Communications  233  11.4.3 Intelligent Transport Systems  ITS   ITS reﬂects the use of communicating devices to enhance transport efﬁciency and security. For instance trafﬁc and speed cameras can be connected to motorways ser- vices to inform users about trafﬁc jams or accidents. Traceability and logistics are also possible use cases allowing tracking assets location, to optimize ﬂeet manage- ment, to monitor critical parameters as temperature, GPS position, and movement and report transportation courses.  For this type of application, strong requirements are related to latency and mo- bility. In case of cameras’ usage, they may require simultaneous secure local wire- less local area network  WLAN  connectivity to the next camera down the road when measuring average speed for instance. Mobility issue such as fast handover and roaming agreements should be addressed as assets can move through dif- ferent countries that allow diverse cellular technologies. Moreover, security is of paramount interest as the sensors may be easily accessible. Preventing theft and leverage sensors remote access for maintenance are mandatory features for these applications [37].  11.4.4 Vehicular  Most vehicular applications use various devices and communication technologies to offer services that ﬁt into the following: diagnostics, security, safety, entertainment or navigation. Diagnostics of car failure can be captured by sensors and diagnostics information that can be relayed to mechanic staff. Automatic crash notiﬁcation can be detected by car sensors and location of the accident sent to the emergency service. Furthermore, vehicular telematics can automate motorway crossing billing when cars are identiﬁed by using for instance RFID technology [10].  Many vehicular M2M applications require a combination of short-range low- power low-throughput wireless access such as Zigbee for sensing processes and local connectivity within the vehicle, and long-range low-latency high-throughput wireless access such as 3G 4G for reporting functions and Internet access for media content services.  11.4.5 Public Safety  Public safety illustrates all possible cases of private and public surveillance appli- cations where control devices monitor a dedicated area and transmit constantly or report any trigger events to a control center. The devices can be video cameras, in- trusion sensors, or locker. The requirements on public safety applications should enforce high reliability  for intrusion detection, the device should continue to work   234  T. Bourgeau et al.  even if a burglar cut electric power , low latency  alerts may be sent as soon as trig- gering events are detected , low mobility  normally the sensor devices as camera are located in a deﬁned area  and high bandwidth  video streaming  [23].  11.4.6 Remote Control  Remote control refers to the ability to control remote actuators as industrial ma- chines, lights, heating systems using the information received from sensing devices as industrial sensors, temperature sensors, light detectors. The applications can be deployed in the industry to control industrial process or in the private area to create smart home scenarios where the home environment is fully automated. For instance, Zodianet Zibase solution offers to control different sensors at home remotely via its mobile phone [43]. The application provider has to offer secure, reliable, and easy to use solutions to facilitate user adoption.  11.5 M2M Standardization  M2M as shown earlier covers a wide range of applications, including smart me- tering, healthcare monitoring, ﬂeet management, tracking, remote security sensing, and on-demand business-charging transactions. Note that there are many types of M2M device, running various M2M applications, thus generating trafﬁc in the net- work. Current wireless networks are optimally designed for human-to-human  H2H  communications, but less so for M2M. Many challenges for Wireless M2M have to be faced. Just as in H2H networks, M2M networks need to be reliable, scalable, secure, and manageable. An important number of devices need to be supported in a M2M network more than in a H2H-based network. Consequently, optimizations are needed to avoid network congestion and system overload. Note that trafﬁc pat- terns of M2M devices are quite different from those of H2H networks. Also, M2M devices might frequently access the network, only to transmit small bursts of data. It is necessary also to adapt and optimize resource management and allocation for low-mobility or ﬁxed devices and offer advanced mechanisms for security. It is also important to minimize battery power usage for low-power M2M devices. Finally, one of the objectives is to offer M2M services and devices at a low cost level, mean- ing that M2M open new challenge in subscription management and billing. All the above mentioned requirements and challenges need to be solved but also standard- ized to ensure interoperability and ease of use of the M2M devices and applications. M2M development concerns both the device processing, the air interface and network architecture, device, and network manageability, but also the services and applications. Each of these concerns are addressed in different standardization bod- ies such as 3GPP [1] responsible for UMTS, LTE and LTE-A, IEEE [19] cover- ing the 802.16 Wireless MAN  mobileWiMAX , the 802.11.x LAN MAN wireless   11 Machine-to-Machine Communications  235  and the 802.15 WPAN standards, European Telecommunications Standards Institute  ETSI  [13], the Telecommunications Industry Association  TIA  [34], the Wi-Fi Alliance  WFA  [39], the GSM Association  GSMA  [16], the Open Mobile Al- liance  OMA  [29], and the ITU [21].  Standardizing aims at establishing a set of common software and hardware plat- forms to substantially reduce development costs and ensure device interoperability and service ﬂexibility. Horizontal developments in the M2M industry are essential for realizing the ubiquitous computing vision. For M2M to be successful, the de- velopment of new technologies that scale with the growth of M2M markets, and a broad standardization effort in system interfaces, network architecture, and imple- mentation platforms are needed.  The standardization process starts with the enhancements related to ﬁrmware and software such as medium access control modiﬁcations to adapt to the huge number of machines accessing the media. The standardization follows with more extensive modiﬁcations to the PHY and MAC, which will accommodate advanced require- ments such as those for the M2M gateway, which serves as a bridge between multi- ple protocols. M2M is dependent on many technologies across multiple industries. In such a heterogeneous context, standardization is signiﬁcantly needed to ensure interoperability and ease of deployment, and usage of M2M-based networks and applications.  As summarized in [15], 3GPP2 is a partnership project developing global speciﬁ- cations based upon the ANSI TIA EIA-41 network. Three major activities in 3GPP2 are related to the M2M work developing an M2M study report, investigating the im- pact of existing numbering schemes used as device and subscription identities for M2M devices over a code division multiple access  CDMA  network, and working on network enhancements to accommodate future M2M devices. In October 2010, the 3GPP2 Service and System Aspects Technical Speciﬁcation Group  TSG-S  completed the draft of the study report on “Machine-to-Machine  M2M  Commu- nications for 3GPP2 Networks”.  The scope of the S.R0141-0 report is to evaluate the aspects of M2M communi- cations required to ensure that the 3GPP2 infrastructure is a viable communication network alternative for M2M business segments. Note that this study of M2M com- munications is focused on exploiting the characteristics of the M2M data communi- cation services on 3GPP2 networks, and is not for speciﬁc M2M applications. The study also reports that architectural enhancements, such as various M2M communi- cation models, need to be considered for efﬁcient network operation.  Another M2M activity at the 3GPP2 Steering Committee  SC  level is to in- vestigate the impact on the current addressing and numbering schemes due to the presence of a large number of M2M devices in the cdma2000 network. The scope of this work includes investigating M2M numbering issues and coordinating with industrial M2M committees. Some of the issues that are under discussion include the “Subscription ID” in the packet-switching domain, the “Calling Number” for M2M devices, and coordination with the Alliance for Telecommunications Indus- try Solutions  ATIS  on the efﬁciency of International Mobile Equipment Identity  IMEI  assignment.   236  T. Bourgeau et al.  In the IEEE 802 LAN MAN Standards Committee as described in [7], several task groups  TGs  are addressing the impact of M2M communication on the radio access network. The IEEE 802.16p TG aims at enhancing of the mobile WiMAX base standards IEEE 802.16e and IEEE 802.16m for M2M, identifying a number of requirements for mainly MAC-related functions such as network entry, group, and device addressing, etc. Other working groups addressing M2M communications include IEEE 802.11 and IEEE 802.15.4, which is the base standard for the ZigBee standard family used in sensor networks.  Note that IEEE 802.16p was formally approved as an 802.16 task group in  November 2010 and had been expected to complete its standard by July 2012.  The unique requirements that 802.16p is intended to address low power con- sumption, a large number of devices, short-burst transmissions, and device tam- pering, detection, and reporting. The IEEE 802.16p-10 0005 “Machine-to-Machine  M2M  Communications Technical Report” has been completed [7, 27].  The ETSI Technical Committee  TC  M2M was created in January 2009, which aims to provide an end-to-end view of M2M standardization. The ETSI TC M2M standardization work mainly focuses on the service middleware underlying layer and network transmission technologies. M2M services will be implemented on top of the M2M service platform, M2M gateway, and M2M terminals. To support a wide range of M2M applications, the ETSI TC M2M is deﬁning a set of standardized service capabilities that provide functions that are shared by these different M2M applications.  In addition to these telecommunication standardization bodies, there are mainly three other major standards that have been deﬁned for facilitating the applica- tion layer multimedia discovering, searching, and sharing in home M2M net- works: UPnP [36], DLNA [32], and Intelligent Grouping and Resource Sharing  IGRS  [20]. The standard speciﬁcations aim to build a world of connected machines and enable a ﬂexible multimedia sharing environment for mainly home machine-to- machine networks.  As described in [41], UPnP is deﬁned by the UPnP Forum, which is organized by a number of vendors in the ﬁelds of electronics, computation, home automa- tion, appliances, computer, mobile services, security, and entertainment. UPnP is essentially a technology in the application layer with the support of TCP IP proto- col stacks in the lower layers. There are two logical devices in UPnP: controlled devices  CDs  and control points  CPs . When a new device is added to a network, it will ﬁrst obtain its IP address and then advertise its services to CPs via a multi- cast Simple Service Discovery Protocol  SSDP . The DLNA standard is essentially an intermediate layer based on the original network framework. In particular, the DLNA Home Networked Device Interoperability Guidelines adopt the UPnP AV architecture for media management and control between networked devices. The key of the DLNA protocol is media management. DLNA deﬁnes two classes of me- dia format: compulsory and optional. The DLNA standard deﬁnes two main classes of device: digital media servers  DMSs  and digital media players  DMPs . Finally, IGRS intends to offer seamless resource sharing and service collaboration among devices for communication terminals, core protocols, application proﬁles, and basic   11 Machine-to-Machine Communications  237  applications. One of the key features of IGRS is taking into account the security issue.  In addition, ITU-T’s new Focus Group on the M2M Service Layer  FG M2M  has just begun its work to identify the standardization demands of a common M2M service layer, focusing initially on the healthcare sector. More details on standard- ization activities are described in [12, 15].  11.6 M2M Open Issues  Every new and pervasive technology presents challenges in implementation, deploy- ment, and exploitation. M2M deployment challenges are mainly related to the areas of reliability, robustness, latency, security, privacy, authorization, heterogeneity, and cost. Data security is one of the most important considerations while designing an M2M solution as it has to be considered in every phase of the development. It is ex- pected that advanced solutions including “security-on-chip” will be developed [6]. Note that devices should be able to communicate over short distances using less power, or over long distances using bridges with power supply. Good data process- ing capability is required, with support for real time processes, and device miniatur- ization will also help in large scale deployment of M2M system.  Flexibility is another requirement, which can allow easy and unobtrusive recon- ﬁguration. Efﬁcient middleware is required which can allow for on the ﬂy reconﬁg- uration of the sensor network or remote maintenance of devices.  Communication dominates energy consumption, and energy efﬁciency can be increased by wisely adjusting transmission power  to the minimal necessary level , and carefully applying algorithmic and distributed computing techniques to design efﬁcient communication protocols  e.g., routing protocols [7, 25] . Mobile cellular systems are primarily designed for human communication. Challenges which arise from the different M2M trafﬁc types are the scaling issue and deployment charac- teristics.  The evolution of cellular systems for M2M is expected to increase in data volume and, more important, number of connections. M2M trafﬁc in conjunction with the massive number of devices raises a wide range of requirements on mobility, latency, reliability, security, and power consumption.  Unlike traditional human-to-human  H2H  services, such as voice and web streaming, M2M services often have very different requirements on a communi- cation system due to their speciﬁc features. For example, the mass of expected con- nected devices cannot hold in the current cellular deployment.  Different M2M architectures are possible; either wired or wireless cellular capil- lary or non-capillary networks using a speciﬁc gateway or following an end-to-end approach. The main objective of all these architectures is to offer reliable, secure, and seamless end-to-end M2M communication and services. One of the major chal- lenges to M2M as mentioned in the previous section is the standardization facing the heterogeneity involved in the system. Currently, there is no global consensus   238  T. Bourgeau et al.  of cross standardization among all players. As mentioned in a recent survey [26], collaboration among standardization bodies leads to a high expectation to allow seamless and ubiquitous M2M communication.  From a business point of view [26], Telco cites partnerships as the biggest chal- lenge to M2M success as the M2M value chain should span all business verticals such as electronic design, network access providers or application service providers. Developing partnerships with other ecosystem players is the biggest challenge that must be overcome in order for operators to succeed in the M2M space. Working out a viable business model is another important challenge even without mentioning that all these efforts should be supported by convincing end users of the beneﬁts of adopting M2M services and applications because someone has to pay for it. Over the next following years, we expect more and more M2M applications  New challenges for LTE-Advanced cellular networks [9] are demanding signif- icant improvements in the efﬁciency of radio resource utilization. Meanwhile, new M2M services have to have little or even no impact on existing human-to-human services in cellular networks.  The evolution of the devices design is also important, as it intends to improve the energy consumption and the processing resources. For instance, usage of future elec- tronic devices such as MEMS  Micro Electro Mechanical Systems  and nanosensors will improve performance, and reduce latency and cost [17]. Furthermore, MEMS and nanotechnology can enable sensors and actuators to be miniaturized, allowing for easy deployment. An important new class of low data rate machine-to-machine  M2M  devices is a key to this highly connected home. Finally, the recent trends in cloud computing encompass the standard vision of client-to-server application with a ﬂexible approach allowing dedicated resources on the ﬂy. As M2M services would require big data analytics and large storage requirements, the cloud comput- ing approach is well situated to offer the best of broad integrated service for the end user.  11.7 Conclusion  Based on the promising M2M market forecast, network operators  ﬁxed and mobile  have foreseen the interest of getting such technology and applications in the com- munication chain by introducing new connected devices interacting with existing ones such as mobile phones, allowing developing new services; thus generating new revenues with the new trafﬁc transported by these networks. The technical issues re- lated to integrating M2M devices in the existing network  e.g. Internet, cellular, etc.  such as the complexity of including a big number of devices generating small packets in a random way  e.g. trafﬁc routing, securing, etc.  are left to the research community and the standardization bodies. At this point only few applications can emerge such as home automation, smart grid, etc. and trigger some actions keeping the network model unchanged as the Internet, and not facing yet the scalability and heterogeneity problems of connecting a billion of different machines as expected by the M2M market.   11 Machine-to-Machine Communications  239  M2M paradigm brings new challenges in both the vertical and horizontal M2M value chain. The M2M vertical value chain consists of providing users with global M2M solutions resulting as the union of several market actors such as electronic device makers, network operators, service application builders. Its technical chal- lenges regard how these different actors will design generic solution within one service. The constraints are mainly interoperability, sustainability, and pricing of their approach. On the other hand, each M2M horizontal value chain will have to address technological issues to several M2M solutions. For the device maker, power consumption, security of assets, and self-conﬁgured devices should be enhanced. The network actors have to enhance the network solution with new techniques that would cope with the scale of M2M communication. Moreover, seamless and ubiq- uitous communication should be possible to allow M2M devices to inter-operate through different communication protocols  Zigbee, 802.11, 3G, etc. . Finally, the application business model should take into account the privacy issues when using data collected at user side and also design solutions that necessitate minimum oper- ation for the end-user. Several standardization organizations  3GPP, ETSI, IETF, etc.  are addressing most of the above mentioned challenges but no harmoniza- tion between these different standards has been planned as to offer a generic M2M framework.  References  1. 3GPP. www.3gpp.org. 2. Atzori, L., Iera, A., & Morabito, G.  2010 . The Internet of Things: a survey. Elsevier Com-  puter Networks, 54 15 , 2787–2805.  3. Bachvarova, E.  2006 . Wireless M2M system architecture for data acquisition and control. In  SENS.  event.  4. Bourgeau, T., & Carcelle, X.  2010 . Power line communication technology overview. In The  Internet of Things. New York: ISTE Willey.  5. CASAGRAS project “Interim report” September 2008, EU Framework 7 project. http:  www.  rﬁdglobal.eu userﬁles documents CASAGRAS%20Report.pdf.  6. Cha, I., Shah, Y., Schmidt, A. U., Leicher, A., & Meyerstein, M.  2009 . Trust in M2M com- munication: addressing new security threats. IEEE Vehicular Technology Magazine, 4 3 , 69– 75.  7. Chang, K., Soong, A., Tseng, M., & Xiang, Z.  2011 . Global wireless Machine-to-Machine  standardization. IEEE Internet Computing, 15 2 , 64–69.  8. Chaouchi, H.  2011 . The Internet of Things: connecting objects. New York: ISTE Wiley. 9. Chen, Y., & Wang, W.  2010 . Machine-to-Machine communication in LTE-A. In IEEE VTC. 10. Curran, I., & Pluta, S.  2008 . Overview of machine to machine and telematics. In Water  11. DLNA  2006 . DLNA Overview and Vision Whitepaper. http:  www.dlna.org. 12. Dohler, M., Watteyne, T., & Alonso-Zarate, J.  2010 . Machine-to-Machine an emerging communication paradigm Mischa. Tutorial presented at Globecom 2010. http:  www.cttc.es  resources doc 101017-m2m-tutorial-dohler-watteyne-alonso-41257.pdf.  13. ETSI. www.etsi.org. 14. Fadlullah, Z. M., Fouda, M. M., Kato, N., Takeuchi, A., Iwasaki, N., & Nozaki, Y.  2011 . To- wards intelligent Machine-to-Machine communications in Smart Grid. IEEE Communications Magazine, 49 4 , 60–65.   240  T. Bourgeau et al.  15. Galeti´c, V., Boji´c, I., Kušek, M., Ježi´c, G., Deši´c, S., & Huljeni´c, D.  2011 . Basic principles of Machine-to-Machine communication and its impact on telecommunications indu