uthorized individuals, entities or processes” [24]. AS  Access Stratum  and NAS  Non-Access Stratum  Conﬁdentiality is ensured in 3GPP  3rd Gen- eration Partnership Program  using generated keys and cryptographic mecha- nisms [15, 33], while GUTI  Globally Unique Temporary Identity  and RNTI  Radio Network Temporary Identity  are used to ensure identity conﬁdentiality. More on conﬁdentiality is discussed in Sect. 12.1.2.2.   Integrity: “The property that the message is not altered by a third party” [33]. More on integrity is discussed in Sect. 12.1.2.1.   Proof-of-origin: “The property that the received message is indeed sent by the intended sender origin” [33]. More on integrity is discussed in Sect. 12.1.2.1.   Availability: “The property of being accessible and usable upon demand by an authorized entity” [24]. Attacks against availability focus on preventing the user from acquiring a new channel  reserving all possible subcarriers, ﬂooding the shared medium, etc. , dropping reserved channels  jamming  or attracting users   246  J.B. Abdo et al.   masquerading as legitimate eNB  evolved Node B  with very good signal and drop any handover requests causing the users to lose their reserved channels . More on Availability is shown in Sect. 12.2.2.1.   Non-repudiation: “The property that the sender cannot later deny having sent a message” [33]. Non-repudiation is considered outside the scope of this chapter, because all the proposed techniques are purely cryptographic and applicable in any communication technology. More on non-repudiation is found in [24].   Identiﬁcation and authentication: “Identiﬁcation refers to an entity  user, equip- ment  claiming its identity by providing an identiﬁer  name, pseudonym, email address, IP address, domain name , or the procedure to ﬁnd the identity of a user among N users known by the systems under several features” [24]. The attacker can identify himself with a victim’s legitimate identity  masquerading attack . It is up to the destination node to make sure that the requester’s identity is con- founded with the presented. “Authenticity is the property of being able to conﬁrm the claimed identity” [24]. More on identiﬁcation and authentication is discussed in Sect. 12.1.2.3.   Trust: Trust is a vital aspect in security, where no secure connection can be es- tablished in absence of trust. Example: PKI  Public Key Infrastructures  certiﬁ- cates cannot be used securely, unless signed by a trusted CA  Certiﬁcation Au- thority . In any coverage area belonging to a commercial network, users from different operators exist. Users trust neither each other nor the serving network and vice versa [29]. Inter-operator communication falls under the “minimal trust” policy [33]. More on trust is discussed in Sect. 12.1.2.4.  Integrity is the state where the read information is confounded with the information written by the legitimate sender. Integrity can be ensured in transmitted data, stored data, established session, etc. and for each of these situations a different integrity deﬁnition can be stated.  12.1.2.1 Integrity  Data Integrity  3GPP has ensured the integrity of transmitted data using NAS  Non-Access Stra- tum  and AS  Access Stratum  integrity mechanisms [15]. After ﬁnishing the au- thentication and key agreement mechanism, UE  User Equipment  and MME  Mo- bility Management Entity  share a key “KASME” which will be used to generate AS and NAS integrity keys  KUPint and KNASint, respectively  as shown in Fig. 12.1. Since EPS was designed to be a long term evolution, 3GPP has implemented modu- lar selection mechanism to choose among available integrity protection algorithms. New integrity algorithms can be adopted with no modiﬁcation on the selection mechanism. UE and eNB select the best suiting algorithm common to both by shar- ing the EIA  EPS Integrity algorithm  code of the supported. Each EPS Integrity   12 Security in Emerging 4G Networks  247  Fig. 12.1 Key hierarchy in E-UTRAN [15]  Algori