elow are some trust issues each requesting different secu- rity measures:   Secure connection is requested between two entities that do not have valid se- curity information about each other, i.e. do not trust each other. To make this   254  J.B. Abdo et al.  connection possible, an intermediate trusted entity should be used such as CA  Certiﬁcation Authority  in PKI.   A user needs to trust the server with his private information; it must not be dis- closed to unauthorized third parties. A privacy contract is needed to bind both parties.   Two processes need to communicate securely, within the same system without exposing any information if hardware test is implemented. Trust platform should be used in hardware.  The above requirements can be divided into two major categories: trusting enti-  ties over the network and trusting entities within the same platform.   a  Network Trust  This section is dedicated to discuss trust issues between different NEs  Network Elements  across the EPS mobile network.  User’s Trust in the Operator AV  Authentication Vector : is a set of creden- tials generated at the home network, and delivered to the serving network. In EPS, AV is used to for mutual authentication between UE and serving network. More information about AV can be seen in Sect. 12.1.2.3 a .  UE-Network trust requirements are:  1. UE should trust its Home network that generated AV will be delivered only to  trusted parties.  2. UE should trust serving networks with valid AV.  The authentication and key agreement protocol shown in Sect. 12.1.2.3 a  is a mechanism to decide if the corresponding serving network is trustworthy based on the requirement shown above.  Inter-operator Trust Inter-operator trust is not a pure technical issue, since pol- itics and economics affect roaming agreements, trafﬁc routing and other collabora- tion aspects. Technical inter-operator trust issues are:   Home network should trust the serving network that none of the received AVs will be disclosed to non-authorized third parties.   Serving network should trust the home network to send correct authentication vectors [33].   Home network should trust the serving network: it must generate correct charging bills.  Since none of the operators control the applied security mechanisms in other operators, trust has to be limited to strict required functionalities, thus the inter- operator relationship falls under the ‘minimal trust’ policy.   12 Security in Emerging 4G Networks  255   b  NE Trust  Possible threats resulting from physically tampering MEs  Mobile Equipments  and other NEs are:   Eavesdropping communicated data between entities inside the same equipment. – Encrypting the communication channel can be useless if one of the encryp- tion termination points is tampered. Plain text data can be eavesdropped before being encrypted of after being decrypted.   Modifying operations or communicated data. – Fake eNB attack utilizes tampered eNB to run malicious operations instead of  the legitimate built-in operations.  Many attempts have been made to develop a trustful platform that hinders phys-  ical tampering and eavesdropping.  Trusted Mobile Platform  TMP  The Trusted Platform Module  TPM  pro- vides trusted information on system’s internal state and stores conﬁdentially cryp- tographic keys and identities [19]. TC  Trusted computing  is widely implemented in PCs and other computing devices with relatively enough resources  power and computation . Using trusted computing is important in some devices such as Fem- tocells, where its absence might result in crucial security vulnerabilities. More about security in Femtocell is in Sect. 12.2.2.1.  TPM is implemented in mobile devices to ensure the following security require-  ments:   Protect hardware, software and OS integrity in mobile platform.   Implement access control data in ME USIM, thus ensuring conﬁdentiality and integrity of the stored data.   It shall protect the conﬁdentiality and integrity of da