t QoS on different trafﬁc types over different access networks. Customer satisfaction should increase in heterogeneous network envi- ronments, and new applications can be used leading to higher revenues for service providers.  To be able to achieve these additional revenues and support the increasing data rates, operators have to re-dimension their networks and increase their investment in the deployed heterogeneous networks such as WiFi AP  Access Point , eNB, WiMax AP.  More recently, HeNB  Home eNB , speciﬁcally Femtocell, is a cost-effective solution to cope the increasing need on data rates, especially that it can be located close to users needing this service. HeNBs can be relocated with minimum effort to areas even not covered by the operator’s network. This short distance between the user and the HeNB allows the attacker to locate the victim with very high precision. User tracking in femtocells and other attacks resulting from network-based changes will be discussed in Sect. 12.2.2.  Mobile phones can access information about their geographical location from the serving network, and this information has been used by LBS  Location Based Services  to locate nearby points of interest of the mobile user. These points of interest are not limited to recommended social events such as parties or friend gath-   12 Security in Emerging 4G Networks  257  Fig. 12.5 Hardware architecture for trusted mobile platform  ering, or the nearest business or service, such as an ATM [35], a restaurant, a hotel, etc.  The LBS trend is being motivated by the widespread of smartphones [36, 37], especially in that high processing applications are also becoming locating depen- dent. Example: in some games, the user’s location is part of the game play [35]. Other critical applications have been developed, such as ﬁnding the nearest doctor in case of medical emergency [35]. LBS has really proven to be very handy and can support customers from leisure to emergency rescue, but paved the way for emerg- ing privacy-breaching attacks by exploiting vulnerabilities not tackled yet by the standard.  We can consider that emerging 4G security threats are due to either the emerging  mobile-based services or the network-based changes as described hereafter.   258  J.B. Abdo et al.  12.2.1 Emerging Mobile-Based Services  12.2.1.1 Location-Based Service [1, 4]   a  What Is a Location-Based Service?  Location-based service is a computer-level online service that utilizes the user’s current position as a critical input for the application providing this service [35]. Location coordinates can be delivered through GPS equipped mobile devices [4], or through the mobile user’s operator. If a multilateration positioning technique is used in the serving network, then the exact location of the user can be speciﬁed. If multilateration is not used, then only the distance to the serving eNB is delivered in addition to the eNB’s coordinates; in other words, the user knows that it belongs to the circumference of a circle centered at serving eNB; its radius is the user’s distance to the center. Note that:  – Location-dependent query is a user triggered request to a location-based service. – Nearest neighbor query is a location-dependent query requesting the address of  the nearest point of interest.   b  What Are the Types of Location-Based Services [1]?  Location-based services are categorized based on the frequency of exposing their location data to application servers or adversaries [1]. They might be:  – Continuous [1]: if the exposed locations are being updated continuously. – Sporadic [1]: if the exposed locations are discrete.  LBS categories are identiﬁed since each group has compatible attack counter- measures. Further differentiation between the above two categories is shown in Sect. 12.2.1.1.   c  What Are the Threats Exploiting Location-Based Services?  Before being able to request any information from location-based services, the mo- bile user has to update his location by sending the coordinates to the LBS server, which in turn replies with the requested information. Security of the location re- lated information transmitted over the air channel is considered outside the scope of this chapter due to the implemented conﬁdentiality and integrity protection at the AS  Access Stratum  layer. We will only consider last mile eavesdropping  between P-GW  PDN Gateway  and LBS server , carried out by outside attackers or the ser- vice providers themselves. Capturing insecure identities and location information allow the attacker to breach the user’s privacy by being able to know if the user is in a certain area, and where precisely he is.   12 Security in Emerging 4G Networks  259  Fig. 12.6 Anonymization using pseudonym  Fig. 12.7 Anonymization using K-anonymity  Anonymization was proposed using pseudonym identities, as a cost effective way to ensure location privacy. Identity anonymization is implemented at the mobile level, where a pseudonym is generated to replace the username in the LBS query as shown in Fig. 12.6. Pseudonym anonymization failed to ensure the required degree of anonymity [36, 37] because each user has a limited number of restricted areas which are known by the attacker and allow him to create a predetermined victim behavior. These restricted areas are places visited regularly by the victim, such as home, ofﬁce, home-ofﬁce road, etc. In other words, the anonymizing technique is vulnerable to correlation attacks. Although the username is anonymized other re- maining attributes called quasi-identiﬁers can still be mapped to individuals e.g.: age, sex, and city [4, 12]. Pseudonym anonymization will be part of a more concrete mechanism as treated in Sect. 12.2.1.1.  The scenario behind Fig. 12.6 is that user A currently found at location 01001 is interested in ﬁnding a certain service which is returned by the LBS server as located at 01110.  K-anonymity [5] is another proposed method to ensure location privacy, where a location-dependent query is considered private if the attacker is able to identify the requester with probability less than 1 K. K is a threshold required by the user [37]. This method uses an intermediate trusted server called anonymizer as shown in Fig. 12.7.  Every subscribed user has to register with a trusted anonymity server  anonym- izer  by updating its identity and location. This anonymizer maintains an updated database of user’s current location. Each triggered NN  Nearest Neighbor  query passes by the anonymizer; it replaces the user’s location by a CR  Cloaking Region    260  J.B. Abdo et al.  and forwards the request to LBS server. CR contains in addition to the real user, K − 1 users belonging to its neighborhood. The attacker knows that one within this vicinity has requested this NN query, but the probability of identifying the right user equals 1 K. The LBS server replies with a list containing the identity of each user from CR with its corresponding POI  Point of Interest . The anonymizer then ﬁlters the POI corresponding to the real user and passes it to the requester [36, 37].  K-anonymity also has drawbacks [36, 37]:  – The anonymizer is considered a single point of failure and bottleneck, thus the  probability of full outage is higher than that in pseudonym anonymization.  – Malicious users can be physically located near the victim, thus the anonymizer will add these users in its CR. Since the eavesdropper knows the malicious users, it can predict the user’s identity with probability > 1 K.  – K-anonymity is also vulnerable to correlation attacks. – K-anonymity’s security level is directly proportional with the frequency of users’ location update. It is not practical and scalable to request location updates peri- odically from all users.  – It is more proﬁtable for idle users not to update their location, since moving from LTE_IDLE to LTE_ACTIVE to send this update message will cause higher bat- tery consumption and excess signaling on core level. – Generated core trafﬁc is K − 1 times more than needed. – Only identity privacy is ensured but not location privacy. – It is difﬁcult to support continuous LBS.   d  Location-Privacy Preserving Mechanisms  LPPMs  [1]  Location-privacy preserving mechanisms are the mechanism used to distort user’s LBS queries inside a secure system before being eavesdropped by an adversary.  LPPMS can be implemented in different architectures:  – Centralized: Uses an intermediate trusted server which implements LPPM at its level, similar to what was discussed in K-anonymity or to mix zones which will be discussed in section Sect. 12.2.2.1.  – Distributed: Implements LPPM at mobile level, similar to what was discussed in  pseudonym anonymity.  – Hybrid: HiSC claimed load balancing between AS and mobile clients, by dividing cloaking services into centralized requests with AS and peer-to-peer requests with other mobile clients [8].  Many LPPMs have been proposed trying to offer a cost effective, practical, scal- able, and secure transfer of LBS queries. Some of the latest proposed mechanisms are presented in the following.  1. Anonymization and obfuscation [1, 4–7]  Anonymization is applying pseudonym anonymization on the username part of the LBS query, while obfuscation is responsible for distorting the LBS query’s second   12 Security in Emerging 4G Networks  261  part  location . Obfuscation is divided into three transformations that are imple- mented at different timings:   Location pseudonym: instead of sending an anonymized username concatenated with the location as shown in pseudonym anonymization, the user will generate n − 1 pseudonym regions in addition to its real region. Pseudonym usernames in addition to n regions are concatenated inside the LBS query to be transmitted towards the LBS server. The attacker can then identify the current location with probability of 1 n. The LBS server will reply back with a list, where each entry corresponds to one of the n sent regions.   Fake-location injection: When the user is not exposing anything, fake location- pseudonyms can be injected at random timing. This mechanism makes it harder for data mining algorithms to detect the correct identity and trajectory of users.   Hiding LBS events: Location exposing events can be hidden, thus making it harder for attackers to track the mobile user.  2. Private Information Retrieval  PIR  [37]  In PIR, the user sends an encrypted request to the LBS server which in turn returns an encrypted reply. The LBS server will not be able to identify the sender, the re- quest, nor what particular information the client has requested. It is computationally intractable for an attacker to ﬁnd the value of the request from the server’s reply; while it is easy for the user to retrieve the information he was looking for from the server’s reply. For more details on the cryptographic algorithms used, see [37]  3. Footprints [36]  Footprint mechanism is very close to K-anonymity, but this time the anonymizer contains not only the list of users and their location, but also the list of users who have been at each location during the past period P. The anonymizer receives the real request, replaces the user’s location by a CR  Cloaking Region , and forwards the request to LBS server. CR contains in addition to the real user, K − 1 users who are currently or have been within the past period p in the area where the user is sending the request form. The remaining of this mechanism is similar to K-anonymity. An attacker may be able to identify all the users who were in that area, but will not know who was there at what time.  The advantage of footprints vs. K-anonymity are:  – Active attack using malicious users has less possibility to succeed, since it is hard to estimate the location where the user will request a service, and spread the malicious users for a period p before the user’s arrival to the estimated area.  – Footprint is immune against correlation attacks [36]. – The is no need for extra signaling or frequent location update. – Identity privacy and location privacy are ensured. – It is difﬁcult to support continuous LBS. – In case of sporadic LBS, each cloaking region needs to be as small as possi-  ble [36].   262  Fig. 12.8 Offer-demand closed ring  J.B. Abdo et al.  – contain footprints from at least K different users.  In case of continuous LBS, each trajectory disclosed must be a K-anonymity trajec- tory  KAT  [36].  4. Feeling-Based Approach [36]  Feeling-based approach focuses on identifying a public region and request that her disclosed location must be at least as popular as that space. This public region should have at least K visitors, where K is considered the required level of protection.  12.2.2 Network-Based Changes  Technology platforms and user demands form a closed ring as shown in Fig. 12.8, since newer technology platforms offer better services, higher bandwidth, and the capability of hosting new applications that satisfy users’ needs. Previous experience with the technology market has shown that demand increases to meet the offered services  if prices are correctly adjusted  until it exceeds what the current technology can offer; so more investment is used to create more powerful platforms and so on. Data trafﬁc is enormously increasing in mobile networks, where it is expected to increase by 18-folds in 2016 when compared to 2011 [38]. Mobile networks have their bottleneck at the radio interface, which is a very expensive and scarce resource. Any expectation to support the multiplicative increase in data trafﬁc should have a radical solution for access technologies. 3GPP has proposed three techniques to be used by operators interested in increasing access capacity, and these techniques can be used in any combination:  – Spectrum refarming [38]: Governments allocate frequency spectrum to be used by operators under the terms of a license. Spectrum refarming is using these al- located frequencies by technologies with better efﬁciency than the one currently   12 Security in Emerging 4G Networks  263  used. This technique offers a very limited range of capacity enhancement, and has low capacity investment ratio.  – Heterogeneous networks: EPS has provided interfaces with other 3GPP and non- 3GPP wireless technologies allowing the use of heterogeneous networks. It will offer higher availability, better trafﬁc classiﬁcation  quality of service , and wider range of service for the user to choose from. Heterogeneous networks provide better services, thus resulting in higher customer satisfaction [14]. This technique offers a very broad range of capacity enhancement, but has an average capac- ity investment ratio.  – HeNB  ex: Femtocell : “A HeNB is a Customer-premises equipment that con- nects a 3GPP UE over EUTRAN wireless air interface to a mobile operator’s network using a broadband IP backhaul” [13]. HeNB can be implemented in spe- ciﬁc area where concentrated data trafﬁc is needed, without the necessity of re- planning the operator’s eNB location. This technique offers a very broad range of capacity enhancement, and has a very high capacity investment ratio.  Heterogeneous networks and HeNB are very practical techniques to cope with the continuously increasing trafﬁc demand, but each result in a set of privacy-related vulnerabilities that can easily be exploited. Resulting vulnerabilities are discussed next.  12.2.2.1 Femtocell and Hotspot  Femtocell technology is achieving excellent sales results and is doubling every year. Operators are also increasingly adopting HeNB systems in their networks [39]. Due to the expected massive presence of femtocells in the coming years, each vulnera- bility found will be considered on a short term a large-scale problem for operators. Some of the identiﬁed weaknesses are as follows.  1. User Tracking [26]  In order to ensure location privacy, 3GPP has proposed the usage of GUTI  Globally Unique Temporary ID  as a way to anonymize user identity using a pseudonym. This suggestion is still valid when used in macrocells and microcells in cellular networks, since the number of subscribers inside the studied cell is assumed to be high. The attacker’s precision in identifying the victim is 1  number of users in a cell , which is fair enough under the above assumption. Femtocells offer small coverage and low capacity cells as shown in Fig. 12.9; thus attackers are able to locate the victim accurately.  In legacy and emerging mobile technologies  including EPS , user temporary identities are pushed by the network under special circumstances. 3GPP’s procedure for reallocating GUTI  user’s temporary identiﬁer in EPS  is shown in Fig. 12.10. More on GUTI is in [16].   264  J.B. Abdo et al.  Fig. 12.9 Microcell and Femtocell eNB  Fig. 12.10 GUTI reallocation procedure  3GPP has proposed two criteria for GUTI reallocation which are:  In Fig. 12.10 the GUTI reallocation procedure is shown [15] where we can easily deduce that only the core network can trigger GUTI reallocation, if one of its criteria is met.   “Inter-Domain Location Area Update” [33], i.e. moving from one MME’s domain to another.   “In state LTE_IDLE and LTE_ACTIVE there exists a security association be- tween the UE and MME, which can be used for protecting TMSI reallocations. But in LTE_IDLE the eNB does not possess a security association with the UE. The TMSI needs to be disclosed every time the UE has to contact MME from state LTE_IDLE” [1]. To ensure user privacy, GUTI reallocation is triggered after each time the user moves from LTE-IDLE to LTE-ACTIVE state.  Inter-femtocell handover or moving to from a femtocell does not satisfy any of the two criteria, so GUTI will not change. It is much easier for an attacker to tamper a cheap femtocell in the attacker’s premises than a production level eNB at a rooftop. If the attacker was able to collect the user’s GUTI from the femtocell, it will become easier for him to track the user after moving to another cell.   12 Security in Emerging 4G Networks  265  Dynamic and context-aware location privacy protection mechanisms are suitable  solutions for this emerging threat.  Dynamic and context-aware location privacy protection mechanisms allow a user to change his identiﬁer based on context and surrounding changes. For the sake of clarity, we will divide these mechanisms into two sub-procedures and discuss each in a stand-alone manner. The sub-procedures are:   Context change detection: UE has different interfaces allowing it to detect changes in surrounding context. Possible usage of the interfaces are: ◦ The transmitted cell broadcast messages allowing the UE to detect neighbor- ing eNBs. Network planners assign more eNBs to areas with high population density and less eNBs to rural areas, thus the UE is able to correlate population density with the number of received broadcast messages [26]. If the number of neighboring eNBs changes, then the UE is moving towards a more less dense area. The user is able to detect context change through broadcast channels. ◦ Peer-to-peer communication technologies, such as WiFi and Bluetooth [27], can be used to identify the number of neighboring devices, and to plan with these devices for simultaneous ID reallocation [26].    Identiﬁer re-allocation: to prevent an attacker from tracking a user as shown in Sect. 12.2.2.1, every user detecting context change should trigger identity reallo- cation. Two modes of identity reallocation are possible: ◦ Collaborative identiﬁer reallocation: a user triggered procedure that suggests to the neighboring devices to participate in a simultaneous ID reallocation using pseudonym. Identiﬁer reallocation is triggered whenever a UE detects context change. Mix Zone is an example of collaborative identiﬁer reallocation. ◦ Single-user identity reallocation: a user triggered procedure that changes the identity of the requester, without affecting other devices. This procedure failed to ensure the requested security level [26].  2. Conﬁdentiality Attacks  Femtocells moved Radio Network Elements  eNB  from the operator’s secure premises to attacker’s private lab where all the needed equipments and resources are available. Due to its low price, even amateur attackers can now afford trying to tamper femtocells, as a start for launching privacy and conﬁdentiality breaching attacks. Production-level eNBs were sold to well-known customers  operators, uni- versities, governments, etc. , thus any launched attack caused by a tampered eNB can be traced back to the attacker. To the contrary, femtocell vendors are not able to keep an updated list of all its sold equipments, especially, so that reselling and stealing these products is possible. Femtocell’s IP interface and cheap components makes it more suited for reverse engineering [26], and launching attacks, some of which are mentioned next.   266  J.B. Abdo et al.  Physical Tampering of Femtocell [26] Access stratum conﬁdentiality protec- tion is terminated at the femtocell, thus it has the used encryption algorithms and generated keys. The attacker can breach data conﬁdentiality, if he is capable of:   tampering the femtocell and reaching the used keys   snifﬁng the data just after being decrypted from over-the-air conﬁdentiality pro- tection and before being encrypted in IPSec.  Device Impersonation [26] More severe tampering of a femtocell allows the attacker to impersonate a legitimate eNB, thus any user close enough from this fem- tocell will be handed over to this tampered access point. 3GPP allows the serving MME to request a user’s permanent identiﬁer:   during AKA  Authentication and Key Agreement Procedure    and the presented GUTI LAI couplet is not linkable to a valid IMSI.  Succeeding to do so, the attacker can breach the user’s identity privacy and  conﬁdentiality.  3. Fake Location Reporting  Each operator has a spectrum license granting it the ownership of a speciﬁc fre- quency spectrum for a speciﬁc period of time over a speciﬁc location. So it is not allowed for a femtocell to be activated outside its operator’s coverage area. If IP- only geo-localization techniques are used [26] then false location reporting can eas- ily be implemented, since IP spooﬁng needs no physical tampering of femtocell’s components.  4. Distributed Denial of Service Attacks DDoS Attacks Against Security Gateway [26]  Mobile network’s view of internet changed from being a separate network with min- imum interaction  through GGSN’s interface  into a vital transport network, neces- sary for supporting a continuously increasing demand as shown in Fig. 12.11. This change added not just internet’s malleability, coverage, and extremely superior re- sources but also a full range of attacks that mobile networks were safe from. DDoS  Distributed Denial of Service attacks  can be implemented against SeGW  Security Gateway  leading to complete outage in femtocell services. More information about DoS attacks can be found in [24].  5. DoS on the Air Channel  Attackers can hinder a legitimate user from accessing operator’s services over the air interface. These attackers use availability breaching attacks named Denial of Service. DoS attacks can be divided into four categories [30].   Jamming attacks: creating noise signals on frequencies used by the operator. Physical channel quality will deteriorate until attack ﬁnishes, then the system will return stable.   12 Security in Emerging 4G Networks  267  Fig. 12.11 Femtocell system architecture    Flooding attacks: exhaust a resource  shared channel , by sending numerous mes- sages towards a receiver.   Semantic attacks: “exploit protocol weaknesses by transmitting valid protocol messages with forged message ﬁelds” [30].   Implementation speciﬁc attacks: Other than theoretical attacks, product-related attacks are mounted on physical devices to evaluate its capabilities. More infor- mation about physical attacks can be found in [28].  6. Detection Methods [30, 31]  Flooding attack usually covers a very limited number of cells. The operator can detect ﬂooding attacks, if the trafﬁc distribution among contiguous cells varies with unexpected standard variation.  In wireless communication, it is very hard for the transmitter to detect a collision since it gets blinded by its transmitted power. Jamming attack detection requires an unexpected transmission stoppage, where the attacker can listens to its used channel. If it is also used, then collision might have occurred. This method is not perfectly secure and cannot be used as a security mechanism. A more secure collision detec- tion algorithm was proposed in [31], where the silent periods are equivalent to the hash of the delivered data. In this method, the users are able to detect a collision  jamming attack  if one occurred.  12.2.2.2 Heterogeneous Networks  Wireless heterogeneous networks are composed of different radio technologies con- nected to one core network. This core network is responsible of billing, authentica- tion, gateway, and handover in some scenarios. In this section, EPC is considered the core network connecting various technologies as seen in Fig. 12.12. In addition   268  J.B. Abdo et al.  Fig. 12.12 Heterogeneous network in loose coupling  to WiMAX, Wi-Fi, UMTS, and EPS, other wireless broadband technologies can also be integrated with EPC.  Integration can be implemented on different levels, each deﬁning the service ef- ﬁciency and speed. If the integration between different technologies is close, the provisioning of the service is more efﬁcient and the choice of the mode in order to ﬁnd the best radio access as the well as the handover procedure is faster. However, a high level of integration requires considerable effort in the deﬁnition of interfaces and mechanisms able to support the necessary exchange of data and signaling be- tween different radio access networks [25]. More on network integration can be found in [25].  Existing wireless technologies happened to be complementary and it can be seen from the below characteristics that   EPS offers acceptable bandwidth, high mobility but have high cost per bit if com- pared with WiFi.   UMTS offers low bandwidth, high mobility but very high cost per bit.   12 Security in Emerging 4G Networks  269    WiFi offers high bandwidth, low cost per bit but limited mobility.   WiMAX offers acceptable bandwidth, acceptable mobility and acceptable cost per bit.  Next generation networks can only satisfy the increasing trafﬁc demand by taking advantage of the strong points in each radio technology. In addition to optimized resource management, heterogeneous networks present new security threats one of which is the following.  Security Threats on Authentication and Key Agreement Protocol in Heterogeneous Networks  The open architecture of heterogeneous networks will create security threats during authentication and handover [23].  Security in wireless heterogeneous networks starts with authentication and key agreement protocol, where the size of the stored secret, the randomness of the used random generator, used key derivation algorithm, . . . is crucial for security preserv- ing. Even when a user is authenticated and shares a key with the serving network, the used encryption algorithm is very critical in preserving the conﬁdentiality and integrity of the transmitted data.  If a GSM user is connected to an EPS network, he will not be able to utilize the advanced security features in 4G networks. Similarly an LTE user when connected to GSM will have GSM’s security level.  These weaknesses can be exploited by forcing vertical handovers into a less se- cure technology, thus allowing the attacker to exploit vulnerable used encryption algorithms.  12.3 Conclusion  Wireless networks, by their nature, which facilitate access to the radio, are more vulnerable than wired networks and need to encrypt communications to deal with snifﬁng and continuously check the identity of the mobile nodes. The mobility fac- tor adds more challenges to security, namely monitoring and maintenance of secure trafﬁc transport of mobile nodes. This concerns both homogeneous and heteroge- neous mobility  inter-technology , the latter requires homogenization of security level of all the networks visited by the mobile.  From the terminal’s side, it is important to protect its resources  battery, disk, CPU  against their misuse and ensuring the conﬁdentiality of its data. In an ad-hoc or sensor’s network, it becomes essential to ensure its integrity as it plays a dual role of router and terminal.  The difﬁculty of designing security solutions that could address these challenges is not only to ensure robustness facing potential attacks, or to ensure that it does not   270  J.B. Abdo et al.  slow down communications, but also to optimize use of resources in terms of band- width, memory, battery, etc. More important in this open context is that the unwired network is to ensure the anonymity and privacy, while allowing traceability for le- gal reasons. Indeed, the growing need for traceability is now necessary for the ﬁght against criminal organizations and terrorists, but also to minimize the plundering of copyright. We are therefore facing a dilemma, that is, of providing a network support of free exchange of information while controlling the content of the communication to avoid harmful content. Actually, this concerns both wired and unwired networks. All these factors inﬂuence the selection and implementation of security tools that are guided by a prior risk assessment and security policy.  Finally, we are more and more thinking about trust models in the design of se- cured systems, which should offer a higher trust level than classical security mech- anisms, and it seems that future networks should implement both models: security and trust models.  References  1. Shokri, R., Theodorakopoulos, G., Le Boudec, J., & Hubaux, J.  2011 . Quantifying location privacy. In 