 Health Act  HITECH  to promote the use of EHRs among clinicians and hospitals [4]. The study was conducted to compare the service performances of physicians using EHRs in the US healthcare settings. Ten quality measures were used to measure the quality of care including:  1  data information set for patients with diabetes,  2  eye exams,  3  hemoglobin A1c test- ing,  4  low-density lipoprotein,  5  cholesterol testing and nephropathy testing,  S. Tongsiri  B   Wichian Sittiprapaporn Mahasarakham University, Maha Sarakham, Thailand  N. Chilamkurti et al.  eds. , Next-Generation Wireless Technologies, Computer Communications and Networks, DOI 10.1007 978-1-4471-5164-7_13,   Springer-Verlag London 2013  273   274  S. Tongsiri   6  breast cancer screening,  7  chlamydia screening,  8  colorectal cancer screen- ing,  9  medication for asthma and  10  children with pharyngitis testing and respi- ratory tract treatment. It was found that the settings where EHRs were implemented had signiﬁcantly higher performances on the measures than those settings with the paper-recorded system. This implied that EHRs could, to some extent, improve qual- ity of ambulatory care. Dorr et al. [6] conducted a review of the literature from 1996–2005 on the use of information systems to support the chronic illness care. The reviewed chronic illnesses mainly included diabetes, heart disease, and mental illnesses. The positive outcome related to the provision of EHRs, electronic sched- ule, computerized prompts, decision support and personal health records, however, the concerns should be directed to the implementation system regarding the costs, data privacy and security as well as the systematic workﬂow.  Health providers were required to create health records including personal data of the patient, vital signs, medications and allergies, problem lists and current di- agnosis, and smoking status to assist clinical decision making with the core quality measures as follows: blood-pressure, tobacco use and weight screening and follow- up. Health providers equipped with EHRs in their settings tend to have relatively higher quality of diabetes care [7]. Extensive analysis of cost-beneﬁt analysis of EHRs in primary care was reported [8].  Compared with the paper-based health record system, the EHR is more cost ben- eﬁcial or has a “positive ﬁnancial return” as reported by Samuel et al. [9]. Costs have been claimed to be a major barrier of the use of an electronic-based record system but the authors, on the contrary, suggested that the EHRs may not be what had been believed. Using the implementation of EHRs in a hypothetical primary ambulatory care setting in the US as a business case, it was shown that EHRs could bring cost averse and increase revenue by saving costs of paper chart retrieving and transcription, preventing accruing costs of not having proper medication utilization, supporting clinical decision, decreasing drug side effects, offering range of medica- tion rather than using only the expensive ones. The costs were shown to be reduced due to unnecessary laboratory charges and radiology tests. Increasing of revenue could be the case by correctly capturing medical procedures. Sensitivity analysis was also applied trying to alter multiple factors and looking at whether the costs and beneﬁts were changed and how much. In the 5-year time horizon, compared with the paper-based system, the electronic system yielded the net beneﬁt of $86,400 per provider in primary ambulatory care services. The largest proportion of this beneﬁt was attributed to saving in drug expenditure. The number of patients in the health- care security insurance plan was the most sensitive factor to the variation of the beneﬁts ranging from $8,400 to $140,100. The greatest large cost saving of approx- imately $202,200 was possible for a high proportion of registered patients in the capitation area coupled with avoiding expensive drug choices. The beneﬁts tended to be increased with the longer time horizon. The authors also suggested other ar- eas of cost savings not included in the study as follows: malpractice premium costs, storage and supply costs, generic drug substitutions, increased provider productivity, decreased staffs number, increase reimbursement, and decreased claims denials.  EHRs has a potential to improve quality of care in patients suffering from di- abetes. As reported by Randall et al. [7], the authors attempted to contribute with   13 Electronic Health Records: Beneﬁts and Contribution to Healthcare System  275  the scarce evidence of the adoption of EHRs in primary care providers by using the implementation of EHRs in the quality standards for the care of patients with diabetes in seven primary health care practice organizations between 2007–2010. Several laboratory tests to indicate quality of care for diabetes patients as well as the patient factors that would have, to some extent, inﬂuences on diabetic treatment including demographic data; insurance type; race; household income and educa- tion attainment level were taken into account. The composite components of care used as the output of the systems comprised measurement of glycated hemoglobin, kidney management, eye examination, and pneumococcal vaccination. Indicators of outcome composite are glycated hemoglobin, blood pressure, cholesterol level, and body mass index  BMI . Statistical analysis showed that, by comparing with the paper-based system, the settings with the EHRs practice have signiﬁcantly higher level of achievement for care and outcome across several insurance systems.  13.2 Challenges in the Changes to EHRs  The transition process from manual to electronic health records is very much of a challenge. We have a report from Ophthalmology Times: EHR: From paper to elec- tronic [10]. To successfully transform health records from paper to electronics, the following requirements should be considered: complexities, resistances from staffs, changes of human resources, software, hardware and how things are processed, in- formation technology  IT  plan and having the program tested and practiced before fully transforming the system from paper to electronic. Juan et al. [11] conducted a case study to assess the implementation of EHRs in a public health system in Mex- ico. Challenges to success in the EHRs implementation were as follows: resistance of healthcare providers, inappropriate attention on resources needed for the system maintenance, and political pressure from the government health development pro- grams. It is suggested that more commitment is essential for the sustainability of the EHRs implementation.  Fragmented data are collected by individual organizations responsible for reha- bilitation for PWDs. The data rarely are shared among stakeholders. EHRs accessi- ble for EHRs may enhance the multidisciplinary works.  13.3 Example of the Use of EHRs in the Rehabilitation Provision  for Persons with Disabilities  PWDs   The Persons with Disabilities’ Quality of Life Promotion Act  2007  stated that all registered PWDs are entitled for receiving extensive medical rehabilitation pro- grams including medicine, physical therapy programs, occupational therapy pro- grams and prostheses & orthoses [12]. Education and vocational rehabilitation pro- grams are also part of rehabilitation. The government provides compensation and   276  Fig. 13.1 Diagram of ICF concept  S. Tongsiri  beneﬁts for disabilities. To achieve these goals of rehabilitation, health data and in- formation systems are immensely important. Attention should be given to the ques- tion of how could this could happen amidst the lack of timely accessible database. The International Classiﬁcation of Functioning, Disability and Heath  ICF  may be used to assist the measurement of functions after home modiﬁcations. In 2001, the ICF was developed by the World Health Organization  WHO  [13]. The member countries have continuously been encouraged to use ICF to collect functioning data of persons with disabilities  PWDs  indicating interactions between body functions and body structures  b codes , activity and participation  d codes , environment fac- tors  e codes  and personal factors. Product and technology, natural environment, and human-made changes to environment are included in the ICF environmental factors. As can be seen from Fig. 13.1, the ICF conceptual framework encompasses interactions among multiple factors and could be used to explain multidimensional areas of health. ICF have been used in a number of research activities in medical contexts, community survey, and disability statistics [14]. The comprehensive data of quality of life of PWDs can be demonstrated using the ICF concept and codes. In 2012, Sirinart and Wachara conducted the survey using ICF to measure functions of PWDs living in a community [15]. Forty-six codes were utilized to represent func- tions of PWDs ranging from body functions and structure, activity and participation, and environment factors.  ICF can be used as part of patients’ outcome measures. An example of applying ICF to a patient could be as follows. An ICF code assigned to a man suffering from stroke and conﬁned to bed would be d450.4 where d450 represents walking function and qualiﬁer  .4  represents the absolute problem of walking function  unable to walk at all . After six months of extensive physical therapy with some recovery of the affected body part, the patient is able to walk independently with a single cane. The ICF code for his walking ability is now d450.2 where qualiﬁer  .2  represents a moderate problem of walking because he still has to walk with an assistive device, however, his improvement of walking function can be addressed by the change of qualiﬁer from  .4  to  .2 .  The comprehensive data of quality of life of PWDs can be demonstrated using the ICF concept and codes. In 2012, Sirinart and Wachara conducted the survey using ICF to measure functions of PWDs living 