 Staffs must also be trained to increase their competency dealing with the systems. Hardware implementation and maintenance as well as the software update would be costly and if not well prepared, problems occur. EHRs could also be beneﬁts for the provision of rehabilitation for PWDs in that functioning data could be processed to enhance the accessibility of systematic and timely database.  13.5 Next Step  Further research should see that it is promising for EHRs to be used to record func- tioning of patients and PWDs and determine disability beneﬁts and compensations. To achieve the goals of rehabilitation, data should be used to assist broader areas of rehabilitation and assist the extensive coordination of services across different providers. Meaningful use should be discussed among users. Use of the records is not only in health but also in education, employment and social beneﬁts, which are truly following the WHO’s “health”.  More research should be conducted for the evidence of quality of care improve- ment in rehabilitation for PWDs by EHRs using meaningful measures comparing settings with paper records and those with EHRs. Cost saving and ﬁnancial returns should also be taken into consideration.  References  1. Safran, C., Bloomrosen, M., Hammond, W., Labkoff, S., Markel-Fox, S., Tang, P. C., et al.  2007 . Toward a national framework for the secondary use of health data: an American med- ical informatics association white paper. Journal of the American Medical Informatics Asso- ciation, 14 1 , 1–9.  2. Beni, J. B.  2011 . Technology and the healthcare system: implications for patient adherence.  International Journal of Electronic Healthcare, 6 2–4 , 117–137.  3. Gang, A. X., Adhikari, N. K. J., & McDonald, H., et al.  2005 . Effects of computerized clin- ical decision support systems on practitioner performance and patient outcomes: a systematic review. JAMA, the Journal of the American Medical Association, 293 10 , 1223–1238.  4. Blumenthal, D., & Tavenn